<html><head><title>Crosslines - Mexico</title><!!keys: Crosslines+Mexico+presidential elections></head><body><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by</i> <a href="crosslines.html">Crosslines</a><hr><h2>NGOs achieve credibility in Mexico</h2><p><i>The 21 August Presidential elections in Mexico received a lot of attention because of the challenge to the long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party. Less attention was given to the fundamental shift in the nature of Mexico's political system produced by an alliance of NGOs. Report by <b>David C. Scott, </b>former Mexico correspondent for the Christian Science Monitor. </i><hr>The 1994 elections in Mexico will probably be viewed as a milestone in the development of NGOs south of the border. Under the coordination of Civic Alliance, Mexican non-governmental organizations banded together on a scale never seen before. Some 400 human rights and social groups marshalled 20,000 volunteers to scrutinize the votes and carry out a series of crucial checks on the election process. Their efforts stimulated a civic ground swell that brought out another 60,000 observers belonging to labour unions, business organizations and youth groups. <p>In contrast to the elections in South Africa, Cambodia and El Salvador (to name some random examples), the United Nations provided only technical assistance in Mexico. Reluctance on both sides of the fence kept the UN role marginal. Instead, Civic Alliance took the lead.<p>In the months leading up to the elections, the Alliance worked with human rights groups from several states to monitor media coverage of the campaigns to detect bias. Regular reports spotlighted the huge bias toward the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (RPI) in the media and had a mitigating effect. <p>On election night, a "quick count" was made by Alliance members reporting in from around the nation, producing an early gauge by which to judge official results. In 1988, the computers tallying the officials results mysteriously "crashed" when early returns showed the opposition party in the lead and final results took weeks to appear.<p>"In 1988 we had no information. This time we had the data, putting pressure on the government institutions to perform," says Sergio Aguayo, director of Civic Alliance and the Mexican Academy for Human Rights. "Society generating its own data is part of the process of democratization of information." The elections gave many of these small, isolated groups their first taste of technology - fax machines, computers, modems - now familiar to urban organizations. The technology was used not only to send in voter tallies but rapidly transmit reports of fraud, intimidation and other irregularities in the election on a timely basis.<p>But Aguayo sees another, more significant benefit for those who participated in the alliance. "We're seeing a profound effect on their self-esteem. They've proven to themselves that they can coordinate and do difficult tasks which have significant political implications."<p>The Civic Alliance model grew out of a voter education and poll-watching effort in the 1991 Governor's election in San Luis Potosi. Aguayo's Mexican Academy of Human Rights brought his technical and political savvy to a partnership with a local NGO, the San Luis Potosi Civic Front. For the first time in Mexico, an organization unaffiliated with any political party provided proof of fraud during the elections. The evidence was a catalyst for huge protest marches.<p>With an authoritarian government, the drive for political rights and human rights goes hand in hand, says Mariclaire Acosta, director of the Mexican Commission for the Defence and Promotion of Human Rights, which participated in the Alliance. "We won't have respect for human rights until we have accountability. And the only way to get accountability is if the political process works." <p>Polls by Este Pa!s magazine editor Federico Reyes Heroles show that 67 percent of the Mexican population doesn't have faith in the judicial system. Only 20 percent believe in their government institutions. But NGOs, increasingly effective and visible in recent years, garner an 80% credibility rating. <p>The government's abysmal credibility is a "very dangerous situation," says Acosta. "To restore credibility to government institutions you have to build from below. That's what we're doing."<p>The Alliance is a democratizing process for the NGOs, too. As in many developing countries, Mexican NGOs often have more contact with foreign counterparts than their domestic colleagues. <p>Through the Alliance, observes Acosta, "we're learning now how to discuss and tolerate our differences, to achieve a shared goal. That's part of the democratic process. The networking also gives us a better capacity to mobilize when we need to in the future." <p>For example, on 23 September the Alliance is pooling the efforts of several groups in Mexico City to hold an unofficial plebiscite on the installation of parking meters in a neighbourhood which claims officials are ignoring their objections to the plan. The Mexican elections attracted nearly 1,000 registered foreign observers. Many coordinated their efforts with the Alliance. Their presence is likely to have a pay-off in terms of increased attention and funding, too.<p>For example, a Canadian group witnessed the persecution and arrest of a Jesuit priest for trying to get the vote out. Members of a North American lawyers' group saw the police teargas a group of campesinos protesting election fraud. "They helped the campesinos escape. This creates solidarity. Injustice now has a name and a face for these visitors," says Acosta.<p>"The elections have been a catalyst for Mexico's citizen movement, which seems to be gaining momentum month by month," says Katherine Kilbourn of Grassroots International, a Washington DC-based NGO which funds coffee farmers in Oaxaca. "The movement has been pushed along by the economic and political situation which in turn is pulling the economic and political system forward. It's exciting." <p>In Mexican literature and history, the Spanish word aguantar is continually used to define the Mexican character. It means "bear up", "endure", or "submit". While in the rest of Latin America poverty has produced revolt and civil war, Mexico's downtrodden have submitted.<p>How does that jibe with Mexico's awakening civic movement? <p>"Mexicans submit not because they are passive but because they are wise," says Acosta. "Until now they've never had a viable democratic alternative. But given an alternative, they will move." <p><hr><h3>MEXICAN CONTACTS</h3><p>Academia Mexicana de Derechos Humanos,<br>Filosofia y Letras 88,<br>Coplico Universidad,<br>Mexico, D.F. 04380.<br>Tel:52(5)-659-87-84, 659-49-80.<br>Fax:52(5)-658-72-79.<p>Acuerdo Nacional para la Democracia (ACUDE),<br>Manuel M. Ponce 322 piso 1,<br>San Jose Insurgentes,<br>Mexico 01020, D.F.<br>Tel: 52(5)-662-3- 6-90, 662-29-85.<br>Fax: 52(5)- 520-87-82.<p>Consejo para la Democracia, A.C.,<br>5 de Febrero 42, Coyoacan,<br>Mexico 04000, D.F.<br>Tel/fax: 52(5)- 554-11-99, 554-83-01<p>Convergencia de Organismos civicos en la Lucha por la Democracia,<br>Prosperidad 31, Colonia Escandon,<br>Mexico 11800, D.F.<br>Tel: 52(5)-516-74-56, 515-16-79.<br>Fax: 52(5)-277-48-51. <p>Instituto Superior de Cultura Democratica,<br>Goya 87, Insurgentes Mixcoao,<br>Mexico 03920, D.F. <br>Tel: 52(5)-611-26-69, 611-23-81.<br>Fax: 52(5)-563-60-02.<p>Movimiento Ciudadano por la Democracia,<br>Prosperidad 31, Colonia Escandon,<br>Mexico 11800, D.F. <br>Tel: 52(5)-518-74-56. <br>Fax: 52(5)-277-48-51.<hr>For more information see: <a href="xlines_rwanda.html"> Special Report: Rwanda.</a><p>This article was first published in the October special Rwanda issue of <b>CROSSLINES Global Report,</b> an independent newsletter of reporting on humanitarian, development and environmental issues.<br>©Copyright CROSSLINES Global Report 1994<p><a href="medianatura_top.html"><img src="crosslines_pix/media_natura_logo2.gif"> Crosslines UK Representative: Media Natura</a><hr><a href="index.html"><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo2.gif"> Crosslines Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
