<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>The Child Survival, Protection and
Development Programme(CSPD)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<a href="nnud_contents.html"></a>
<BR>
<br><HR><BR>
<H1><CENTER>The Child Survival, Protection and <BR>
Development Programme(CSPD) </CENTER>
</H1>
<BR>
UNICEF's cooperation with the government of Tanzania started in 1954 with
a shipment of milk powder. 40 years later UNICEF and the government of Tanzania
are partners in a comprehensive, multi-million dollar effort to improve
the lives of women and children.<BR>
<BR>
Tanzania is renowned for the culture of self-reliance which was initiated
by its first president, Nyerere, who was in office for 24 years. The population
of Tanzania is still predominantly based in rural areas, and still largely
reliant on subsistence farming for day to day survival.  <BR>
<BR>
From 1970 President Nyerere established  a programme of villagisation, which
encouraged subsistence farmers in remote parts of the country to resettle
in population clusters where they could be more easily reached with social
services. Although unpopular at the time it  certainly helped the development
of Tanzania's extensive social services programme. <BR>
<BR>
Following villagisation, in the late 1970s UNICEF's new Basic Services Strategy
supported efforts to: provide improved water schemes to more than half the
country's villages; construct thousands of primary schools and health centres,
and train teachers and healthworkers. Sadly, life for many Tanzanians is
probably worse now than it was 20 years ago. As in so many countries, repayment
of the national debt and introduction of economic austerity measures is
restricting funds available for health and education, which has meant that
these services are inadequate and deteriorating.<BR>
<BR>
Nyerere retired in 1985 and was followed by President Mwinyi (facing elections
in October '95) but much of the administrative structure remains the same.<BR>
Tanzania has a pyramid administrative structure (see diagram below). A similar
structure has been developed in Zanzibar. This facilitates delivery of the
CSPD programme. <BR>
The CSPD programme began in the mid-1980s. It is now active in 12 out of
the 20 mainland Regions as well as Zanzibar, reaching almost half the population.
The programmes in two of  Mwanza Region's six districts, and Zanzibar, where
we visited, are completely supported by UNICEF, largely through donations
from the UK Committee. UNICEF supports the CSPD programme in 50 of the 104
Districts. Other donors to UNICEF include the government ministries of:
Sweden (SIDA), Norway (Norad) and the Netherlands.<BR>
<BR>
A major part of the CSPD programme is the establishment of systems for planning,
delivering and monitoring services at community level. Each village selects
two village health workers - a man and a woman. Every village has a village
government structure of elected members, supported by a government representative
who will live in the village but not originate from the village. This person
feeds village decisions into Ward level meetings. The selected health workers
are crucial to the success of the CSPD programme. They need to be stable
members of the village, reliable and trustworthy with a primary level education.
They receive two months training. One of them may already be a traditional
birth attendant.<BR>
<BR>
The village government sets up four committees: health, water and sanitation,
finance and village safety and security, which are overseen by the village
leaders. (See the data for Kashishi Village, page 14, for example of the
decisions made by village government.)<BR>
<BR>
The two health workers keep registers of all families/householders, children
and their health records. Education extension staff from the Ward level
oversee pre-school and primary education. Every village has at least one
primary school and a school committee of parents and teachers. Secondary
schools are at District level and children often have to board.<BR>
<H3>CSPD in Mwanza Region</H3>
<BR>
Mwanza Region - population<BR>
<BR>
Region 	- population 	1.7 million<BR>
District 	- population 	2-300,000<BR>
Division 	- population 	50-70,000<BR>
Ward 	- population 	10-15,000<BR>
Village 	- population 	2-3,000<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The CSPD programmes in Geita and Sengerema, two Districts with high population
density, started in June 1992.<BR>
<BR>
First the programme was discussed with Regional authorities, who are government
officials, and District Councils, who were enthusiastic about the prospect
of this integrated approach to community development. The first year was
spent mobilising local leaders and communities so that they would understand
their responsibilities within the programme, and that of the supporting
agencies like UNICEF and non-governmental organisations working in the Region.<BR>
<BR>
With acceptance of the programme came 'capacity building', i.e. training,
research, putting equipment and supplies in place. UNICEF provided the following
to Geita District which has 76 villages:
<BLOCKQUOTE>155 bicycles - for village health workers<BR>
12 motorcycles - for 13 Ward offices<BR>
2 motor vehicles (Toyota Landcruiser and Hilux) - at Regional and District
level<BR>
56 weighing scales (hanging)<BR>
62 weighing scales (standing)<BR>
78 file folders<BR>
196 registers for recording information<BR>
20, 679 growth monitoring cards<BR>
41 birth attendant kits<BR>
147 Village health workers kits <BR>
147 drug kits </BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
Every village has a village health day once a month when mothers come to
the health centre with their young children for weighing and vaccination
in a systematic growth monitoring programme. UNICEF provides regular supplies
of vaccine which are kept cold in UNICEF supplied kerosene fuelled refrigerators
- the government supplies the kerosene. The vaccination programme is a national
programme and takes place throughout the country.<BR>
<H3>The Child Survival, Protection and Development Programme is divided
into six main areas:</H3>
<BR>
<B>Community mobilisation</B>, participation and management involves raising
awareness of health, nutrition, education and community development issues
in the village. It helps communities to assess the situation, analyse the
causes of the problems and take action for solutions - a process known as
the Triple A approach  to problem solving.  Communities gather information
on their social problems such as child malnutrition and manage their initiatives.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Adequacy of food intake</B> is a concept used to describe efforts to
ensure that women and children get enough of the right kind of food, which
entails improving feeding practices and the availability of food.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Child development and education</B> aims to improve the quality of early
child care and basic education through greater community involvement in
the management of day-care centres and primary education. It supports training
for teachers, childcare centre attendants and members of village and school
committees.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Health, water and sanitation</B> rest on the principle that clean water
and good health are inseparable. The CSPD programme provides support for
communities to improve and manage health and water and sanitation systems
themselves.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Income-generating activities</B> are designed to alleviate poverty, one
of the most basic causes of malnutrition. Assistance is provided, especially
to women, to increase their income and their control over it. Income-generating
schemes provide credit, training and technical assistance.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Children's and women's rights and protection</B> are promoted through
advocacy using the Convention on the Rights of the Child and the Convention
on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women. The main
focus is on children at risk, the special needs of girl children, street
children, AIDS orphans and women's rights.  <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<center><TABLE BORDER=4 cellpadding=6>
<TR>
<TD><B>Where the money goes</B><BR>
<BR>
UNICEF assistance to the places where the photos were taken:<BR>
<BR>
<a href="unicef_pix/nnud_3.jpg">Pics.3</a> &amp; 4, Kuleana Children's Rights Centre. UNICEF paid for the initial
seven-month study into street children in Mwanza and provided a vehicle
for reaching the children.<BR>
 <BR>
<a href="unicef_pix/nnud_6.jpg">Pic.6</a> Zanzibar's programme of Community Based Rehabilitation of the blind
and disabled is supported by UNICEF and funds from NNUD will go to this
programme.<BR>
<BR>
Pic.7 The Akinamama Mshimama Co-operative is one of 30 women's income-generating
co-operatives on Zanzibar and 75 on the mainland who receive interest-free
loans from UNICEF.</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE></center><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
