<html><head><title>Crosslines: The Center for Preventative Action</title><!!keys: Crosslines+Chechnya+war+violence+migration+Russia></head><body><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="crosslines.html"> CROSSLINES</i></a><hr><h2>The Center for Preventive Action</h2>The Center for Preventive Action (CPA) is a new Council on Foreign Relations initiative to study and test conflict prevention. Many of today's serious international problems -- ethnic conflicts, failing states, and the resultant humanitarian disasters -- could potentially be averted or ameliorated with effective early attention. <p>Yet, despite the considerable attention given to conflict prevention, there has still been little clinical scrutiny of the concept or practise. The CPA is an effort to fill those voids of understanding and action.  <p>The CPA has four main functions:<p><ol><li>To convene an annual conference -- the first was held in New York on 16 December 1994 -- to assess the state of the art. The conference brings together practioners from governments, international organizations, and NGOs with scholars, representatives of foundations, Congress and journalists to assess what they have learned in the previous year.<p><li>To serve as a coordinating centre, letting everyone involved in conflict prevention know what everyone else is doing.<p><li>To serve as a repository for relevant books, articles, and other documents. Such a centralized research centre does not currently exist.<p><li>To test systematically the viability of conflict prevention by sending investigative teams to pre-explosion crisis areas to map out how to settle or manage conflicts and then to advocate action by appropriate governments and organizations, national and international, private and public.</ol><p>For further information contact: Barnett R. Rubin, Director. Center for Preventive Action, Council on Foreign Relations, 58 East 68th Street, New York, NY 10021, USA. Tel: 1(212)-734-0400. Fax: 1(212)-861-1916. <p><hr>©Copyright:<b> CROSSLINES</b> Global Report 1995. Uploaded with permission.<hr><a href="index.html"><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo2.gif">  CROSSLINES Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
