<body>
<title> HOW TO PHASE OUT CHILD LABOUR IN FOOTBALL PRODUCTION
     WITHOUT DRIVING CHILDREN INTO POVERTY</title> 
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<br clear=right>
<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../scf_info.html"> Save the Children Fund</i></a>
<hr>
<p>

<br>


<h2 align=center> HOW TO PHASE OUT CHILD LABOUR IN FOOTBALL PRODUCTION
     WITHOUT DRIVING CHILDREN INTO POVERTY</h2>

<h4>13 February 1997</h4>



     
      
     
     On Friday 14 February, Save the Children (UK) will lend its support to 
     sporting
     goods companies and other children's rights groups who are working 
     towards
     phasing out child labour from the production of soccer balls in 
     Pakistan. Vital to the
     plan are steps to ensure that the situation is not made worse for 
     children. Details
     of the initiative will be announced at a press conference in Atlanta 
     USA (12.00
     noon, or 5pm UK time - for details, see below).<p> 
     
     Pakistan is the source of approximately 75% of the world's annual 
     sales of hand-
     stiched soccer balls, an industry estimated to involve 7,000 children 
     under the age
     of 14. Save the Children believes that an immediate boycott of the 
     industry could
     have a very negative effect by reducing vital family income and 
     pushing children
     into potentially more hazardous and exploitative forms of work. 
     However, this
     proposed action programme is much more realistic in that it allows for 
     the gradual
     phasing out of child workers over a period of 18 months while 
     providing them with
     practical support. It will be particularly important for families to 
     find alternative
     sources of income. Crucially the initiative has the backing of sports 
     manufacturers
     themselves.<p>
     
     David Husselbee, Save the Children's Field Director in Pakistan, who 
     will be
     speaking at the press conference on Friday said:<p>
     <blockquote>
          "Save the Children has been working with Pakistani soccer ball
          manufacturers for several months to ensure that their commitment 
     to end
          child labour in their industry is complemented by other efforts 
     to ensure that
     
          children removed from work do not end up in more damaging 
     physical or
          economic circumstances. This partnership offers the promise of 
     substantial
          additional resources from the ILO and UNICEF to assist at-risk 
     children and
          their families."<p>                             
     </blockquote>
     
     More than 50 sporting goods brands including Adidas, Mitre, Nike, 
     Puma, and
     Reebok have pledged to purchase balls produced in Pakistan only from 
     local
     manufacturers that participate in the monitoring programme. <p>
     
     Save the Children joins the World Federation of the Sporting Goods 
     Industry
     (WFSGI), the Soccer Industry of America, the International Labour 
     Organisation,
     and UNICEF (among others) in putting together a plan for action. This 
     will include
     a social protection programme to provide educational and other 
     opportunities to
     children removed from the industry, as well as a system for 
     independent
     monitoring to ensure that child labour is phased out by participating 
     manufacturers
     within 18 months.<p>
     
     Says David Husselbee:<p>
     <blockquote>
          "With all the best intentions, phasing out child labour in this 
     industry will not
          work unless an independent removal and monitoring system is put 
     in place.
          This has to take account of the best interests of affected 
     children, and it has
          to be phased in over a period of time so that there is time to 
     develop
          effective social programmes and alternative sources of income for 
     the
          families affected. Save the Children intends to work with the 
     industry and
          other partners to make sure that this is achieved."<p>
     
    </blockquote>
<hr width=80%>

<h4>NOTES FOR EDITORS:</h4>
     1. The press conference will be held at 12 noon US time at the 
     Auditorium of the
     Georgia World Conference Centre, Atlanta.<p>
     
     2. David Husselbee and London-based representatives from Save the 
     Children (UK)
     are available for interview.<p>
     
    <h4>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION:</h4>
    
     Save the Children press office          0171 703 5400<br>
     Out of office hours           0831 650 409<p>
     
           <table border=6>
<tr><td><b><a href="../index.html">Save the Children Home Page</a></b></td></table>
