<head>
<title>UNICEF Rwanda Emergency Programme</title>
<!!keys: UNICEF+Rwanda+children>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000">


<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="unicef_info.html"> UNICEF </i></a>
<hr>
<h2>UNICEF Rwanda Emergency Programme</h2>
<h3>Briefing Notes on Rwanda</h3>
<h4>1. Update on situation in SW Rwanda (Kibeho)</h4>
<ul><li>Before the forced clearing of the camps, there were approximately 240,000 Internally Displaced Persons (IDP) in the SW in 13 camps.
<li>Largest camps were Kibeho and Ndago - together about 200,000.
<li>Agencies recognise need and right of Government to reduce security risks in these camps, training was going on, arms were available, intimidation of IDP's were going on, incursions from Zaire for sabotage are common.<p>

<li>However, the rapid clearance of the camps caused numerous deaths of innocent civilians, including many women and children.  UNICEF deplores the killing, in particular the killing of women and children, but these figures are disputed by Government as too high and by some NGO's as too low.  The president of Rwanda and the UN Secretary General have called for a Commission to be formed to investigate the events leading  up to the clearance of the camp and the killings that took place.  The Commission should start its work this week.<p>

<li>More than 1,500 Unaccompanied Children (UAC) have been moved by UNICEF and others from Kibeho to Butare, Gitarama and other locations with UAC centres.  Most are in centres with NGO's providing shelter, water and care.  By 22 April all UAC were evacuated from Kibeho, following agreement with Government.  UNICEF has provided UNIMIX, Water bladders, tents, milk, emergency health kits (each enough for 10,000 people for 3 months), HP biscuits, medical supplies and equipment.
<li>We have our office in Butare, which is catering to the most immediate needs.  This team has been strengthened by additional health, water and social assistant staff to provide support to the emergency relief operations.<p>

<li>Current situation:  Only very few left in Kibeho and other camps (approximately 1,000 in Kibeho).  Most others have fled first to Butare and Gitarama, and subsequently to their home communes (walking or transported by UN).  The remaining population includes a very large number of women and children and UNICEF has been involved with The International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), UNAMIR, WHO and others to negotiate the delivery of food and water to these people.  The majority of the people inside have thus far refused to leave the compound, despite atrocious sanitary conditions.  An outbreak of Cholera may be possible if conditions are not improved immediately.<p>

<li>UNICEF continues to monitor the situation and provide assistance to those in need of emergency relief.  We will also continue to support the provision of support to communes of return, water, health facilities, education, relief supplies, technical assistance.</ul>


<a name="basic"></a><h3>2. Basic Information</h3>
The UNICEF Rwanda Emergency Operations began in May 1994 (in Ngara Tanzania and cross-border relief from Uganda into Rwanda).  UNICEF had an early presence in Rwanda for relief assistance - 2 people were in Kigali continuously from May-July 1994.  A full office was set-up in August 1994.  The office covers operations inside Rwanda, in Goma, Bukavu, and provides financial and technical assistance to the Tanzania-based programme in Ngara.  The current operation thus covers (unusually) areas in 3 countries, given distances, relative ease of access, and common populations.  A gradual re-phasing of activities to the host country offices is planned in 1995-96.  This will depend somewhat on the decision of refugees to return home - thus the long-term nature of the refugee population.<p>

The pre-war budget of UNICEF Rwanda was approximately $3.0 - $4.0 million per year.  However, given the 
very large assistance requirements in the country and the support required to the refugee population, the actual expenditure for July-December 1994 surpassed $40.0 million.  The planned budget for 1995 is $66 million of which $55 million is for inside Rwanda and $11 million for the adjacent refugee areas.<p>


Current estimates of affected population is indicated below:<p>
<hr>
<pre>

Location             Refugee Pop.      UAC        IDP

Rwanda                                 41,000     100,000
                                                  dispersed
Goma                 743,000           30,000

Bukavu               302,000           10,000

Uvira                 59,000            2,000

Ngara/Karagwe,TZ     602,121           12,000


Estimated population inside Rwanda is approximately 6.0 million

</pre>
<hr>
<a name="major"></a><p>
<h3>3. Major Programme Areas - UNICEF Rwanda Emergency Programme</h3><p>

<h4>Traditional UNICEF areas</h4>
<ul><li>Health:  Rehabilitation of health centres (150 planned of 307 pre-war, work begun in 27, being prepared in 66); repair of central medical store (done and now functioning); provision of medical equipment, supplies and medicines;  Reactivation of national vaccination programme (210 centres of 307 now operational); preventive health and health education (training conducted for malaria, hygiene, HIV/AIDS, ARI); emergency support to IDP's and camps,  AIDS/HIV prevention (focus on youth).  In camps, support to UNHCR and NGOs for provision of essential medicines and drugs, vaccination services for refugees and local population (Zaire and Tanzania), support to health care services for Unaccompanied children's centres.<p>

<li>Nutrition & HFS:  Supplementary feeding in camps and for UAC - UNIMIX; nutrition surveillance starting, training and support to nutrition centres (UNICEF will rehabilitate 106 of 278 nutrition centres);  Women's credit facilities are being reinitiated, support for food production within context of IDP's and support to area-based activities (distribution of seeds and tools and technical support to 12 communes).  Support to Ministry of the Family and Women's Promotion for review and eventual revision of laws pertaining to women.  In camps,  support and to supplementary feeding of unaccompanied children and for growth monitoring at health centres.<p>

<li>Education:  Provision of Teacher Emergency Package of education materials (TEP's or 'school in a box') in Rwanda and in camps - 7,500 distributed.  Curriculum development, textbook development and support to production, development of Education for Peace programme, teacher training for TEP's and for regular school, teacher training in trauma recovery.  In camps, development of basic schooling programme with TEPs, curriculum and organization with UNHCR and NGOs.<p>

<li>Water and sanitation:  Provision of emergency water assistance for IDPs, refugees and returnees.  This includes drilling wells in Ngara, trucking water to camps in Zaire and Rwanda and provision of chemicals and equipment for water distribution.  Repair and rehabilitation of urban and rural water schemes support to operation of key urban water schemes (coverage of urban water supply now at pre-war levels), support to donor consortium to repair electrical grid line in Rwanda to ensure long-term sustainability of water supply.  Hygiene education.</ul><p>

<h3>Areas specific to Rwanda Emergency Operations</h3>
<ul><li>Children in Especially Difficult Circumstances (CEDC): UNICEF is focal point for issues dealing with children inside Rwanda and has joint responsibility with UNHCR for children's issues in all camps.  Special programmes for <i>Unaccompanied Children</i> (UAC) including identification, family tracing, direct support to children, to fostering and family follow-up.  To date nearly 9, 000 children have been re-united with their families thanks to the combined work of UNICEF, ICRC, SCF, UNHCR and several NGOs.  Photographic programme with ICRC and UNHCR in camps and inside Rwanda (12,000 children photographed in Goma and over 8,000 children in centres inside Rwanda) is now accelerating the tracing process.  Posters with photos assist the parents and relatives to find their children.<p>

<li>Develop and carry-out a programme with Government and NGOs for moving <i>child prisoners</i> from currently overcrowded prisons to separate detention centres.  The first 200 children should be moved this month, once the new facility is available.  UNICEF is also providing education materials (TEPs), recreation equipment, trauma counselling and legal assistance to children accused of participating in the genocide.<p>

<li>develop and organise a programme for the <i>demobilisation of child soldiers</i>.  Inside Rwanda approximately 2,000 children are being removed from their current military context to a centre in Butare.  Support for education, counselling, parent tracing and fostering will be included in the programme.  A further 1, 500 child soldiers outside Rwanda (with former government) are also being demobilised.<p>

<li><i>Trauma recovery programme:</i>  training, development of materials, counselling, development and support for a national trauma recovery centre.  Over 2,000 social agents have been trained (teachers, care givers in orphanages, NGO staff, health workers and religious/community leaders).  Mass media campaign for radio with dialogue on trauma and support in Kinyarwanda.  Pilot surveys of children and women done, survey of 2,200 children throughout Rwanda will be carried out this month.  National seminar on trauma and bereavement held on 5-6 April as part of national week of mourning.  National trauma recovery centre will be opened this month for documentation, training and treatment.<p>

<li>Institutional support: To commune level development - provision of equipment, supplies and temporary personnel for commune level development.  Support to central ministries and physical rehabilitation of infrastructure, transport and logistics.</ul>

<a name="funding"></a><p>
<h3>4.  Current funding Situation 1995</h3>
<ul><li>The UNICEF portion of the 1995 Consolidated Appeal seeks a total of $66.0 million of which $55.0 million was for inside Rwanda and an additional $11.0 million for UNICEF support programmes in the refugee areas of E.Zaire and N.Tanzania.  The impressive response to the 1994 appeal and the gradual contributions (some received in November and December) allowed UNICEF to carry-over more than $20.0 million to 1995.  These funds are exhausted and UNICEF is now operating on a very limited budget of approximately $8.0 million received to date against the 1995 appeal.  Funding needs against currently available grants are indicated in the table below.</ul><p>

Sources of Funding:<br>
<ul>45%   National Committees for UNICEF and other private fund-raising.<br>
32%   Bilateral.<br>
23%   Multilateral (World Bank, ECHO, UNFPA, WHO)</ul>

<a name="donor"></a><p>
<h3>5.  Donor Reporting</h3>
UNICEF Rwanda has received more than 100 individual contributions from over 50 separate donors.  We have now completed the first overall Progress Report covering the period of May 1994 - March 1995 (copies available).  This will be submitted to all donors along with a short detailed description of the utilisation of their specific donation.  We have tried to develop a format that is informative and interesting to donors without being overly burdensome to the UNICEF operations.
<hr>
 <pre>
SECTOR           APPEAL AMOUNT        FUNDED      UNFUNDED

Health            15,900,000        1,191,900    14,708,100

Nutrition          6,550,000          324,500     6,225,500

Water and         11,000,000        1,090,900     9,909,100
sanitation

