<html>
<head>
<title>Statement by Dr. (Mrs.) Attiya Inayatullah


President of IPPF


on 


World Population Day

11 July 1996  
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3>
<i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i>
<br clear=left><hr>


<center>
<br>

<h2>Statement by Dr. (Mrs.) Attiya Inayatullah<p>


President of IPPF<p>


on <p>


World Population Day<p>


11 July 1996 </h2><br clear=all>

<hr width=71%></center><p>



<blockquote>
On this World Population Day, IPPF urges the global community to live up to the promises made at recent international conferences by incorporating the human right to sexual and reproductive health care into their national policies and by allocating the funding necessary to make these promises a reality. <p>




The UN-sponsored conferences of the past few years - particularly the International Conference on Population and Development in Cairo, the World Social Summit in Copenhagen, the Beijing Fourth World Conference on Women and the Conference on Human Settlements in Istanbul - have been valuable tools for discussion and consensus building. We have witnessed in recent years, an international community that is ready for change - that through its acceptance of the lofty language of conference documents, has signalled its willingness to accept people-centred development as the only kind of development that is truly sustainable and acceptable.<p>




The Habitat II Conference which took place in Istanbul in June brought to a close the series of world conferences designed to move the focus of the UN member states from the traditional concepts of security towards sustainable development. For the past few years the world community has debated development from the point of view of environment, social issues, population, women and finally human settlements.<p>




The subjects of these conferences were of direct concern to IPPF which worked throughout to emphasise that sexual and reproductive health care and rights were important components of sustainable development. <p>




In Cairo at the International Conference on Population and Development, we were able to help the global community move away from the demographic way of thinking about population programmes toward the human dimension which recognises reproductive health as fundamental to population and development policies and initiatives. In Beijing at the Forth World Conference on Women, we helped the global community recognise and accept the pivotal role of women's empowerment and rights in achieving healthy families and communities and in overall economic and social development. In Istanbul at the Habitat II Conference, we joined together with our partners in development to ensure that the "human" element - particularly as it pertained to women, young people, and the maginalized - was front and centre in the discussion on human settlements. The outcome of the Habitat II Conference was significant because, as the last of the series of international conference in the millennium, it protected the advances made in Cairo and Beijing and went an important  step further by recognising women's rights to inheritance and ownership of property. <p>




Since the Cairo Conference nearly two years ago governments in some countries have made real progress. In Pakistan and Thailand for example, the governments are increasing spending on reproductive health programmes and on education for girls and women. South Africa has begun nationwide public consultations on new reproductive health and population policies. India has passed a national law banning sex selective abortion. New Zealand has passed progressive human rights legislation that includes sexual rights protection. Canada has become one of the first countries to recognise Female Genital Mutilation as grounds for refugee status in that country.<p>




But much more work needs to be done. Each year nearly 600,000 women continue to die from problems associated with pregnancy and childbirth. Twenty million women have unsafe abortions each year and tens of thousands die as a result. Fifteen million teenage girls give birth yearly. Pregnancy and childbirth is the biggest killer within this age group.<p>




Despite promises made in Cairo of an extra $12 billion in funding for population-related activities, family planning and sexual and reproductive health continue to be viewed by most countries as a consumer sector for which a few dollars are reluctantly spent. Yet for half of that - the amount it cost to build 10 B-2 Stealth Aircraft or 5 Trident nuclear submarines - the entire maternal health and education of the women of the world could be paid for.<p>




IPPF and its member Family Planning Associations are determined to integrate the goals agreed to at Cairo and the other global conferences into their work. FPAs sometimes with the help of other agencies and governments member, are making a difference. In Russia for example the FPA through programmes to disseminate information and provide access to services has helped reduce the high number of abortions performed. In Mexico the FPA has created successful programmes to encourage men to take responsibility for their sexual and reproductive behaviour. In Kenya the FPA has started a successful advocacy programme which is helping to change public attitudes toward the harmful practice of Female Genital Mutilation. <p>




Let us use World Population Day to mark the beginning of a new era for development - where IPPF and its global partners form the bridges of communication, using their foundations of grassroots pragmatism to help governments shape constructive policies and wisely use their limited financial resources to ensure healthy lives for women, children and men everywhere.</blockquote><p>





<hr>
©Copyright IPPF
<hr>

<p><a href="index.html">IPPF Home Page</a>
<hr>
</body>
