<center><h2>TANZANIAN PUPILS SAMPLE BRITISH LIFE</h2></center>

A group of Tanzanian students visiting Britain for the first time say our weather is similar to theirs - well, they did visit in the middle of a July heatwave!<p>

The east African students, from Shambalai School in Lushoto, were on a three-week visit to St Bedes School in Redhill, Surrey. Their visit was part of an exchange scheme between the two schools dating back to 1989. Highlights included a trip to the Rover car factory in Cowley, Oxfordshire, and a visit to the Houses of Parliament where they met Baroness Chalker, Minister for Overseas Development.<p>

Last year pupils from St Bedes visited Shambalai School in Tanzania.  For many of them, it was their first experience of Africa - and they found a warm welcome.<p>

<i>"We were all overwhelmed by the friendliness of the Tanzanians and how they went out of their way to help us," &nbsp;</i>remembers Alice Lear. <p>

Louise Barton, another pupil, noticed that Tanzanian students were less keen on fashion than British teenagers. <i>"The Shambalai students consider clothes a necessity and not a fashion statement," &nbsp;</i>she said. <p>

Timothy Larcombe summed up the trip: <i>"It was the experience of a lifetime," &nbsp;</i>he says.<p>
<hr width=60%>
<br><br>

A visit to the Cowley car plant in Oxford helped 18-year-old Erick Justin make up his mind about  his future. <p>
<i>"I enjoyed the car visit best," he says. "We saw how cars were made - now I want to go to college to study engineering."&nbsp;</i><br><br><br><br><br clear=all><hr width=60%>

<br>
<i>"Most of the families are very small,"&nbsp;</i> says Sylvia Denis, 17, who is one of  five brothers and two sisters. <i>"It's good because it's easier to take care of the children."&nbsp;</i><p>

Other plusses included computers, the "beautiful houses" and the food (chips, chicken and beef). Sylvia finds the British days too long though: in Tanzania it's dark by 6 pm.<br><br><br clear=all>

<hr width=60%>

<br><br>
<i>"Families are very different," &nbsp;</i>says 18-year-old Daniel Herman.<i> "In Tanzania, the women and the girls do the cooking. Here, even the fathers cook for their children.<p>


"But people are so busy here, they don't have time to talk to each other."&nbsp;</i><br><br><br><br clear=all>
<hr width=60%>
<br><br><br>

Like Erick, 18-year-old Hyasinta Lucas enjoyed the visit to the  car factory best. Other likes include the air conditioning, the food, television and British family life. <p>
Any dislikes? <i>"Only  that some of the skirts are too short,"&nbsp;</i> she says.<br><br><br clear=all>

<a name="take2"></a><p>

<hr>
<p>


