<center><h3>CHRISTIAN AID CELEBRATES 50 YEARS</h3></center>

Harvest is the theme for Christian Aid's 50th birthday weekend on 30 September and 1 October.<p>

Supporters are holding harvest parties and vigils on Saturday and thanksgiving services on Sunday.<p>

As part of the celebration Christian Aid is publishing  materials for schools and churches, with ideas for parties, festive recipes  and ideas for church services.
<a name="hope"><a/>
<p>
<hr><br><br>
<h4>A dramatic image of  development: </h4>This poster, by Susie Taylor of Stratford-Upon-Avon Grammar School for Girls  in Warwickshire, highlights the need for clean water in developing countries. Captioning her poster, painted as part of a West Midlands Schools Challenge put forward by the ODA, she writes: <p>
<i>" The whole poster is a scene of hope."&nbsp;</i>
<a name="chosm"></a><br><br><br clear=all>
<hr><p>


<center><h3>SIXTH-FORMERS TO SPEND DAY AS WORLD LEADERS</h3></center>

Sixth-formers are being invited to spend the day as diplomats, presidents and prime ministers in eight mock international debates during the autumn.
Pupils will debate world issues in a role-play based on the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting, which this year will take place in Auckland, New Zealand.<p>

The schools conferences will focus on trade, aid and debt; the environment and development; the Commonwealth and the 'new world order'; and human rights.
<a name="care"></a><p>
<hr><p>


<center><h4>CARE launches telephone info line</h4></center>

The aid agency CARE has launched a telephone service to give callers up-to-date information on its work around the world.<p>

Callers to the 'dispatches' service, which was launched in May, hear a two-minute pre-recorded message on CARE's work in developing countries such as Egypt and India and in war zones like Bosnia and  Afghanistan. 
The messages, which are updated weekly, are recorded by CARE workers overseas.<p>

<i>"Dispatches would be suitable for schoolchildren doing projects on particular countries,"&nbsp;</i> says press officer Antony Robbins. <i>
"What makes this service special is that these messages are from people in the field, so callers can get an overview of our projects all over the world."&nbsp;</i><p>

You can hear 'Dispatches'  by telephoning +44 (0)171 284 5052 at normal BT rates. 
<p><hr>©Copyright: Oda 1995<hr><p>

