<html><head><title>Crosslines: Victims speak out</title><!!keys: Crosslines+Chechnya+war+violence+migration+Russia></head><body><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="crosslines.html"> CROSSLINES</i></a><hr><h2>Victims speak out</h2><i>The New York-based <b>Human Rights Watch</b>/Helsinki (HRW) has been documenting violations of human rights and humanitarian law by Russian and other forces in the Chechnya conflict. A fact-finding mission has been interviewing refugees who fled from Grozny, the Chechen capital, and the surrounding missions and is reporting its findings in a series of information bulletins, the first which was published in January 1995. Updated bulletins are expected to follow in the months ahead.</i><hr>According to the HRW researchers, Russian security forces have shown utter contempt for civilian lives in its efforts to suppress revolt in the breakaway republic. Both victims and witnesses have reported Russian bombs, shells and mortar fire levelling apartment buildings, entire neighbourhoods, and single-family homes in Grozny. The Russians have also been hitting civilian areas in outlying villages both in Chechnya and in neighbouring Ingushetia. <p>HRW maintains that Russia's consistent pattern of firing on civilians grossly violates its humanitarian law obligations set out in the 1949 Geneva Conventions and their 1977 Second Protocol, which governs internal armed conflict. The Geneva Conventions strictly forbid indiscriminate fire and targeting civilians, and oblige Russian forces at all times to prevent harm to civilians. Russia has similar obligations under United Nations rules adopted in 1969. <p>HRW says that it condemns "in the strongest terms" the conduct of Russian forces and calls upon Russian President Boris Yeltsin to end the indiscriminate bombing and shelling of civilians and civilian property. It also calls upon the Russian leader to condemn these attacks, and to punish, in a manner consistent with international law, those responsible for carrying them out. Similarly, HRW calls upon Defence Minister Pavel Grachev and Interior Minister Viktor Yerin to enforce adherence to the Geneva Conventions by the Russian Army and Interior Ministry commanders and troops, and to announce publicly that violations of humanitarian law will be punished. <p>(Human rights observers at the Geneva Human Rights Commission in February noted that even with the Russian takeover of the Chechen capital, fighting may not come to an end but is expected to move to other areas, many of them with large civilian populations.)<p>HRW also criticized the Clinton Administration in the United States for losing an opportunity to take an early stand against the slaughter in Chechnya. It first made mild calls for Russian restraint and characterized the conflict as "an internal matter", even though the rules of the Organization on Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) consider that gross violations of human rights are the concern of all member states. Only after public criticism of its position and after its European partners deplored Russian conduct did the US government show appropriate concern, HRW maintains. In contrast, Western European governments were quick to condemn Russian conduct in Chechnya and to threaten sanctions. The Council of Europe, for example, has suspended temporarily Russia's application for admission, which is premised on respect for human rights principles.<p><hr>For further information contact: Human Rights Watch/Helsinki, 485 Fifth Avenue, New York, NY 10017-6104, USA. Tel: 1(212)-972-8400. Fax: 1(212)-972-0905 <p>©Copyright:<b> CROSSLINES</b> Global Report 1995. Uploaded with permission.<hr><a href="index.html"><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo2.gif">  CROSSLINES Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
