<html><head><title>Rwanda: Special Report - Healing the mind</title><!!keys: ></head><body><h2>Healing the mind</h2>According to a recent Unicef survey in one part of Rwanda, 47% of children saw other children killing people, two-thirds had witnessed massacres, 20 % witnessed rape and sexual abuse, and 56% saw family members being killed.These traumatised children must find some way to express the horrifying scenes they have witnessed, rather than suppress them. <p><ul><img src="../unicef/unicef_pix/rw_role.gif"></ul><p><i>Psychologists are helping these children role play their memories in order to gain a sense of mastery over their experiences.</i> <p>Says Dr Leila Gupta, Project Officer for Unicef's Trauma Recovery Programme: 'Trauma doesn't go away. If you try to push it down it's a disaster. Nobody has escaped the trauma. All the adults are grieving so their own emotional resources are limited. The adults can't think about the future and the children feel the adults have let them down. Our greatest success has been to get the word out - it's ok to be traumatised: there are people you can talk to who will understand." <p>Some 2000 Social Agents - teachers, social workers and aid workers - have been trained to alleviate trauma. <p><ul><img src="../unicef/unicef_pix/rw_hoop.gif"></ul><p><i>The trained helpers encourage the children talk about their experiences, paint pictures, or play games.</i>  <p><br>©Copyright: Stills extracted from video by Unicef.</body></html>
