http://www.ecdpm.org:80/womankind/news_aut95/will.html 193.128.6.150 19970213134817 text/html 5479
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Thu, 13 Feb 1997 13:47:36 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.5
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Thu, 22 Feb 1996 17:25:56 GMT
Content-length: 5305
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Womankind Worldwide - Newsletter</title></head><body bgcolor="bdfbc0" text="000000" link="9306a9" vlink="502c88"><h1 align=center><img width=589 height=77 src="newsletter_logo.jpg" ></h1><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="../wk_info.html">Womankind Worldwide</a></i><hr><h1 align=center>Making a will</h1><font size=+1>If sorting out your will is something you have been meaning to do for ages but just haven't got around to yet, you are not alone. In fact, three quarters of the population have never made a will. Yet, making a will can be quite simple and takes a lot less effort than people imagine.</font><h4>Why make a will?</h4>By making a will, you can be sure that those close to you will benefit from your estate in accordance with your wishes. Many people underestimate the money and assets they have to leave to their family, friends or favorite good cause. A small property added to a car, and maybe an insurance policy or one or two items of value, can easily mount up to quite a considerable estate.<p>If a person dies without leaving a valid will, they are said to have died intestate and their estate is divided among certain relatives according to the laws of intestacy. Of course, the way in which the law divides up your estate may not reflect your wishes.<p>For instance, many people assume that if they are married and die intestate, everything automatically goes to their wife or husband. This is not necessarily the case by any means. In fact, a spouse may have to share the estate with children or other relatives. There have been cases where a surviving husband or wife has had to sell the family home in order to pay a relative's share of their partner's estate. For the growing number of couples who choose to live together without being married, many do not realise that a common law husband or wife is not entitled to any part of their partner's estate unless they are specifically mentioned in their will.<p>The laws of intestacy are fascinating and it is worth finding out more about them. There are easy to read books available for the lay person. Nevertheless, the one sure way to guarantee your money will be divided according to your wishes is to take the time now to make a will.<p><h4>How to make a will</h4>Writing your own will is easier than most people think. There are helpful 'DIY' packs and books available from leading stationers and book shops. In fact, 1 in 5 people do write their own will. However, we would recommend that you seek professional assistance from a solicitor or your bank, especially if your affairs are at all complicated. <p>One area where professional advice may be able to help is by advising you on how you might reduce or avoid inheritance tax. In general, if the value of what you leave in your will, added to the value of any gifts made over the last seven years, is more than £150,000 then inheritance tax is payable on the excess ( unless bequeathed to your spouse ).<p>If you already have a will, it is worth reviewing it every once in a while and keeping it up to date with your personal circumstances. It is important to remember that in most circumstances your existing will be completely revoked if you get married. Minor alterations, such as including additional beneficiaries, can be made as a codicil to your will but it might be better to write a new will if there are major alterations. ( Make sure you destroy the old one ! ) <p><h4>Remembering a good cause</h4>Remembering a charity in your will is a wonderful way of leaving a gift that will go on doing good work in your memory. <p>Legacies already make a considerable contribution to the excellent work carried out by the voluntary sector. Every year, people in England and Wales alone leave between £600 and £700 million to charities. This accounts for about one-third of all voluntary income. The outstanding work of British charities could not continue without the generosity of ordinary people who remember their favourite cause in their will.<p>We hope that you, our supporters, will remember the lives of women in developing countries when you come to write or modify your will. We are still a very young charity and, as to be expected, our income from legacies is small. However, as we look towards our long term future, it is our hope that some of our vital work can be supported in this way. <p>A gift in your will towards the work of WOMANKIND will be a departing gesture of hope and encouragement to women in developing countries who face hardship and prejudice every day of their lives. Whatever you leave, it will help to support their unfailing courage and determination to get their voices heard and to make the most of their tremendous talents, vision and hard work.<p>If you are considering leaving a bequest to WOMANKIND in your will, we do have a leaflet setting out approved wording which we would be happy to send you. Please call Simona on 0181 563 8607 and ask to be sent our 'Have you the Will?' leaflet.<p><h3 align=center>Make a Will Week, organised by The Law Society, will run from 16 to 22 October this year.</h3><b><a href="index.html">Contents Page</a></b><p><hr><p>©Copyright:1996 Womankind Worldwide<hr></body></html>
