<h2>TVE New Programmes</h2>



<font size=4 face=helvetica, arial>GLOBAL BANQUET:
TVE FILMS FOR THE WORLD FOOD SUMMIT<br>
13 to 17 November 1996</font>
<p>


<font size=2 face=helvetica, arial>Dear Broadcaster,<p>

I am writing to let you know about a new series of programmes that TVE is offering for broadcast this
autumn.<p>

More people eat better than ever before - while, at the same time, more people go hungry than ever
before. It s a paradox accounted for by increasing global food production and increasing numbers of poor
people. Before the middle of the next century, the planet will have to feed 50 per cent more people than
are alive today. But increasing current food production is only one aspect of the agenda on the World
Food Summit - a better diet; security of tenure; improved marketing; soil and biodiversity conservation;
help for women farmers are others. The challenge is to provide enough food.<p>


To mark the Food Summit, TVE is producing a 30-minute special , <b><a href="food.html">FOOD FOR
THOUGHT</a></b> - which is embargoed
until the eve of the conference itself. <b><a href="food.html">FOOD FOR THOUGHT</a></b> looks at some
of the
key issues the world s governments will consider in Rome: land reform in Nepal; revival of traditional
farming in Zimbabwe; monsoon harvesting in India are among the stories currently in production. <p>


The programme begins with a five minute introductory overview. The six 
featured stories can be shown as separate items, or together as a single programme in chapters .<p>


We also have <b><a href="newprogs2.html">details of the other programmes we can provide for your
stations</a></b>.<p>


I look forward to receiving your order.<p>


Yours sincerely,<br>


<b>Jenny Richards, Deputy-Director<br>
TVE International</b><p></font>

