<html>

<header>

<title>Netherlands development cooperation: Norms and policy</title>

</header>

<hr>

<H2><center><p></a>

Netherlands development cooperation: Norms and policy</h2>

<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>

<p>

Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No. 3, July 1993</h4>

<h5>The full text of the report in English, as well as a list of other publications, are available free of

charge from the Council's secretariat: E-mail: nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</h5>

</center>

<hr>

<b>On 1 July 1993 the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) presented the

Minister for Development Cooperation, J P Pronk, with a report on the norms and nature of the Netherlands

development cooperation.</b>

<p>

<h3>Summary</h3>



With this report, the NAR wishes to make a contribution to the current social and political discussion on

Netherlands development cooperation. The report contains the following propositions:

<ul>

<li>the current confusion regarding the nature of the Netherlands development effort and the norms

defining its extent - in that order - should be brought to an end as quickly as possible;

<li>the recently abandoned norm was in no way excessive, considering the problems, both old and new,

confronting developing countries;

<li>the problems currently facing developing countries need to be re-assessed in the light of recent

developments;

<li>there is an urgent need for a clear policy, particularly in the light of current public opinion in the

Netherlands - as perceived by the Council - regarding development cooperation.

</ul>

<p>

<h3>Time for clarity</h3>



The NAR urges that a number of measures should be taken within the coming five years to address the

problems, both old and new, facing development policy. Aid to the poorest developing countries should be

increased, with less going to the richer ones. More scope should be created for assistance to Central and

Eastern Europe and to tackle environmental problems. With this new framework for aid established, the

norm for the Netherlands contribution should be set at a new level - 1.5% of NNI (Net National Income)

after the five-year period.

<p>

Furthermore, the Council urges that the multilateral trade negotiations (the Uruguay round) be completed as

soon as possible and in such a way as to increase the export potential of developing countries. The Council

also believes that there is scope for drawing up regional trade agreements between the North and South.

<p>

Protection of the markets of the rich countries against the import of goods and the migration of labour from

developing countries restricts the development potential of these countries. The Council sees this as a further

reason for providing assistance, to compensate for these restrictions.

<p>

Discussion of new tasks in the areas of the environment, peace and security and aid to Central and Eastern

Europe should not be avoided. These issues are relevant to development cooperation and should, under

certain conditions,  be integrated into development policy.

<p>

In the interests of effectiveness and to prevent fragmentation, the Council advocates reducing the number of

countries (currently 54) which receive aid from the Netherlands. In addition, efforts aimed at structural

poverty alleviation should be concentrated in the 37 poorest countries with which the Netherlands already

has a development relationship. Expansion of the programme to countries in Central and Eastern Europe

will make further streamlining  necessary.

<p>

<h3>Stop the political erosion of development cooperation</h3>



The NAR is optimistic regarding the extent of public support for development cooperation in the Nether-

lands. It laments the erosion of development policy at the political level and the emergence of a political

decision-making process which is both unclear and out of line with the intentions and preferences of a large

part of the Netherlands population. The "contamination" of the budget, which has increased considerably

since 1989, should be rectified within a specified period to allow scope for the proposed new policy.

<p>

<h3>Measures</h3>



Given the current situation, the Council recommends that the government undertake the following action

during the coming five years:

<ol>

<li>Official Development Assistance (ODA): The first priority should be to increase ODA to developing

countries through multilateral and bilateral programmes (including those of the Co-Financing Organisations)

from its current level of 0.78% to 1,0% of GNP in the 1998 budget. The table below indicates how the

development budget should be allocated:

<p>

<p>



<TABLE>

<TABLE BORDER=1>

<TR>

<TH>Category</TH><TH>1998 Target</TH>

</TR>

<TR>

<TD>countries < US$ 650</TD><TD>0.72</TD>

</TR>

<TR><TD>countries > US$ 650 and <1,235</TD><TD>0.18</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

<TD>GEF and other environmental<TD>0.10</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

<TD>ODA developing countries</TD><TD>1.00</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

<TD>non-ODA</TD><TD>0.14</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

<TD>ODA C/E Europe*</TD><TD>0.05</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

<TD>Total (% of GNP)</TD><TD>1.19</TD>

</TR>

<TR>

<TD>* very rough estimate</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>





<p>

<li>'Purification' of the budget: A clearer picture should be given of the expenditure that should, now or

in the future, be included in the aid budget. A number of the items that are currently covered by the budget

(see annex 3) should be removed. These include the costs of accommodating asylum-seekers, the

contribution to the Ministry of Education and Science and a number of others which are in no way related to

the interests of developing countries. The first two items mentioned account for 36% of the non-ODA part

of the 1993 development budget (NLG 497.7m of a total of NLG 1,385m). The total non-ODA part of the

budget is 0.24% of GNP or 0.31% of NNI. This purification should be effected within a specified period

(for example, five years);

<p>

<li>Choice of countries: In the interests of efficiency, the criteria for countries eligible for development

assistance from the Netherlands should be tightened up. In respect of the ODA contribution, at least 80%

should be allocated to countries with a per capita income of US$ 650 or less and no ODA should be

allocated to countries with a per capita income higher than US$ 1,235 (1991 levels). Countries falling

between these two limits may be eligible for concessional loans on ODA terms in exceptional circumstances;

<p>

<li>New countries: Aid to countries in Central and Eastern Europe will automatically be categorised as

ODA when they qualify for the DAC list and if the aid is sufficiently concessional. This assistance should

be provided from regular development funds, as far as this is made possible by reducing the contamination

of the budget. If this proves insufficient, additional funds will have to be released;

<p>

<li>Environmental expenditure: Contributions that are made by the Netherlands through bilateral and

multilateral (e.g. GEF) channels to help developing countries on the DAC list comply with international

environmental agreements will automatically be considered ODA by the DAC. This assistance should be

provided from regular development funds, as far as this is made possible by reducing the contamination of

the budget. If this proves insufficient, additional funds will have to be released;

<p>

<li>Separation of expenditure: Certain items that fall under the development budget which are relevant to

developing countries but are not ODA as defined by the DAC should be given a ceiling. This expenditure

includes such items as administrative expenses, certain interest subsidies, etc. It is recommended that a

ceiling of 0.14% of GNP be imposed on these items within a period of five years;

<p>

<li>Security: Development funds should not be used to put an end to armed conflict but to provide

humanitarian aid and support for reconstruction once conflicts have been resolved. Assessment of defence

spending by developing countries and subsequent policy should as far as possible follow the criteria drawn

up jointly by donors. Support for the setting up of democratic institutions at both national and local level and

including institutions to guarantee access to reliable legal procedures should be given high priority.

</ol>

<p>

"It would be a miracle if we succeed, functioning as we do". These words were used by Jawaharlal Nehru

when he presented India's first Five-Year Plan. The NAR believes that international problems in the areas

of security, poverty and the environment will increase in both size and intensity during the coming decade,

demanding a greater international effort and greater sacrifices from the industrialised countries. As a

development partner and in its role as international defender of the interests of developing countries and the

poor that inhabit them, the Netherlands should reaffirm that it is able to provide an appropriate and reliable

contribution to the solution of these issues. Where possible the Netherlands should strive to attain a higher

norm - two per cent of NNI is not an excessive target.

<p>

<HR>

<H6> <i>Updated on January 22, 1996</i><p>

Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the Netscape browser. Please address comments

on content or style to <a href="mailto:pb@ecdpm.org">Peter

