<html>

<header>

<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>

</header>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Luxembourg</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the

National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.

<br> 

<h5> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.

1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen

European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The

report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The

Hague, the Netherlands.

</h5>

<hr>

<h3>Contents:</h3>

<ul>

<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Luxembourg's Development Cooperation</a>

<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>

<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>

<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>

<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"></a>

</ul><p>



<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Luxembourg's Development Cooperation</h3>



Government development assistance programmes were created in the second half of the 1980s, supported by

the public and the many NGOs in Luxembourg. Support for development cooperation is still high among the

public and in Parliament, based on a humanitarian tradition.

<p>

Net official development assistance grew steadily - and sometimes quite spectacular - since the mid-1980s

and in 1992 stood at US $ 36 million, or 0.26 per cent of GNP, while further rises are planned. 55.5 per

cent of the total ODA was spent bilaterally in 1992, and 25 per cent through the EU. The remaining 20 per

cent mainly went to the World Bank Group. Multilateral assistance and contributions, having been very

high, stabilised since 1988 on 30 - 45 per cent. Luxembourg joined the DAC in November 1992. 

<p>

<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>

<p>

Development cooperation is the political responsibility of the Minister of Foreign Affairs. The management

of Luxembourg's aid programme lies with the Directorate for International Relations and Economic

Cooperation in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, External Trade and Cooperation. It is not a structure

specifically geared to development problems. Its staff is primarily made up of diplomats, who tend to

change posts, making it hard to build up expertise. In 1992 the administrative structure was completely

overhauled. A legislative framework for development cooperation was established by a number of laws in

1985, and has been up-dated since. It created, amongst other things, a special fund to finance the aid

programme, the FAD, which presently is the main bilateral aid channel. The Development Cooperation

Fund (FCD) is replenished annually by the Government, by budgetary capital gains and by private grants. It

is not subject to the annual budget appropriation principle, which facilitates the administration of

development projects spanning several years. The MFA is responsible for 89 per cent of the total

cooperation budget (1993). The other Ministries involved are the Treasury (for contributions to international

financial institutions), Finance (contributions to certain international organisations), Health, and National

Education. The latter operates a.o. through an independent Agency in the field of cultural cooperation for

countries that are (partially) French speaking.

<p>

For implementation of the bilateral programme the MFA relies heavily on Lux-Development, a private

status company. Set up to promote exports to developing countries in 1978, it is now, after a reorganization

in 1992, a fully equipped implementing agency. Lux-Development has a governing board of 13

representatives from the Federation of Luxembourg Industries, the banks, the Chamber of Commerce,

consulting engineers, and, as representatives of the Government, three members from the MFA, one from

the Treasury and another one from the Ministry of Finance.

<p>

Until now no specific structure within the Ministry of Foreign Affairs has been set up for the formulation of

development cooperation policy. No formal mechanism has yet been established for programming and

evaluating activities in developing countries. This situation, sometimes causes pipeline problems, with regard

to the disbursement of the planned aid volume. Policy coordination and control - the latter between the

Ministry and Lux-Development - is reported lacking sometimes.

<p>

<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>

<p>

There is no (formally organised) advisory structure for development cooperation in Luxembourg. Outside

experts and consultants are involved in the technical operations of project and programme preparation and

implementation.

<p>

Annually an activity report of the FCD plus a financial statement is submitted to Parliament, as well as the

annual report of the MFA about development cooperation.

<p>

<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>

<p>

There are approximately 800 NGOs in Luxembourg. One-fourth of total development assistance is

channelled through NGOs. 65 NGOs that are accredited by the Government (in 1993), are allowed to draw

from the FCD. Coordination of development efforts, streamlining of (co-financing) procedures and

professionalisation are topics of discussion between the Government and the NGOs. Consultative meetings

with government representatives take place about four times a year. An umbrella organisation, the 'Cercle

de Coop&#233;ration des ONG de Luxembourg', is created to represent the main NGOs in their contacts

with the Government and the European Union, as well as to encourage contacts among its members

(currently: 36).

<p>

No development research institutes are reported to exist in Luxembourg.

<p>

<hr>

<H6></a>

<i>Updated on November 7, 1995</i><br>

Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the Netscape browser. Please address comments

on content or style to <a href="mailto:pb@ecdpm.org">Peter Ballantyne</a>, Information Programme,

ECDPM</H6>

<HR>

