<html><head><title>OneWorld Radio News</title></head><body vlink=#990099 link=#990099 bgcolor=#ffffff background="../../images/background.gif"><blockquote><font face=helvetica,arial><TABLE BORDER=0 width=90%><TR><TD align=left><img align=left border=0 hspace=10 vspace=10 width=189 height=74 src="../../radio_news/images/blurb.gif"></td></tr><tr><td align=right><img align=right border=0 hspace=10 vspace=10 width=263 height=86 src="../../radio_news/images/logo.gif"><br clear=all><br></TD></TR></TABLE><h2 align=center>ONEWORLD TACKLES INFORMATION POVERTY THROUGH WEB RADIO</h2>If you want to reduce the information-poverty gap, what's the point ofputting information on the Internet, where 94% of the world's populationcan't access it? Decades will pass before the conventional benefits of theWeb reach most of the rural South - unlike radio, the world's most-usedmass medium.<p>But the trouble with radio is that it usually has to remain within nationalbounds.  Few stations can afford foreign correspondents - and it isproblematic to send broadcast-quality audio material over long distanceswithout expensive technology, so southern broadcasters are often frustratedwhen they try to acquire affordable foreign news. Content is a problem too:who offers broadcasters global news of human rights and sustainabledevelopment?<p>Now there is to be an innovative new service that aims to meet all theseneeds.  The OneWorld supersite, the world's leading website on human rightsand development issues, has now developed the OneWorld Radio News Service -and it is free to Southern broadcasters.<p>Says OneWorld's editor, Anuradha Vittachi: "To radio's advantages as a massmedium, we are adding the Internet's outreach and flexibility - in order toput the debate about global justice firmly on the world's agenda."<p><h3>THE ONEWORLD RADIO NEWS SERVICE</h3>The pilot project will enable radio broadcasters worldwide to download fromthe Internet - and then re-broadcast from their local radio station - soundclips containing important human rights and development news.  Theinformation is intended to flow both ways: radio stations from the Souththat join the Radio News Service will be contributing material as well asreceiving it. So direct South-South information exchange could become quickand easy.<p>The one year pilot project  is being launched in April 1997 by OneWorldOnline (the Internet arm of the One World Broadcasting Trust) with helpfrom the Commonwealth Broadcasting Association.<p><h3>WELCOME FROM BROADCASTERS</h3>The Radio News Service has already had a warm welcome from internationalbroadcasters.  Govin Reddy, Chief Executive of Radio at the South AfricanBroadcasting Association has expressed to COMBROAD his interest in checkingout the project's potential for SABC.<p>Jonathan Marks, Director of Programmes at Radio Netherlands, went further,emphasising the need for alternative global news networks: "It's a veryimportant development.  Media coverage of an event is too often based onwhether CNN or other big networks are covering it - if they're not, thenthe story is often dismissed as being of no news value.  If the creation ofthis OneWorld Radio News Service means that programme-makers around theworld have greater access to relevant environmental or human rights storiesfrom places where there isn't a camera, and use this opportunity, then it'sfulfilling a vital need."<p>OneWorld and the CBA are eager to involve community radio broadcasters fromthe very beginning of the project.  They hope to give support to existingradio partnership networks, like Pulsar in Latin America.<p>"We are working on a number of projects including a pilot service providingradio spots and announcements on HIV and AIDS," says Steve Buckley,Vice-President of the World Association of Community Radio Broadcasters(AMARC) and Director of the national Community Radio Association in theUnited Kingdom.  "We are keen to work in partnership with otherorganisations such as OneWorld who could develop the use of radio forbroadcasting information on social and developmental issues."<p><h3>HOW IT WORKS</h3>OneWorld has set up a Web site - globally accessible through the Internet -where radio broadcasters can browse through audio news and features andchoose which items they would like to re-broadcast on their stations.There are no copyright restrictions (bar a requirement to attribute thesource).<p>After logging into the OneWorld Radio News Service and choosing a clip, thebroadcaster only has to enter a few short details and a password - and hitthe 'download' button.  The clip will then download to the radio station'scomputer and be ready for local playback.  The clips will play back at veryhigh quality for broadcast, which can then be recorded onto tape andprogrammed into the station's output.  To assist broadcasters, OneWorld hasmade available a text summary of each audio clip, a suggested introduction,in and out points, and a possible back announcement.<p><h3>TECHNICAL DETAILS</h3>To transfer quickly across the Internet, digital audio files must bemassively compressed.  Using RealAudio, this can be achieved with only asmall loss of local playback quality.  Further, Shockwave software allowsaudio to be 'streamed' in realtime over the Internet, for broadcasters tohear previews before downloading clips.  Both pieces of software areavailable free from the Radio News site.<p><h3>HOW TO JOIN</h3>A pilot project of the Radio News Service is already operational.  OneWorldwould like to hear from any broadcasters interested in trying out orhelping set up the Radio News Service.  Registration can be completed withan online form on the Radio News site: <a href="../../radio_news/">http://www.oneworld.org/radio_news/</a>Alternatively, broadcasters can e-mail OneWorld on: <a href="mailto:justice@oneworld.org">justice@oneworld.org</a>  -or fax: 00 1494 481751<p></font></blockquote></body></html>
