<html>

<header>

<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>

</header>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in France

</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by

ECDPM on behalf of the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR)

of the Netherlands.

<br> 

<h5> Source: Kooij, A.

and R. Mevis. 1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development

Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen European Countries</i>. The Hague:

National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The report is available from:

NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The Hague, the

Netherlands.

</h5>

<hr>

<h3>Contents:</h3>

<ul>

<li><a href="#org">Organisation of French Development Cooperation</a>

<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>

<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>

<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>

<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"></a>

</ul><p>



<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of French Development

Cooperation</h3>



France's official cooperation with developing countries, which dates from the early

1960s, is an extension of its earlier decolonisation policies and administrative set-up.

The annual opinion poll shows that the French public is concerned about the problem of

the hunger issue, and that there is a growing support for aid to Third World

development (25 per cent in 1992).

<p>

Net official development assistance in 1992 stood at US $ 8 270 million, or 0.63 per

cent of GNP. After a period of growth, ODA disbursements are expected to rise only

slightly after 1992. About three-quarters of French ODA is bilateral aid. 24 percent was

disbursed multilaterally in 1992, nearly half via the EU.

<p>

<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>

<p>

Development cooperation is based on a number of successive constitutional laws that

defined France's relationship with its colonies/former colonies, and was elaborated

subsequently in numerous decrees by the President and the Prime Minister. The

administrative set-up and allocation of responsibilities have changed over the years,

following the domestic political situation. 

<p>

Policy preparation, formulation and implementation is spread over four main ministries -

Cooperation and Development (MCD), Foreign Affairs (MFA), Finance and Economic

Affairs (MEA) and the Interior, five or so technical ministries and many (semi-) official

and (semi-) autonomous agencies (educational and training institutes, research

institutes, and NGOs), the latter category being involved mainly in implementation.

<p>

Overall and strategic policy coordination are the responsibilities of the Offices of the

President and Prime Minister. Over and above the internal administrative structure of

the various ministries, decision making is the prerogative of a 'Cabinet', the Office of

each Minister.

<p>

There is no centralised budget for development cooperation, although the Ministry of

Finance and Economic Affairs keeps an overall record of the budget for and expenditure

on development cooperation by the various departments and institutions. 

 

The Ministry of Cooperation and Development, created in 1961 on the basis of the

previous administrative set-up for a French Commonwealth, is responsible for technical,

financial, cultural, military and scientific aid to 'du champ' countries (14.7 per cent of

ODA in 1992). The MCD has the most technical and sectoral expertise of all the

ministries. 

<p>

The Ministry of Foreign Affairs has traditionally been responsible for French external

cultural policy in countries not within France's sphere of influence. Within the MFA the

Directorate-General for Cultural and Scientific Relations is responsible for technical,

cultural and scientific cooperation in the 'hors champ' countries (8.7 per cent of ODA in

1992). Another department handles multilateral cooperation and UN relations (24 per

cent of ODA in 1992). The MFA conducts major policy debates, e.g. on security and

European issues. 

<p>

The Treasury at the Ministry of Finance and Economic Affairs and the MFA are

currently considered as having the greatest influence on policy matters. The Treasury

disburses financial aid (loans and grants) and, together with the Ministry of

Cooperation, finances debt cancellations in the 'du champ' countries. The Treasury

functions as a consultative body for macro-economic matters, drawing on the

substantial analytical and economic expertise of the CfD (Caisse Fran&#231;aise de

D&#233;veloppement).

<p>

Disbursements to the TOMs, as well as to the DOMs, are administered by a State

Secretariat (Ministry of Overseas Departments and Territories; MODT) under the

authority of the Ministry of the Interior. 

<p>

The technical ministries of Research (7.7 per cent of ODA in 1992), Health, Education

(1992: 8.4 per cent of ODA), Agriculture and Culture each manage their own projects.

<p>

Various development institutions implement projects and programmes, often through

specialist agencies working under them. The Fonds d'Aide et de Coop&#233;ration

(FAC), which is a fund without corporate status, administers economic and social

infrastructure projects. The CfD, a banking agency created in 1941, finances through

its many agencies state approved loans for productive investment projects in the 'du

champ' countries, and recently also in some 'hors champ' countries. The technical

ministries operate in the 'du champ' countries often through institutions working under

their authority. Cooperation with development institutes, the private sector, NGOs and

experts in respect of project identification, assessment and preparation, and

implementation and evaluation of technical cooperation is widespread. In addition, there

are various institutions responsible for the training of and technical support for the

French "cooperants." 

<p>

Policy planning and formulation is a complex process involving many institutions, at

various levels. The main actors are the government institutions and agencies

responsible for French cooperation and the relevant interministerial consultative

structures. While policy formulation and decisions are strictly the responsibility of the

Government, many outside actors are involved at a more technical level. 

<p>

As far as the evaluation function is concerned, generally speaking, a systematic and

independent evaluation structure would seem to be lacking, although all institutions for

development cooperation in principle have an evaluation procedure for ODA-funded

operations. Evaluation and programming units are often part of the internal audit or

statistical function. Procedures for feedback and coordination of evaluation activities

will have to be developed. Some institutions have an evaluation or programming unit,

that has input into policy formulation. Since 1989 the Ministry of Cooperation and

Development for instance has had a Studies, Evaluation and Prospective Analysis

Mission that plans policy on the basis of its reviews of French assistance to 'du champ'

countries. Summaries of the findings are for government use only. 

<p>

Since foreign policy, including aid, is a 'shared' concern, coordination of development

cooperation policy ultimately rests with the President of the Republic and the Prime

Minister. They play a discrete but important and, if necessary, arbitrating role. The

State Secretariat of Planning ('le Plan') at the Prime Minister's Office has an important

coordinating function, as has the 'Cabinet' of each minister.

<p>

In 1992 the Government set up a Committee for Orientation and Programming (COP) to

ensure greater complementarity and coherence of cooperation activities in the 'du

champ' countries. Chaired by the Minister of Cooperation, COP is composed of

representatives from his own Ministry, the MFA, the MEA and the CfD. It has

apparently met infrequently. Suggestions for improvements have been put forward.

<p>

Since EU affairs fall under the Prime Minister, several ministries participate in EU policy

preparation, the MFA having a leading role. The General Secretariat of the

Interministerial Committee (SGCI) defines and coordinates the French position on

European affairs. 

<p>

Consultations between ministries and departments on specific topics do occur, e.g.

between the MCD, MFA, MEA/Treasury, the President's Office and the Ministries of

Environment and Agriculture during the preparations for UNCED. Informal talks are held

on trade, multilateral cooperation, treasury matters and cooperation procedures. Policies

and programmes for 'hors champ' countries are coordinated ad hoc by the departments

concerned. However, the frequency of such talks on the 'hors champ' countries is

considered low. Trade and investment relations with developing countries are discussed

with the Agency for Technical, Industrial and Economic Cooperation (ACTIM).

<p>

Project proposals for funding from FAC or CfD funds are handled in a Project

Committee, chaired by the Minister for Cooperation and Development. CfD activities are

coordinated by a 'Conseil d'Administration' which comprises representatives of the

MCD, MFA, MEA and the Ministry of the Interior (DOM/TOMs). The FAC, which is

chaired by the Minister for Cooperation and Development, comprises representatives of

departments involved in development cooperation.

<p>

<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and

Mechanisms</h3></a>

<p>

France has strong central governmental institutions. There is a certain reluctancy to

seek official external advice; there is no tradition of this, and no formal structure for it.

In fact much advice is given during technical and political consultations. The dividing

lines between 'consultation', 'advising' and 'decision-making' are not always clear to

outsiders.

<p>

The Minister for Cooperation and Development submits an annual Statement on aid to

Parliament, as an annex to the Finance Act. The National Assembly has a Foreign

Affairs Committee. However, no substantial discussions appear to be conducted in

Parliament.

<p>

<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>

<p>

Many outside actors make an indirect contribution at least to the

preparation of future policies. First, there are the many research institutes - both

government-financed and independent - that have many years of experience and a

wealth of technical knowledge about the Third World. They undertake studies on their

own initiative and/or may be contracted in by government institutions. Secondly,

private organisations - NGOs and businesses - and the "reseaux" -- sectoral networks

with a broad basis in French society, are involved in implementation and consultation

(see below). Finally, the informal and institutional contacts between politicians at

various levels and individual experts, in organisations ranging from the 'Syndicats

d'Agricole', the White Fathers and M&#233;decins sans Fronti&#232;res, play an

important role in policy consultation and preparation.

<p>

The following categories of organisations, more or less outside the Government, could

be listed as having an 'advisory' impact on French development cooperation policy and

its implementation: informal, mixed brainstorming groups; NGOs and the bureaux

d'&#233;tudes; networks (reseaux); parastatal or state-owned research institutes and

independent research institutes and individual members of their staff. 

<p>

Ad hoc working groups or committees may be appointed to deal with specific subjects,

e.g. the Scientific Committee on Women in Development set up to prepare for the

1995 World Conference on Women in Beijing, which includes representatives of the

ministries concerned and the French and European Parliaments, and journalists. 

<p>

Some departments responsible for development cooperation have informal

brainstorming relationships with outside specialists and institutions. The Centre

d'Analyse et de Prospective (CAP) for instance is involved in brainstorming and policy

preparation on behalf of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. It functions in a rather informal

and independent way, with members from inside as well as outside the Government. 

<p>

In 1992 1 per cent of bilateral ODA was disbursed through NGOs. This is supposed to

reach 5 per cent by 2002. Many of the several hundred French NGOs are involved

actively in French cooperation programmes, through project identification and

preparation, implementation, evaluation, studies and discussions. Discussions with the

Government appear to focus more on the project and programme level than on overall

cooperation policy. Government co-financing activities with NGOs in 'du champ' and

'hors champ' countries are coordinated by an Associations Bureau that both reports to

the MCD and the MFA. 

<p>

The largest of the NGOs (which are now called Associations (or Organisations) for

International Solidarity (AIS) are organised in eight Development Collectives. The largest

collective, created in 1990, is the Comit&#233; de Liaison des Organisations de

Solidarit&#233; Internationale (CLOSI). It comprises eight umbrella organisations that

represent around 250 NGOs. CLOSI, which is financed entirely by the Government, was

set up to improve links between the NGOs themselves and between NGOs and the

Government. A Development Cooperation Board comprising representatives of the

MCD, the MFA, the technical ministries and the NGOs and chaired by the Minister of

Cooperation and Development discusses topics of more general interest. Discussion are

being held on creating a new structure for the joint management, on an equal footing,

of public funds for NGOs: a Public Interest Group (Groupement d'Inter&#234;t Public

(GIP). Many NGOs also have a study and research capacity (the 'bureaux

d'&#233;tudes') and carry out government contracts, for instance GRET, SolaGral,

SURVIE, AGIR-ICI and institutes such as the Institut des Sciences et des Techniques de

l'Equipement et de l'Environnement pour le D&#233;veloppement (ISTEED). An

Evaluation Fund has been established for NGO activities, managed jointly by the NGOs,

the MCD, the MFA and the CfD.

<p>

Since 1992 nine networks (reseaux) have been created on the initiative of the MCD,

comprising institutions and individuals with a recognised interest and expertise in

development cooperation (e.g. farmers' organisations, communities, national and

international women's organisations, NGOs, ex-"cooperants"), as a consultative

structure for the Ministry. These networks, which are financed entirely by the MCD,

were originally set up to work out the details of sectoral programmes for the MCD and

to mobilise development cooperation initiatives in France. They are organised by topics

(e.g. health, women in development, food production). They also have a brainstorming

function: to generate and exchange ideas on development cooperation. In addition they

conduct studies, distribute information on French development cooperation and liaise

with French development institutions, expatriates in developing countries and local

partners (notably in Africa). The original idea was that the networks would grow into

solidarity organisations and undertake development activities. They would appear,

however, to be turning increasingly into implementing agencies for the MCD, although

their relationship with the Ministry is not without its problems. 

<p>

Many large state-owned institutes traditionally do research and carry out studies for the

French Government. The following are well known for their work in development

cooperation: the Institut Fran&#231;ais de Recherche Scientifique pour le

D&#233;veloppement en Coop&#233;ration (ORSTOM), the Centre de

Coop&#233;ration Internationale en Recherche Agronomique pour le

D&#233;veloppement (CIRAD) and the Institut de la Recherche Agronomique (INRA).

To some extent the CfD can be included in this group. It has a large analytical research

capacity in various macro-economic fields (e.g. privatisation, debt, regional cooperation

and sustainable development).

<p>

According to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey there are 103 institutes in France - some

attached to universities, and some not, some government owned, others not - that

qualify as Development Research and Training Institutes. Some of these play a

considerable role in development cooperation studies, consultation and implementation,

on an institutional and/or individual basis. The best known of these are the Centre

d'Etudes et de Recherche sur L'Economie du D&#233;veloppement (CERED) in

Nanterre, the Centre d'Etude et de Recherches sur le D&#233;veloppement

International (CERDI) in Clermont-Ferrand, the Centre d'Etudes et de Recherches

Internationales (CERI) in Paris, the Institut d'Am&#233;nagement R&#233;gional (IAR)

in Aix-en-Provence, the Centre d'Etudes d'Afrique Noire (CEAN) and the Centre

d'Etudes de G&#233;ographie Tropical (CEGET), both in Talence. Eight specialised

institutes for applied scientific research in development cooperation are grouped

together in the Study and Research Group for the Development of Tropical Agriculture

(GERDAT). 

<p>

One group in the business sector that is involved in policy consultation is the Conseil

d'Investisseurs en Afrique Noire (CIAN). There are also other consultative structures in

which the Government consults with representatives of the local authorities, and

Chambers of Commerce.

<p>

<hr>

