<html>
<head>
<title>Save the Children - Social Summit</title>
<!!keys: Save the Children Fund+Social Summit+children>
</head>
<body>

<br clear=right>
<br><i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="STCF.html">Save the Children Fund</a></i>
<hr>
<h3>1. The Social Summit: A Vision Which Will Fail</h3><p>
<p>
<i>The World Summit for Social Development (Social Summit) holds out the promise of putting human welfare back at the top of the world's agenda.  Save the Children welcomes this approach but believes it will fail children.</i>

<p>
Save the Children, as a development agency working in 50 countries including the UK, welcomes and supports the Social Summit, for two reasons: 

<ul><li>it is an attempt to establish a new vision for development which puts people first;  
<li>it encompasses the North as well as the South of the globe.
</ul>

<p>
Save the Children fervently hopes that world leaders will heed this call for a new vision.  
<p>
But at the same time, Save the Children believes that <b>there is a flaw at the very heart of the new vision.</b>  As it stands, <b>it will fail children.</b> In so doing, it will fail as a comprehensive tool for social development.  

<p>
Development, to date, has failed millions of the world's children.  Some of the new policies which will be discussed in Copenhagen will bring improvements. But, for social development to succeed, <b>children must be placed at the heart of policy and planning,</b> in ways which the Summit does not adequately address.

<p>
The way societies regard their children and relate to them, the extent to which children's needs, interests and rights are placed centre stage, must come to be seen as a litmus test of their commitment to human and social development.

<p>
<b>A 'Children's Agenda' for development is urgently required.  Save the Children (UK) has been working towards such an agenda.  The following briefing sheets explain why, and what we mean.</b>
<hr>
<h3>2. How Children Have Been Failed So Far</h3>

<p>
The Social Summit's very existence shows that policy-makers are now facing up to the consequences and failings of economic and social development as practised in the last 50 years. Above all, these failings are reflected in the conditions of life for tens of millions of children.
<p>

The last five decades have brought great improvements in infant mortality, nutrition levels, and life expectancy. But they have also brought growing impoverishment and exclusion from these processes, expressed in the widening gap between rich and poor in all societies, including the industrialised countries.
<p>

Around 1.3 billion people, a quarter of the world's population, live in absolute poverty. And across the world, <i>children</i> are much more at risk of living in poverty than the population as a whole.
<p>

<b>Children in developing countries are twice as likely to be poor as the population as a whole. Almost <i>half</i> of all under-fives in the world live in absolute poverty.
<p>

In the UK, the government's own figures suggest that almost one child in three lives in poverty, again much higher than the proportion of the whole population (about one in four).</b>
<p>

These children face considerable threats to their physical and mental development due to ill-health, poor nutrition and poor housing. Such conditions exist in countries at every stage of development.
<p>

There are other impacts on children of the failure of development, including:
<ul><li>
family breakdown, and lack of family support;
<li>child labour and exploitation;
<li>discrimination;
<li>lack of equal access to essential services such as education and primary health care;
<li>abandonment;
<li>trafficking and sexual exploitation of children.
</ul><hr>
<h3>3. Children As A Litmus Test For Social Development</h3>
The failures of development outlined above matter for several reasons -- not least because <i>children are one of the largest groups in any society,</i> developed or undeveloped.
<p>

Globally, one out of every three people is a child under the age of 15. In some countries the proportion is even higher: in many parts of Africa and the Middle East, children are <i>half</i> the population. But even in industrialised countries, between one fifth and one quarter of the population are children. Thus <i>any</i> development model which neglects or damages children's interests must be accounted a failure.
<p>

But the argument against policies which neglect or damage children is not one of 'special pleading'. <b>Damage to children means damage to society as a whole.</b> 
<p>

Childhood is a vital window of opportunity not only for the individual child's development, but for society as a whole. 
<b>Considerable evidence exists that investing in childhood can generate enormous long-term benefits, among them:
<ul>
<li>a happier and more integrated population
<li>a better trained and more productive population
<li>less wastage, such as educational drop-out
<li>lower delinquency
<li>lower expenditure on welfare and social services</b>
</ul>
<p>
By contrast, failure to invest in childhood both denies individuals the opportunity to reach their full potential <i>and</i> has a massive impact on society's own capacity to develop. 
<p>
It deprives children of their right under the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child to: "a standard of living adequate for the child's physical, mental, spiritual, moral and social development". In so doing, it produces societies which are less likely to be well integrated, well educated and productive, and with greater problems of meeting social and welfare budgets.
<p>
<b>Development policies which ignore or damage children's interests are therefore a failure not only on moral grounds but <i>even on their own, largely economic and social terms.</i></b>
<p>
It is for this reason that policy-makers'attitude towards children can be seen as a <b>litmus test</b> of their attitude to social development. It is a test which the documents to be discussed at Copenhagen do not pass.
<hr>
<h3>
4. The Invisibility of Children</h3>

In the policies to be discussed at the Social Summit, as with previous development models, children are invisible. This may be surprising, given the emphasis on social <b>integration and participation.</b> But Save the Children (UK)'s research has discovered that when policy-makers address development:
<ul><li>there is little information or data available specifically related to children 
<li>children's positive and productive contributions to society's development are not recognised
<li>decision-makers see them only as dependents of adults, not individuals in their own right
<li>children are not consulted or expected to participate
</ul>
<p>
In short, <i>policy-makers actually know very little about children's real lives.</i> For example, in research, statistics, government reports and policy proposals children are usually described according to adult categories, often as members of 'households' or 'families'. 
<p>
This can be highly misleading. An increase in household income may not actually benefit the children within the household. Indeed, if it involves extra hours of employment for parents, the attention to children's needs and interests may decrease. 
<p>
Children's contribution to development is not recognised. The majority of children in developing countries 'work', in that they undertake activities which help the household's economic survival. In Brazil, children contribute up to 40 per cent of family income; in India 19 per cent. Children herd animals, fetch water and firewood, help in the fields, and care for other children within the family or community. These active contributions never appear in official figures.
<p>
If, in addition, children are rarely asked to participate or to express their views, this means adults make assumptions about them which are not based on evidence. 
<p>
Thus, <i>policy is made without reference to those whom it affects.</i> In any other sphere it would immediately be clear that any such policy would fail -- this remains unrecognised where children are concerned.
<p>
<b>Save the Children (UK) believes that the goals set out in the Social Summit Declaration will be achieved only if children and their needs, interests and perspectives are placed at the centre of social and economic policy, alongside and equal to those of adults.
<p>
If we wish to make a new start, to give 'social development and human well-being' the highest priority, policy-making can no longer treat children as invisible. A 'Children's Agenda' for development, both North and South, is an urgent necessity. </b>
<hr>
<h3>5. Towards a Children's Agenda</h3>


Save the Children (UK) is actively working towards a Children's Agenda. 

<p>
This will be a long term process, involving a whole range of groups and organisations, and of children themselves, whose participation in the design and implementation of projects is beginning to be explored. 
<p>

However, the outlines are becoming clear, and Save the Children (UK) issues the following call for action to all policy-makers:
<p>

<b>In order to move towards a Children's Agenda, Save the Children recommends that all decisions on social policy, practice and development should adhere to the following principles.</b>
<p>
<ul>
1.	The needs, rights, responsibilities, views and interests of children and adults are not necessarily the same.
<p>


2.	Children are 'social actors' in their own right. They make their own social, economic and cultural contribution to their communities.
<p>


3.	Children have a right to participate in the decisions which affect them, giving informed consent to the fullest extent possible in line with their age, abilities and culture.
<p>


4.	Society must share responsibility with parents for giving every child an equal start in life, and for investing in future generations of adults.
<p>


5.	Families are the basic unit of care, nurturing and support for children, but government and society must support them in these tasks. 
<p>


6.	Child-focused policy and practice must not penalise children. It must ensure that the impact of policy on children is foreseen and beneficial.
<p>


7.	Child-centred policy and practice must be informed by child-centred information and data.
<p>


8.	Different historical, cultural and subcultural traditions of childhood should be recognised and respected -- without endorsing discrimination, exploitation, repression or the waste of potential.
<p>

9.	All development policy and practice should adopt an holistic approach to children's needs.
<p>

10.	Children's needs and capacities vary with age. Social policy and practice should address all age groups, including young people in their teens.
</ul><hr>
<h3>

CHILDREN 'S PLACE IN DEVELOPMENT</h3>

<p>

The importance of putting children at the centre of development thinking may become clearer by using the following, imperfect parallel.
<p>

It is now recognised by all development planners including governments, UN agencies and non-governmental organisations that development policy will fail unless it fully recognises the specific position of women within societies and social groups.  This was not always so: a revolution in thinking has occurred over the last 30 years.
<p>

Children remain in the position of women 30 years ago in many respects:
<ul><li>
they are invisible in policy-making and not counted in statistics and research
<li>policies are made 'in their best interests' without consulting them
<li>they receive different and unequal treatment, often oppressive
<li>they suffer disproportionately from social adjustment and inequalities in opportunity and well-being
<li>they are seen as unproductive
<li>they are seen as dependent on powerful others, not as social actors
<li>they are denied participation in decision-making
</ul><p>

The parallel is imperfect because childhood is a different state to gender. The boundary between children and adults is less clear than that between women and men; childhood is not a permanent state; and children's ability to take a full part in decision-making is limited by other factors than social position -- such as parental rights and biological immaturity.
<p>

What the parallel does show is how profound and radical a shift in all thinking about social development is required -- if we truly want social development to work.
<hr>


<a name="back"></a>
<h3>Background</h3>

<h3>The World Summit for Social Development</h3>
<p>


The World Summit for Social Development (Social Summit) will take place from 6-12 March 1995 at the Bella Centre in Copenhagen. It was established by UN General Assembly Resolution 47/92 in December 1992

<h3>Focus and Structure</h3>
The Summit represents a call for "social development and human well-being " to be given "the highest priority both now and into the twenty first century" (Draft Declaration 26 January 1995).  To do this it will focus on

<ul><li>the alleviation and reduction of poverty
<li>measures to increase productive employment
<li>measures to promote social integration 
</ul><p>

The Summit comprises two parts: an expert Conference (6-10 March) and a heads of state/ heads of government Summit (11-12 March)

<h3>Documentation</h3>
Two documents will form the basis of discussion at the Conference and agreement at the Summit: the Declaration and the Programme of Action.
<p>

The Draft Declaration sets out a series of key principles. These include the importance of policies which "empower people to strengthen their own capacities, resources and opportunities", the interdependence of economic and social development, and the importance of democracy and human rights. 
<p>

The Draft Declaration's nine commitments are elaborated in the Draft Programme of Action:
<ul><p>

1.	An enabling economic, political, social, cultural and legal environment, conducive to social development
<p>
2.	The eradication of poverty
<p>
3.	The right to work and to secure and sustainable livelihoods for all people
<p>
4.	The promotion of social integration by fostering stable, safe, and just societies
<p>
5.	Full equality and equity between men and women, and enhanced participation for women.
<p>
6.	Promoting economic, social and human resource development of Africa and least developed countries
<p>
7.	Ensure that structural adjustment programmes include social development goals
<p>
8.	Increase significantly and/or use more efficiently resources asigned to social development
<p>
9.	A strengthened framework for international cooperation for social development
</ul><h3>
NGO Forum</h3>
The Social Summit will be paralleled by a Forum of Non-Governmental Organisations, which will be held  at the former naval base on Holmen in Copenhagen. 

<hr>
This article first appeared in a <b>Save the Children Fund</b> press release, Sunday 5th 1995<br>
©Copyright Save the Childen Fund
