<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<hr>

<H2><center><p></a>

The Week in Europe, 9 January 1997</h2>

<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>

<p>

Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>

</center>

<hr>

<P>

On Tuesday last (January 8) the European Commission imposed safeguard

measures restricting the volume of rice exported from the ACP (principally

Guyana and Suriname) arriving in Europe via the Overseas Countries and

Territories (OCT) route through the Netherlands Antilles, Turks & Caicos

and Montserrat.  They did so in response to a formal request from Italy,

itself a rice producer, which together with other southern European rice

producing states had become alarmed at increasing volumes of rice appearing

on the European market from the ACP and other sources.

<p>

The Italian request began life, in part, as a tactical measure to try to

force the Dutch government into accepting an Irish proposal to limit ACP

exports by establishing annual quotas for the OCT route (about which more

later). But the safeguard proposals have now become one measure in what is

likely to be a much broader battle, in which five EU member states and the

Agriculture Directorate of the European Commission seek to limit rice

imports from third countries into Europe. Their fear is, that the supply

from outside Europe has increased so dramatically that it will exceed EU

domestic demand, thereby causing the EC to take between 250,000 - 300,000

tonnes of EU produced rice into intervention at the expense of the European

tax payer.

<p>

The history of how this situation has arisen is, to say the least,

complicated. Scarcely four weeks ago it seemed that the then Irish

Presidency of the EU had established a compromise acceptable to all member

states bar one on the much-debated trade aspects of the EU/OCT agreement.

<p>

Under the OCT/EU relationship, which forms part of the Lom&#233; Convention,

products from the ACP which undergo certain transformation in the OCT enter

Europe quota and duty-free. This facility was first used by Guyana and

Suriname for rice and, just as intended, it has had a developmental effect

in the OCT and in the ACP nations concerned. However more recently this

route has begun to be used for sugar from the Dominican Republic, dairy

products, and a range of other sensitive items.

<p>

Faced with this - and subject to a discussion on numbers - the EC, all but

one member state, and the ACP rice producers accepted that a system would

have to be established to set quotas on specific products exported to

Europe in this manner. But the solution required unanimity and the Dutch,

for reasons that are no longer clear, were not prepared to work with other

member states on an acceptable compromise. To the anger of all other EU

nations, Dutch intransigence in a General Affairs Council meeting led to

the Irish compromise not being agreed and the issue remaining unresolved.

<p>

If this had simply resulted in the status quo prevailing, ACP producers

could have slept, if not easily, then without too much discomfort. But what

materially changed the circumstances was a parallel action by Italy to

introduce safeguard measures. Although the Italian position was probably

tactical initially with the objective of encouraging Dutch agreement in the

General Affairs Council, the absence of agreement to the Irish compromise

led directly to a decision to proceed to demand the imposition of safeguard

measures.

<p>

Apparently sensing that their stalling was likely to be damaging to their

own interests, if the result were safeguard measures, the Dutch, just

before Christmas, began to indicate their willingness to compromise on the

trade aspects of the OCT/EU review if EU member states were prepared to:

keep the OCT/ACP trade route open after the Lom&#233; Convention expires;

compensation was offered to owners of mills in the OCT; quotas proposed by

the Irish were increased slightly; and clarification was provided on

certain technical issues proposed by the EC. But this was not enough to put

off those EU member states angry with the Dutch and the ever-increasing

volume of other commodities transiting the OCT, from forging ahead with

safeguard measures.

<p>

So what does all this mean for the small rice farmer in ACP who quite

understandably has planted in the expectation of continuing access to

Europe via the OCT?

<ul>

<li>Firstly exports of ACP rice by this route will be severely limited as the

safeguard quota of 42,650 tonnes per quarter is only about half of existing

export levels if annualised. Moreover quotas allocated for Turks and Caicos

(1328 tonnes) and Montserrat (4594 tonnes) may possibly mean that one or

both routes may close as there is some suggestion that these figures are

below what is commercially viable for the mills concerned. The end result

may therefore be an unseemly battle between millers in the Netherlands

Antilles to see who can ship the most rice by the earliest date, thereby

further dislocating the market in Europe; 

<p>

<li>secondly the whole issue is likely to become highly political in the

Caribbean as the implications of the removal of this successful development

measure becomes apparent on the economies of ACP rice-producing nations;

and

<p>

<li>thirdly in Europe itself further Dutch intransigence  on this issue will

not be welcome while they hold the EU Presidency and have to deal with

immensely more weighty questions on the future of Europe. It may also mean

the early introduction of safeguard measures on sugar and other commodities

using this route through the Netherlands Antilles.

</ul><p>

What  this appears to point to is a possible compromise solution through

early agreement on the much debated OCT/EU dossier in a manner that allows

for sensible quotas for rice and other commodities passing through the OCT.

If such a solution can be found in conjunction with the planned tariff cuts

for ACP rice reaching Europe by the direct route, ACP rice farmers and the

millers in the OCT will have a workable solution.

<p>

What is now required is for the Caribbean Governments' concerned, in

conjunction with their rice industries and representatives of the least

developed OCT's (Turks & Caicos and Montserrat) to make clear in every

possible way, that the issue is a political one requiring a workable

solution to be found as a matter of urgency.

<p>

<HR>

