<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Week in Europe</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<hr>

<H2><center><p></a>

The Week in Europe, 2 January 1997</h2>

<h4>by <i>David Jessop</i>

<p>

Executive Director of the <A HREF="cce.htm">Caribbean Council for Europe</A></h4>

</center>

<hr>

<P>

It is no exaggeration to say that 1997 will be the most critical year in

the history of the Europe/Caribbean relationship since Britain decided to

become a member of the European Community, thereby changing its

relationship with the Caribbean irrevocably. 

<p>

This year will be the one in which inter-European politics will decide the

structure of the future relationship between the Caribbean and Europe. This

will not be by any considered  action relating to the Caribbean alone, but

as a result of decisions that will be taken on the way in which Europe sees

its own future and its ties with the wider world. How the Caribbean or

individual nations in the region choose to interest Europe in their future

will determine whether a new form of special relationship can be

established or whether the Caribbean is to see its identity increasingly

subsumed into that of the Americas.

<p>

The most obvious issue in Europe in 1997, when seen from a Caribbean

perspective, is the negotiation of a successor agreement to Lom&#233; IV which

will be the subject of many more column inches as the year proceeds.

Suffice it to say at this time, the European Commission has produced its

discussion document, and Germany, the UK, Holland, France and Spain have

all either developed post Lom&#233; positions or are finalising them. As a

result Europe will have debated and completed its approach by  either the

end of the Dutch Presidency in June, or most probably the start of the

Luxembourg Presidency in the second part of the year.

<p>

Of less apparent impact, but of much greater potency in the long term will

be the inter-European debate that will take place in the first six months

of this year on revisions to the Maastricht Treaty during the EU's Inter

Governmental Conference (IGC). This Heads of Government meeting will

establish the basis on which the mechanisms that will govern Europe in the

future, can be made more manageable and responsive. At the heart of these

discussions will be proposals to change the voting system in Ministerial

meetings to a simple majority vote; the strengthening of decision making by

the European Commission and other EU institutions; and the enlargement of

the Union to include nations of Central and Eastern Europe.

<p>

It is enlargement that is providing the stimulus to the IGC discussions as

it is apparent in most European capitals that unless decision making is

simplified, future expansion to a Europe of 25 nations will be impossible

and the Union will become unmanageable. The debate is critical to the

future of the Union and implies for some states, such as Germany and the

Netherlands, political reforms that point to the need to move to a more

federalist approach. But whatever happens to the detail during the

negotiations no one should have any doubt that enlargement will proceed. To

do otherwise would be to loose an historic prize for western Europe, namely

its re-consolidation following the collapse of the Soviet Union and the

ending of the cold war. 

<p>

While this is desirable from a European perspective this will create new

uncertainties for the Caribbean. Not only will enlargement cause the EU to

become even more remote from former partners but will also demand the

reconstruction of the EU's Common Agricultural Policy and internal

financing so as to accommodate significantly poorer economies of eastern

Europe. Such changes early in the next millennium- now just three years

away - will almost certainly change the nature of the EU's trade

relationship with the Caribbean, even if the WTO and post the Lom&#233; debate

do not.

<p>

The final shape of the IGC proposals, or the highly contentious issue of

European Monetary Union (EMU) the criteria for which have to be met this

year by  EU member states, will lead to a new balance of power in Europe.

In this regard the position taken by the Anglophone Caribbean's traditional

friend in Europe, the United Kingdom may well determine whether it becomes

an outsider in the European debate.

<p>

A general election is expected by May 1 in Britain and it seems

increasingly probable that the outcome may well be determined by the

position the two main parties take on  future relations with Europe.

Politics aside, this will have a direct and indirect term impact on the

Caribbean's future relations with Europe.

<p>

The signs are that the Conservative government, which has opposed changes

to future EU voting in Council meetings, any further strengthening of the

Commission and has fudged the question of membership of the EMU, is likely

to take a strident anti- European posture during the election campaign.

This means that if the present Conservative Government were to win again,

it may well have alienated most of its colleagues in Europe just at the

moment the Caribbean will need its support and leadership on a post Lom&#233;

relationship. This may be compounded by the fact that a future Conservative

government is likely to be dominated by a new intake of  young right of

centre Conservative members dedicated to an Atlanticist approach, the

introduction further market oriented policies that for example see no role

for preference and the semi-detachment of the UK from its European

neighbours. 

<p>

Alternatively a Labour win may well make Britains role in Europe a central

part of its foreign relations strategy and as a part of this a position of

leadership on a post Lom&#233; accord. However, not only is this less certain if

Britain's membership of the Union comes to dominate the election campaign,

but no one in the region should have any illusions that new Labour's

policies will be pragmatic and like its Conservative counterpart, aimed at

ensuring a secure Europe.

<p>

European Governments, the European Parliament, the European Commission and

most others return to their offices on January 6 after a long Christmas and

New Year's break.  Pressing issues that will be back on the daily agenda

include: the WTO and bananas; proposed safeguard measures to limit ACP

Caribbean rice exports;  relations with Cuba; the Helms Burton

legislation; the development of the debate on a post Lom&#233; relationship; and even the obscure matter of  how to establish a nomenclature for Trinidad lake asphalt. But it will be a wider range of positions emerging, as the year proceeds, from the inter-European debate that will determine the real shape of the Caribbean's future  relationship with Europe.

<p>

<HR>

