<html>
<head>
<title>Gemini: Peace moves as water disputes head for boil</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<br><i> The material that follows has been provided by </i> <b><a href="gemini_info.html">  Gemini News Service</a></b>
<hr>
<h3>PEACE MOVES AS WATER DISPUTES HEAD FOR BOIL</h3>
<i>
If wars over water become common next century, as environmental doomsters 
predict, the Nile basin is a possible troublespot. The basin's 10 countries, 
reports <b>Gemini News Service</b>, are taking the first steps to sort out their 
conflicting demands.<p>


By <b>CRESPO SEBUNYA</b>,<br>
Kampala </i><hr><p>


A new World Bank report on the dangers of water conflicts in North Africa and 
the Middle East comes in the wake of a conference that spotlighted the Nile 
basin as a potential flashpoint.<p>

The Bank's recipe for averting "looming crisis" is a reduction of subsidies, 
greater efficiency in irrigation and diversion of water away from low-value 
agriculture towards cities and people.<p>

It looks to investment of up to $60 billion in the North Africa-Middle East 
region over the next decade. This, it says, would increase water supplies by 50 
per cent and avoid disputes.<p>

Dispute-avoidance was also the underlying concern of the Nile waters 
conference.<p>

Within hours of the opening of the Kampala meeting, a Ugandan participant 
accused Egypt of acting like colonial masters determined to preserve the status 
quo regardless of the interests of sub-Saharan Africa: "I think we are entitled 
to some form of compensation," he said.<p>

His charge was based on arguments that Egypt and Sudan consume an unfairly 
large amount of the river's waters after being given the right by colonial 
Britain to veto all major developments along the Nile, which Egypt regards as 
its lifeblood.<p>

When Ethiopia announced a plan to divert water from the river in the 1980s, 
for example, Cairo threatened military retaliation. The proposal was dropped 
immediately.<p>

The veto policy, explained Egyptian legal scholar Dr Aziza Fahmi, stemmed from 
the view that the North African states were more dependent on the river than 
were African countries with their rain-fed agriculture: "This created servitude 
in favour of Egypt as against the upper riparian states," said Dr Fahmi.<p>

But economic development in all 10 countries in the Nile basin - Burundi, 
Egypt, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya, Rwanda, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda and Zaire - is 
placing increasing demands on all available water resources.<p>

"The Nile is a gift from God for all of us," said Uganda's Water and Natural 
Resources Minister Henry Kajura. "Every country has a right to use the 
resource, and no country should have veto power over the rest and hinder their 
beneficial use of the resource."<p>

Uganda's concern for the river has grown because of climatic changes. "We are 
all concerned by the recent climate trends," said Kajura. "We have been 
experiencing recurrent drought which tends to be more severe and prolonged and 
which, coupled with poor environmental management and rising population, is 
making the Ugandan environment increasingly fragile and threatening the social 
livelihood of the people."<p>

Uganda criticises Egypt for sticking to those parts of historic agreements 
that are in its favour, but ignoring other aspects of river-sharing, such as 
compensating Uganda for its role as a reservoir for the Nile waters.<p>

Not all conflicts are between sub-Saharan and Arab countries, although that 
ethnic divide is potent. Last year, some Kenyans said that expansion of 
Uganda's Owen Falls dam had caused a drop in the level of Lake Victoria, 
affecting water supplies to several Kenyan towns.<p>

Denying the allegation, Ugandan officials attributed the drop in the lake to 
the rapid spread of the water hyacinth which, they said, was increasing 
evaporation rates.<p>

To sort out such disputes, an International Nile Basin Association is being 
established.<p>

"We hope the headquarters will be functioning fully with a secretariat before 
the end of 1998," said P. Kahangire, chairman of the conference organising 
committee and Uganda's Director of Water Development.<p>

A technical committee is already in existence, charged with helping countries 
make effective and equitable use of the river's waters.<p>

The 10 countries have been asked to draw up national water action plans for 
integration in the proposed $100 million Nile Basin Development Plan, which is 
currently unfunded.<p>

"It is an ambitious project," admitted Fathy El Gamal, water resources planner 
for the technical committee. But he expressed optimism over the commitment of 
the governments concerned.<p>

To achieve real results, economic cooperation may be needed, and that has 
proved elusive in the past.<p>

Egyptian diplomats in Kampala say their country is considering ways of cutting 
water use. One suggestion is for Egypt to reduce its grain output and increase 
imports from countries up-river, while stepping up industrial production and 
exports to its near neighbours. But the conference was also told that Egypt has 
plans for irrigating a further 1.5 million hectares of land.<p>

Another proposal up for consideration is that Uganda should expand its 
hydropower output. It already supplies electricity to Kenya, Tanzania and 
Rwanda. Zaire and Sudan could theoretically be added to the list of buyers, but 
only if huge political, financial and technical problems can be resolved. <p>
<hr>

About the Author: <b>CRESPO SEBUNYA</b> is a freelance Ugandan journalist who 
formerly worked for Business World in Kampala.
<p>

Copyright: News-Scan International Ltd (1996)     22/3
<hr>
