<head>
<title>Gemini - Planners aim for 'a little Taiwan' in the jungle</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<br><i> The material that follows has been provided by </i> <b><a href="../gemini_info.html">  Gemini News Service</a></b>
<hr>
<h3>PLANNERS AIM FOR 'A LITTLE TAIWAN' IN THE JUNGLE</h3>
<i>
Plans for a land bridge across Mexico to rival the Panama Canal and cash in
on global trade are being welcomed by business interests. But critics,
reports <b>Gemini News Service</b>, point to the dire threat to a largely unspoilt
tropical forest and its indigenous inhabitants.
<p>


By <b>JOHN ROSS</b>,<br>
26 July 1996,<br>
Mexico City      </i><hr><p>




Mexico is hoping to cash in on economic globalisation by creating "a little
Taiwan" - in an area containing the country's last great tropical forest.<p>

Whereas the government sees international success - a chance to make the
country a link between the Asian "Tigers" and consumer markets in the
United States - environmentalist Miguel Angel Garcia sees local disaster.<p>

"This proposal is a death sentence for these forests," he warns, "and
Mexico can't live without them."<p>

Supporters describe the plan to drive a transport corridor through the
Tehuantepec isthmus as a brilliant opportunity to tap growing world trade.<p>

They say the Atlantic-Pacific link could both rival and relieve the
congested Panama Canal.<p>

The building of road and rail links could also pave the way for large-scale
industrial development in the narrow neck of Mexico. "This could become a
Taiwancito," gushed a government official.<p>

But critics say that such an outcome could be disastrous for the
Chimilapas, the forest that covers much of the isthmus, and the 12,000
Zoque Indians who live there.<p>

"These plans will reduce the Chimilapas to the size of a park," says
Garcia. "They'll probably give us a golf course," he quips blackly,
referring to another community's struggle against a controversial sports
project in Morelos state.<p>

Teeming with tapirs, toucans, ocelots, jaguars and rare flora and fauna,
the 18,000 square kilometres of Chimilapas mountain and lowland jungles
straddle an area that has for centuries been eyed as the site of a canal or
land bridge between oceans.<p>

The Aztecs, Spanish and North Americans all sought to develop Tehuantepec
trade routes.<p>

In 1907, a 303-kilometre single-track railway was built, and oil pipelines
were constructed in the 1970s with the help of Japanese investors keen to
tap Mexico's oil boom.<p>

A Tehuantepec canal is currently ruled out on cost and technical grounds.
But proposals for a land bridge have now been drawn up by the department of
Mexico's Secretary of Communications and Transport (SCT) at a time when the
government is selling off railways and port facilities as part of a major
privatisation drive.<p>

Detailed plans have not been published, but a four-lane highway between
Veracruz and Oaxaca is already scheduled for completion by 2000 to
facilitate road haulage between coasts.<p>

Rail privatisation could herald two-way container trains. More than 80
transport companies will start bidding in August for the concessions on
five routes - of which the Tehuantepec line is the plum attraction.<p>

Big commercial rewards are guaranteed for whoever picks up the line and the
port facilities at either end. Time-saving is a key feature of the
Tehuantepec route: unloading, transporting, and reloading between oceans is
calculated to take 24 hours.<p>

Cuitlahuac Morales, port director at Salina Cruz, says that use of the
route will cut days off comparative journey times through the Panama Canal
where more than 60 vessels have to wait in line.<p>

With this in mind, Salina Cruz is building storage yards to hold 80,000
containers.<p>

The SCT is also understood to be proposing the siting of new assembly
plants on the Pacific-side Tehuantepec plain, touting the region for its
cheap labour and the abundant hydroelectric power that future dams on
Chimilapas rivers could provide.<p>

Commented a leading national financial newspaper, El Financiero: "The
development and concession of the Tehuantepec corridor is the most
important strategic decision (Mexico's President Ernesto) Zedillo will take
during his six-year term."<p>

Transforming the isthmus into a land bridge is of vital strategic
importance to transnational interests competing in a global economy, says
Andres Barreda, a strategic resources investigator at the Autonomous
University of Mexico.<p>

It will improve links between production centres in eastern Asia and prime
consumer markets in the southern and eastern US and the Midwest. Oil flows
will also benefit.<p>

Environmentalist Garcia believes the proposed commercial corridor will open
up the forest to private exploitation - posing a big threat to the
Chimilapas and the Zoques, who have long sought to defend their land from
timber firms and other commercial interests.<p>

Garcia, assisted by a World Wide Fund for Nature grant, has been seeking to
bring the Chimilapas' 34 agrarian communities together in a pact with the
Zoques to boost conservation efforts. In the past, they have managed to
curb road-building and the burning of woods for new farmland. "Every road
built represents a loss of resource," he says.<p>

The projected industrial boom will poison the air and drain rivers on the
Atlantic side if dams are built to siphon off hydroelectricity for Pacific
coast development, he says. And a big influx of job-seekers "will bring us
everything the neo-liberal social pathology dictates: prostitution,
alcoholism, inflation, contamination". - GEMINI NEWS




<hr>

About the Author: <b>JOHN ROSS</b> is a poet-journalist-activist who has been
covering Mexico for 30 years. He was named a winner of the 1995 American
Book Award for his book, Rebellion From The Roots - Indian Uprising in
Chiapas.<p>


 Copyright: News-Scan International Ltd (1996)     26/7
 
 <hr>
<p>

