<html>

<header>

<title>The "European initiative": Cooperation between advisory councils at European

level</title>

</header>

<hr>

<H2><center><p></a>

The "European initiative":<br>Cooperation between advisory councils at European

level</h2>

<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>

<p>

Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No. 10, March 1995</h4>

<p>

</center>

<hr>

<h3>The beginnings</h3>



In 1991 the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) provided the

initiative for cooperation between European advisory bodies in the field of development

cooperation. A workshop was held, at which it became clear that the participants were interested

in continuing this form of contact. One important point to emerge was that the agendas of the

different countries were largely the same - further evidence that coordination could enhance the

impact of national advisory work. The European Commission was also convinced of this fact and

twice invited the advisors to Brussels to give their advice on the implications of the Maastricht

Treaty which, in its provisions on development cooperation, envisages a greater role for European

cooperation. Subjects with a European dimension also occupy an important place in the NAR's

regular advisory activities.

<p>

<h3>Workshop in Feldafing, FRG (November 1994)</h3>



In the run-up to the follow-up meeting, the NAR commissioned a <A HREF="nar_adv.htm">study of the advisory structure

in 17 European countries</A>. This revealed that external policy advice is obtained in a wide variety of

ways in the different countries. The countries of northern Europe tend to opt for advice 'at arm's

length' from a body that is independent and has a fixed structure (a council), while southern

European administrations seem to prefer to obtain advice on each subject individually, on a contract

basis and with various partners. One important conclusion drawn from the study is that

cooperation on the basis of pragmatic considerations would seem to offer the best chance of

success.

<p>

The study was welcomed by delegates at the follow-up meeting, which the FRG organised during

its presidency of the European Union. The Wissenschaftliche Beirat beim Bundesministerium

f&uuml;r wirtschaftliche Zusammenarbeit und Entwicklung which hosted the meeting had taken the

lead with the drawing up of a joint advisory report entitled The <A HREF="nar_comp.htm">Comparative Effectiveness and the

Coordination Efforts of EU Donors</A>.The report, which was drawn up by a team of three authors,

from Germany, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom, explores the scope for improving aid

(policy, procedures, instruments, evaluation etc.) by cooperating at European level. It was

approved by the meeting and subsequently presented by the delegates to their overseas aid

ministers. The Council of Ministers of the EU discussed the same subject shortly afterwards.

<p>

The NAR contribution to the report consisted of a <A HREF="hoeb95.htm">comparative study of the effectiveness and

evaluation efforts of EU donors</a>. The Council has since  published this contribution separately.

<p>



<HR>

