<html>

<header>

<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>

</header>

<hr>

<h3><center><p>

Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy:<br> A Survey in 17 European Countries

</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by the European Centre for Development Policy Management (ECDPM) on behalf of the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) in the Netherlands. The full-text of this report is broken up into an <A HREF = "#intro">introduction</a>, a series of <a href="../country.htm">country</a> sections, and a <a href="adv_syn.htm">synthesis</a> chapter.

<p>

 

<h5>Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis. 1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen European Countries.</i> The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The report is available from the NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The Hague, the Netherlands. (e-mail: <a href="mailto:nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl"> nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</a>).

</h5>

 Acronyms can be checked by clicking on  <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"></a>

<p>

<hr><h3><a name="intro">Introduction</a></h3>

This report describes in broad terms the possibilities for cooperation between Advisory Councils for Development

Cooperation, including other institutions that may have an advisory function for development cooperation policy in

the current 12 Member States of the EU as well as in the three new Member States, Norway, and Switzerland.

<p>

The report is the result of a one year survey carried out by the European Centre for Development Policy

Management (ECDPM) on behalf of the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) in the

Netherlands. The survey was conducted by Annemiek Kooij under a contract with ECDPM. The report was written by Annemiek Kooij and Ren&#233; Mevis, deputy secretary to the NAR.

<p>

In 1989, the Irish Advisory Council on Development Cooperation (the predecessor of the current Aid Advisory

Committee) and the NAR decided to initiate activities for cooperation between advisory institutions for

development cooperation policy in Europe. A need was felt to strengthen national advisory activities, and to

contribute to the strengthening of the coherence and coordination of EU development policy. 

<p>

In 1991, the idea was discussed in a workshop in The Hague, with participants from several advisory institutions in

Europe. The meeting was also attended by a representative of the Directorate General for Development Cooperation

(DG VIII) of the European Commission (NAR, 1992). Participants concluded that policy making on national as

well as on European level could benefit from coordinated or joint advisory efforts. It was decided that efforts for

cooperation should be continued. A subsequent NAR report on development cooperation after the Treaty of

Maastricht in 1993 recommended that one of the ways for cooperation was for members of several interested

advisory institutions in Europe to produce a joint report on a common theme (NAR, 1993).

<p>

In June and December 1993, DG VIII organised meetings to build up direct and bilateral contacts with experts and

researchers in EU Member States. These were attended by several members of Councils and institutes that were

also involved in the cooperation activities that resulted from the workshop held in the Hague. DG VIII clearly

focuses on gaining access to information and knowledge that is available in Europe for its policy-making. Both

initiatives run parallel, and sometimes they meet. This report might give some clues for a possible common future.

<p>

In 1993, NAR asked ECDPM to explore more detailed possibilities for further cooperation of advisory institutions

and structures for development cooperation. Terms of Reference were designed along the following lines:

<ol>

<li>To conduct a survey of existing advisory structures, of which the results could be discussed at a workshop.

<li>To collect and disseminate information among participants in the survey and among interested institutions,

concentrating on published recommendations. Where appropriate, the feasibility of publishing English summaries

of recommendations should be discussed, in order to facilitate future exchange of information among participants,

notably by NAR and ECDPM.

<li>To explore the feasibility of a follow-up meeting of the 1991 workshop in The Hague.

<li>To indicate ways for the continuation and strengthening of future cooperation.

</ol>

<p>

The survey would focus on Formal Advisory Institutions, i.e. Advisory Councils for Development Cooperation

Policy installed by the Government, and which have the explicit mandate to advise the Government on matters of

development cooperation policy. This definition does not take into account other characteristics, such as

procedures, right of initiative or actually performed functions; these were to be considered as secondary. 'Policy'

was defined as general development policy, excluding specific policies for sectors or countries. A Council can be

classified in this category when at least its mandate permits it to advise on general policy questions; actually it may

also cover other areas. These Institutions are described in this report under the paragraphs two of each country

report, headed 'Formal Advisory Institutions'. Other institutions that might have a policy advisory function are

described in the paragraphs three, 'Other Actors'.

<p>

NAR and ECDPM agreed further that in those countries where there are no Formal Advisory Institutions, leading

research institutes that may have a policy advisory function would be included in the survey. All advisory

institutions, structures and mechanisms in those countries are described under the heading 'Advisory Structures and

Mechanisms'. Research institutes were supposed to have expertise on issues that are essential both to policy

making by national Governments and by the EU institutions.



For the survey, literature on the 17 countries was studied and interviews were held with representatives of relevant

institutions in 14 countries (no interviews were held with institutions in Greece, Italy and Luxembourg).

<p>

In the country reports, Advisory Councils for Development Cooperation and other institutions that may have an

advisory function are described in their policy and administrative context. The last paragraphs connect with

advisory  aspects of the work of NGOs and other relevant groups in society. Country reports include descriptions

of: 1) development cooperation: history and support; policies and changes; administrative structures; policy

planning and coordination; policy papers; 2) advisory institutions and structures: history and tasks; membership;

procedures; agenda's and publications; 3) other actors: Parliament; NGOs; research institutes; private enterprise.

<p>

The final chapter summarises the main characteristics and trends observed in the description of development

cooperation policies and administrative structures, and it summarises and categorises the various advisory

structures. It concludes with an overview of possibilities for future cooperation between advisory institutions in

Europe. 

<p>

Many aspects of development cooperation are covered in the country reports. However, the authors have no

intention to be complete. Including an aspect serves to place advisory structures and their functioning in the

relevant context. The survey is not an evaluation. It intends to give a fair picture of structures and activities as they

are reported in documents and discussions. Naturally, all opinions expressed and observations reported are the

responsibility of the authors.

<p>

<h3>References</h3>

<p>

NAR. 1992. Workshop 'Development Cooperation Policy: Towards a European Advisory Approach?, November

1991: Synthesizing Report. The Hague: NAR.

<p>

NAR. 1993. Recommendation on Development Cooperation after the Treaty of Maastricht. The Hague: NAR.

<p>

<HR>

