<html>
<head>
<title>Summary of the findings of a recent review of World Bank supported agricultural extension projects</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#8fbc8f" link="#238e23" alink="#ooffoo" vlink="#4a766e">
<hr>
<h3>Summary of the findings of a recent review of World Bank supported agricultural extension projects</h3>
<p>
A recent review of 33 free-standing extension projects approved after 1977, plus a further 76 projects having an extension component, noted that the Training and Visit approach had been successful in the Green Revolution context providing that certain basic principles were met: clearly-defined farming systems; technology 'on the shelf', with a high B:C ratio; and complementary resources readily available, especially in irrigated areas.
<p>
However, outside favourable areas, the performance of T&V- based extension projects has generally been weak:
<p>
 - returns to extension are high only if prices are right and complementary services are available (including input supply); frequently these conditions are not met, especially in the more difficult environments; extension has generally been more successful as a component of wider projects which aim to meet at least some of these conditions;
<p>
- inadequate understanding of farming systems, and of farmers' opportunities and constraints (including their risk-aversion practices and coping strategies) commonly means that recommendations are inappropriate;
<p>
- the number of relevant messages for difficult environments is generally limited, and without a steady stream of new technologies, the marginal returns to successive visits by extensionists are likely to diminish rapidly; 
<p>
- current extension models (i.e. especially T&V) are generally too expensive to be fiscally sustainable beyond the duration of external credits;
<p>
- the specific needs, opportunities and constraints faced by women farmers have generally been neglected;
<p>
- the 'contact farmer' mechanism of T&V rarely works as well as intended, and group organisation has rarely been a recognised component of extensionists' activities. For both these reasons, the impact of T&V on human resource development has generally been weak.
<p>
Source: Purcell, D.L. (1993), <i>"Agricultural Extension Investment and International Development Institutions: is the World Bank on the right track?"</i> Paper presented to the Australian/Pacific Extension Conference, Queensland, Australia. October 12-14 1993.
<p>

<hr>
</body>
