<html>
<head>
<title>Men and their sexual and reproductive health</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3>
<i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="../ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i>
<br clear=left>

<hr>



<h1>Men and their sexual and reproductive health </h1>










<b>by Evert Ketting</b><p>




The current wave of interest in male involvement in family planning, sexual and reproductive health is not new. Since the late 1970s, the issue has repeatedly been discussed in the International Planned Parenthood Federation, in family planning associations and in other agencies interested in reaching men, particularly organizations which concentrate on vasectomy and on promoting condom use.  <p>




However, the adoption of the International Conference on Population and Development (ICPD) Programme of Action in 1994, which expanded the field of family planning to take in the whole area of sexual and reproductive health, has created renewed interest in the role, behaviour and needs of men. 
<p>



The rationales for male involvement and the approaches taken in male involvement initiatives have changed over the years. Initially, men were seen primarily as obstacles to female acceptance of family planning; now programmes tend to focus on men as partners, or as potential clients who have sexual and reproductive health needs themselves.
<p>



The following are some of the reasons given for giving more attention to male involvement.
<p>
<ul>


<li>	Men are more interested in reproductive health information than is often assumed. In fact, the strong focus on women in reproductive health programmes makes some men feel excluded, even though their role in it is obvious.<p>


	

<li>	Men have their own sexual and reproductive health needs and often these are not met. For example, men need knowledge of their own and their partner's sexuality; information about and treatment for the causes of infertility; information about the prevention of sexually transmitted disease (STD) and HIV infection; understanding about sharing decision making on reproduction with partners; and diagnosis and treatment of prostate diseases.<p>


	

<li>	Men are often more supportive of family planning than is generally thought. Recent Demographic and Health Surveys indicate that in most countries men's approval of family planning matches that of women.  However, women are often unaware of partners' positive attitudes, and so do not discuss the issue.<p>


	

<li>	About one-third of couples in developing countries use male contraceptive methods, or methods that require male cooperation. Yet only a small fraction of programme efforts is usually directed towards men.<p>


	

<li>	Reproductive health initiatives are generally more effective if there is better communication between spouses. Experiences from the field clearly show that educational programmes aimed at improving spousal communication are associated with better contraceptive use.<p>



<li>	Serious reproductive health problems, including transmission of STDs, adolescent pregnancy and unsafe abortion are often caused by a complete lack of knowledge and a poor sense of responsibility among male adolescents. These problems can be solved only if young men are effectively included in information, education and communication activities and if sexual and reproductive health services are made accessible to young men.</ul><p>




One objective of male involvement programmes has been to increase male acceptance of family planning, and has targeted three categories of people: the general population (in order to create a generally favourable social climate for male participation); political, religious and other male leaders (to create community support for male participation); men as partners (to reduce or remove their opposition to their wives adopting family planning). <p>




A second objective has been to increase the use of male contraceptive methods, and programmes here have centred on vasectomy, with a more recent additional emphasis, since the advent of HIV/AIDS, on condom use. Two further objectives have been to improve spousal communication on family planning and related subjects; and to meet the sexual and reproductive health needs of men. <p>




Some projects have been based on a combination of all four objectives. The male motivation programme carried out by the Zimbabwe National Family Planning Council between 1987 and 1991 is a good example of this.  Meeting the first two objectives dominated programmes started in the 1980s, while improving spousal communication has been given more emphasis in current programmes.  Identifying and responding to the needs of men has only just begun. <p>




There were, however, some early initiatives in which special services for men were offered: the Brazilian PRO-PATER clinic and the men's clinics of the Colombian FPA, Profamilia, are the most outstanding examples. Activities for men usually require completely new structures; unlike women, men cannot be reached through existing maternal and child health facilities. <p>




Male involvement initiatives so far have tended to use one of the following approaches.<p>

<ul>
 

<li>	Mass media campaigns, using the written press, radio and television. These campaigns are often supported by a variety of materials, such as leaflets, T-shirts, plastic bags, etc. Notable examples are the vasectomy promotion campaigns by PRO-PATER in Brazil during the 1980s, the Los Tromés campaign launched in Peru in 1992 which aims at encouraging communication between young couples, a national male motivation campaign in Bolivia started in 1994, and the Zimbabwe programme already mentioned. <p>


	

<li>	Providing information to men at their workplaces and, where health services are available, sometimes family planning services too. This approach has been extensively implemented in Africa, with examples in The Gambia, Ghana, Sierra Leone, Swaziland, and recently in Mauritius.  Workplaces include army barracks, police offices, the government, industrial centres, training institutes and bars and hotels.<p>


	

<li>	Community outreach to men has taken a variety of approaches, with direct contact between fieldworkers and men in the community the common denominator. Activities include formal and informal discussions, home visits, film and video shows, puppet shows, games, and also condom distribution and referral to clinics. Good examples of this approach are found in Mardan in the north-west of Pakistan, in Mali's Katibougou project, in Swaziland's roadshows which include condom promotion games, and in Kenya, where puppet shows aim to motivate men on family planning and STD prevention. Another interesting example is a project of the Nigerian FPA in which traditional healers are trained to promote the use of non-prescriptive contraceptive methods.
<p>

	

<li>	Motivating and gaining the support of male community leaders. Men are influenced by the opinions of community leaders, particularly religious leaders, so this is an important approach, mostly undertaken through organizing seminars, training courses and informal meetings. The FPA of Bangladesh has worked with religious leaders for a long time, and a comparable project has been implemented in the Minya province in Egypt, where Muslim and Christian religious leaders were trained in family planning and community mobilization skills. Subsequently, these leaders conducted meetings with men in villages. A different example is found in Tanzania, where the family planning association (UMATI) has worked extensively with political leaders at national and local levels, and with members of parliament, since the early 1980s.</ul><p>




The current growing interest in programmes directed towards men can be interpreted as a response to the need to balance the strong concentration on women's reproductive health during the past decade. The reality remains, however, that women carry a far greater burden of reproductive morbidity and mortality, and of the physical and social responsibility for fertility and its consequences, than men. Reproductive health initiatives directed towards men therefore should not just concentrate on benefits for men themselves, but also on the needs of women. <p>




At the same time, experience suggests that it is often neither realistic nor very effective to approach men as just irresponsible, uncaring and uninterested. Men should be approached as responsible partners. They also have their own particular needs, such as sexual education for young men, education and services promoting safer sex practices, sharing responsibility for child care, and counselling and treatment for sexual problems, dysfunctions and diseases.<p>




Pointers for the future include the need for information programmes that portray men as caring husbands and fathers, and that stress the benefits of shared family responsibility for both men and women; a need to improve the image of male contraceptives and of male contraceptive use; sexual health education and special services for adolescent men; special clinic hours for men and creation of an atmosphere in clinics that appeals to men; and more research into men's special sexual and reproductive health needs.<p>














 
