<header>

<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>

</header>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Spain</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the

National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.

<br> 

<h5> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.

1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen

European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The

report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The

Hague, the Netherlands.

</h5>

<hr>

<h3>Contents:</h3>

<ul>

<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Spanish Development Cooperation</a>

<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>

<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>

<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>

<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"></a>

</ul><p>



<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Spanish Development Cooperation</h3>



Spanish development assistance is closely related to historical and linguistic relations and cultural activities

in Latin America, as well as to Spanish commercial interests, and to geographic proximity and migratory

pressures from Northern Africa. Official Spanish development cooperation started in 1985, when the first

aid programme was initiated. NGO development activities date back to the 1950s and even the 1940s. In

1983 Spain was removed from the DAC list of developing countries. The country became a member of

DAC in December 1991. The public is concerned with domestic problems of high unemployment, economic

recession, immigration, and racism. However, in a recent opinion poll 65 per cent of the public declared

itself in favour of raising the aid budget to 0.7 per cent of GNP, a target requested by a Parliamentary

report in 1992. Parliamentary support for development cooperation is quite strong, in contrast to the actual

measures taken by the Government.

<p>

Net official development assistance in 1992 stood at US $ 1 518 million, corresponding with 0.26 per cent

of GNP, after a period of decline in the 1980s. Forecasts for 1993 and 1994 are around 0.24 per cent of

GNP. After a considerable rise in multilateral contributions, they fell to 0.25 in 1992. The greater part, 0.20

per cent of total ODA, went to the EU budget and the EDF. The EU-share was the second most important

component of ODA in 1992, after the concessional official export credits through the FAD (Fondo de

Ayuda al Desarrollo), which reached 56 percent of ODA in 1992.

<p>

<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>

<p>

Spanish development cooperation still lacks a unified development concept, a centralised aid budget and the

corresponding administrative structures. Government development cooperation structures are relatively

young and their staff has limited experience. 

<p>

A law establishing a legislative basis for development cooperation, will probably be voted by Parliament

during 1994. Until now development cooperation is based on ad hoc administrative rules, although already

in 1984 the Senate approved a motion on international cooperation.

<p>

There is no Minister for Development Cooperation. The administration of Spanish aid is spread over a

dozen ministries, the Spanish Agency for International Cooperation (AECI, established 1988) and the

Institute for Official Credits (ICO). Each ministry has a separate aid budget. Autonomous regions and some

municipalities also have their own aid programmes, mostly implemented by NGOs. The Ministry for

Foreign Affairs (MFA) has a State Secretariat for International Cooperation and Latin America (SECIPI,

established 1985). It is responsible for the programming, control and evaluation of the aid programme of the

MFA, and it is in charge of the coordination of the aid activities by other ministries. Its role is nonetheless

rather limited, since it administers only a small share of the aid programme (10 per cent of ODA including

AECI's share in 1992, otherwise 2 per cent).

<p>

The largest share of reported Spanish ODA falls under the responsibility of the State Secretariat of Trade of

the Ministry of Commerce and Tourism (MCT). It deals with FAD's extensive loan programme which is

administered by the Institute for Official Credits, and with the contributions to international financing

institutions. Other multilateral contributions are mainly handled by the Ministry of Economy and Finance

(MEF).

<p>

The bilateral technical cooperation programme is designed and carried out by the Agency AECI directly, or

subcontracted to others. AECI is managed by a Governing Council and an Executive Committee. It receives

its funds from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs to which it is attached through SECIPI. AECI is organised

along geographical lines in three institutes, that can be compared with directorates-general: the Institute for

Iberian American Cooperation (ICI), responsible for Latin America and the Caribbean, the Institute for

Cooperation with Arab Countries (ICMA), in charge of cooperation with Arab countries and other countries

in the Middle East and North Africa, and the Institute for Development Cooperation (ICD), which covers

sub-Saharan Africa (mainly Portuguese speaking countries in Africa) and Asia. The ICD and the ICMA are

bound to merge in a current administrative reorganisation. Compared with 1989 AECI's budget for 1994 is

reduced by half.

<p>

The most important other ministries involved include Labour and Social Security, Education and Science,

Health, and Social Affairs.

<p>

To coordinate the various aid activities an Interministerial Commission for International Cooperation (CICI)

was established in 1986, chaired by the Foreign Minister, in which fourteen ministries are represented. The

CICI used to meet twice a year. In order to strengthen the role of the Commission, the number of meetings

has been increased, following the 1992 Parliamentary recommendations. CICI discusses the Annual Plan for

Development Cooperation (PACI), the inventory of activities and programmes for development cooperation

(not allocations or budgets) of all ministries involved. PACI is prepared by SECIPI's Planning and

Evaluation Office (OPE). These plans, after an elaborate procedure, are submitted for approval to the

Council of Ministers.

<p>

After preparation in various departments of the MCT, FAD credits are submitted to the Interministerial

FAD Commission (CIFAD), which meets about six times a year. Final approval is given by the Council of

Ministers. The Commission, chaired by the Ministry of Commerce and Tourism, is composed of senior

officials from several ministries, including MFA/SECIPI, Economy and Finance, Public Works and

Transport, Agriculture and Fisheries, Industry and Energy, and the Bank of Spain.

<p>

The Parliamentary report of 1992 envisages to strengthen the coordination of the various instruments of

Spanish aid. Although the MFA, SECIPI, and the Ministry of Commerce and Tourism are represented

already on both the CICI and the FAD Commission, and although recommendations of both commissions

need the approval of the Council of Ministers, coordination might be improved. 

<p>

Many internal consultation mechanisms do exist for day-to-day policy implementation. AECI's president is

in charge of the Emergency Aid Group, by which SECIPI coordinates emergency programmes. Members of

the Group are the Ministries of MFA, of Defense, of the Interior, and Health and Consumption, the Cruz

Roja, UNICEF, Caritas, and IBERIA. Supporting the conclusions of the 1992 Parliamentary Report, the

Government has taken steps to improve the use of the PACI as a planning instrument, to strengthen the role

of the CICI. In addition the CICI approved guidelines for Spanish development cooperation in February

1994, to be operational in 1995.

<p>

The annual budget plan PACI is published. SECIPI has an evaluation office OPE, and MCT has its own

evaluation system for FAD (mainly directed towards the verification of the proper use of funds). Evaluations

are not published. Planning, monitoring and evaluation procedures are to be revised and evaluation

frequencies stepped up. The State Secretariat of Commerce issues a magazine about Spanish development

cooperation, 'Informaci&#243;n Commercial Espa&#241;ola'.

<p>

<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>

<p>

There is no formal advisory structure in Spain. However, the Government considers the establishment of a

Consultative Council for Development Cooperation which would be composed of representatives of NGOs,

universities, trade unions, and industries. It would create a discussion platform on development cooperation

with relevant groups in Spanish society. From the side of the NGOs this plan is favoured by the

Coordinadora, a platform in which 70 NGOs are assembled.

<p>

The members of Parliament and the Foreign Affairs Committee of both houses of Parliament are well aware

of the problems in developing countries, of the Spanish administration's need for change, and they are

actively engaged in discussing the strengthening of the Spanish aid performance. Annually the Secretary of

State for Cooperation presents the Plan for Development Cooperation to the Foreign Affairs Commission.

<p>

<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>

<p>

There are about 200 Spanish NGOs active in the field of development assistance. They have their origins in

the Church, in professional organisations, in political and solidarity committees, and in trade unions. Some

of them raise a considerable amount of money from the public, far exceeding the amount received from the

Government. Spanish ODA channelled through NGOs has increased somewhat in the last years, but fell in

1992 to 2 per cent of total ODA. Funds are allocated on a project-by-project base, through annual

competitive bidding and a rather elaborate procedure. Half a dozen larger, experienced organisations receive

more than half of the official support. Most NGO activities are located in Latin America.

<p>

The NGOs, regrouped in a single platform, Coordinadora, with 70 members, want to be more involved in

policy discussions with the Government and in decision making. They are pleading for larger government

support, and for effective procedures and greater openness on official aid activities, in particular on FAD

credits. The Government intends to expand the cooperation with NGOs.

<p>

Trade unions recently have become more active in the field of development cooperation. The two largest

unions decided to set aside 0.7 per cent of the membership fees (one), or of all trade union income (the

other); they started awareness raising campaigns.

<p>

According to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey, 16 institutes in Spain qualify as Development Research and

Training Institutes. Some are involved in government development policy debates, studies or consultancy

work. Generally, government institutions are only allowed to contract outside consultants for a one time

period of 3 - 4 years.

<p>

<hr>

