<title>Oxfam News Summer 1996</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">

<h6>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="oxfam.html">OXFAM UK&I</a></h6><hr><p>


<h2 align=center>Sensational fax shames the UN </h2>

On 11 January 1994, three months before the start of the genocide in Rwanda, the UN Commander in Kigali, General Romeo Dallaire, sent New York a coded cable. It revealed that 1,700 troops from the Interhamwe Hutu militia were in Kigali. They had access to arms and were boasting that they could kill 1,000 Tutsis in 20 minutes. The scene was set for a terrible outburst of brutality. General Dallaire called for intervention but the UN chose not to respond.<p>
 
  Details of this fax came to light in March this year in a damning report, The International Response to Conflict and Genocide, which criticised the UN and donor governments for not acting to prevent tragedy in Rwanda. The report also criticised the UN for pulling out its troops once the genocide began; and for being indecisive about sending reinforcements to protect civilians. While it praised the aid effort, which responded to a series of crises of massive proportions, it criticised several aid agencies, whose performance was not up to the highest standards of care. Oxfam (UK and Ireland) and M&eacute;dicins Sans Fronti&egrave;res were highlighted as two agencies that responded to the crises with skill and professionalism. <p>

 
  <i>'The International Response to Conflict and Genocide: Lessons from the Rwanda Experience' was prepared by international specialists under the aegis of the Danish government's aid department, DANIDA.</i>


<p>

<br><br>
<font size=2>March 1994. Pre-geocide Rwanda. A UN soldier stands guard outside Kigali's parliament building where 600 RPF soldiers have been stationed as part of a power sharing agreement. Two weeks later, the killings began.</font><p>
<br clear=all>



<hr>

<center><h3>[<a href="index.html">Oxfam news contents</a>] [<a href="../index.html">Oxfam Home Page</a>]</h3><p>
<hr></center>


