<html><head><title>Crosslines: Why film-makers love to talk</title><!!keys: Crosslines+film festival+documentaries+Recontres Medias Nord-Sud+media></head><body><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="crosslines.html"> Crosslines Global Report</i></a><hr><h2>Why film-makers love to talk</h2><p><i><b>Rencontres Medias Nord-Sud  (North-South Media Encounters) </b>is afilm festival where people come talk about the problems ofdevelopment as well as to see some of the best documentariesmade for television. Now 10 years old, the four-day meeting on3-6 April in <a href="#geneva">Geneva* </a>offers some 120 films for viewing, alldealing with developing countries or development. But at thesame time, the Rencontres is organizing nine hours of debate onthe future of the United Nations, bringing in experts andcommentators who have put forward proposals for reform. By <b>Peter Hulm.</b></i><hr>The festival takes place in April because it used to be held inthe University of Geneva and that's when the University goes onholiday so the meeting rooms are available. <i>Rencontres MediasNord-Sud (RMNS)</i> is that sort of event. You won't find Coordinator TinaBoillat making grandiose assertions about its ambitions or itsimpact. The most she will claim is that "it is really four daysof dialogue". But RMNS (international Geneva makes you want toslip into a comfortable acronym as soon as you decently can) hasbuilt itself a solid reputation as a place for independent filmmakers to meet people from the television organizations(including buyers), and particularly for Third World directorsto show their wares. Tuesday morning, for example, on Africaoffers films from Niger, Iran, Togo, Madagascar, Sweden (onAfrica), Togo, Switzerland (Rwanda), France (AIDS in Africa) andArte (a personal African story) in quick succession.<p>The meeting's gradual and continuous evolution makes it difficultto describe anything about RMNS as being fixed: this year'ssessions take place for the first time in the Maison des Arts duGrutli and Fonction:Cinema is now a co-organizer. But howsignificant is this? It testifies more to the organizers' skillat using whatever opportunity comes up to strengthen support forthe event and make it better known. "We first went to the Valaisduring the 700th anniversary celebrations the SwissConfederation in 1991, because the authorities there were givenresponsibility for the audio-visual side of the event and wantedto do something about Switzerland's relations with the world,"explains Boillat.<p>The Grutli is Geneva's Cinetheque, and so (for the second time)RMNS is showing some of the films to the general public: "One ofaims is to make these films known, particularly the work ofindependents," Boillat stresses. "These people are making verygood films -- often better than the conventional companies --and they depend on events like ours."<p>Boillat, who took over the coordinating job five years ago afterhelping out before, sees one major change in the number of womenmaking documentaries in the Third World. "There are now manywomen directors, making films in incredible conditions," shesays. "A woman from Burkina Faso who has now become a regular atthe Rencontres was forced to edit her first film at nightbecause the facilities were reserved for the news broadcastersduring the day."<p>This year RMNS received more than 90 applicants for thecompetition for independent film-makers (of CHF4,000/over$3000), and finally accepted 39. Another 35 entries came frommainstream TV.  Recent winners of the top award (CHF5,000), theGeneva International Television Prize, have been <i>Battle of theTitans </i>by Danmarks Radio (1994), Central Television's <i>War byOther Means </i>(1993), Central Television's <i>Rivers of Sand </i>(1992),and Channel 4's <i>Lessons of Exile </i>(1991). This is not afrancophone/development event that practices linguisticchauvinism or UN political correctness through geographicdistribution of its rewards.<p>But, conversely, how many of the independent prizewinners havewe seen on Northern screens?  <i>Profissao:Domestica </i>by CECIP,Brazil, won the 1994 South-North Prize. INA (France)'s <i>La FlacaAlejandra </i>won the Independents' Prize. In 1993 the winners were<i>L'acces des femmes   la terre </i>(Burkina Faso) and TVE's <i>Lucia. </i>In1992 the Sud-Nord prize went to Colombia's <i>Saranda de sue os,</i>and in 1991 to Brazil's <i>Verde Verdade.</i><p>The chances are you haven't seen more than one or two. "I don'tthink that [rich world television stations] are taking less[from developing countries]," says Boillat. "They have nevertaken films from the South. But I'm sure that if buyers from theNorth saw these films they would buy them immediately. Thechallenge is to let them know what is available."<p><a name="geneva"></a><b>* There's a fifth day of ceremonies and showings in St Maurice(Valais) on 7 April.</b><p><hr>Contact: Tina Boillat, Coordinatrice, <a href="crosslines_rmns.html">Rencontres MediasNord-Sud, </a>Television suisse Romande, Case postale 234, CH-1211Geneva 8, Switzerland. Tel: +41(22)-708-81-93. Fax:+41(22)-328-94-10.<p><i><b>Peter Hulm</b> is a former English Editor of the Swiss FilmCatalogue. He has edited and translated several film andtelevision scripts.</i><p>©Copyright: Crosslines Global Report April 1995<hr><a href="index.html"><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo2.gif"> Crosslines Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
