<html><head><title>Crosslines - Humanitarian Reporting</title><!!keys: Crosslines+Herbert Giradet+humanitarian reporting></head><body><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo.gif"><br><i>The material that follows has been provided by</i> <a href="crosslines.html">Crosslines</a><hr><p><h2>Humanitarian reporting</h2><p><b>CROSSLINES Global Report</b> and the New York-based International League for Human Rights will co-host an exhibition of the works of Herbert Girardet, the Swiss-American painter who died last year. The exhibition will also mark the inauguration of a new media organization: The International Centre for Humanitarian Reporting (ICHR).<p>The ICHR will seek to encourage better coverage of humanitarian and human rights issues often neglected by the world media. In particular, it will focus on the new Rwandas and Somalias of today and tomorrow as well as on situations that have been largely forgotten: the continuing war in Afghanistan; slavery in the Middle East, Africa, and Southeast Asia; human rights repression in Tibet, Burma, and East Timor...<p>The ICHR will offer small grants (e.g. sufficient to cover an air fare) and information resources for journalists, photographers, artists, television and radio teams wishing to cover such stories. Because of budgetary cutbacks among major newspapers and broadcast networks, it is often up to independent journalists or media organizations with limited resources to provide the first stories, sometimes at great personal risk. CROSSLINES Global Report will help ensure that such coverage is picked up by the international media.<p>The ICHR will be supported in its information efforts by collaborating closely with international humanitarian and human rights organizations. It will also work through an informal world-wide network of concerned journalists, editors, broadcast producers, and journalism schools. The ICHR will be officially announced at the opening of the Herbert Girardet exhibition/retrospective, which will run from 4-20 November 1994. Selected oil, water colour and pastel paintings as well as drawings by Herbert Girardet will be sold at the exhibition with proceeds going to the new centre.<hr><i>For further information, please contact: <br>Edward Girardet at Tel/Fax: 41(21)-801-6271. <br>Or Peter Hulm, managing editor, CROSSLINES Global Report.</i><p>This article was first published in the October special Rwanda issue of <b>CROSSLINES Global Report,</b> an independent newsletter of reporting on humanitarian, development and environmental issues.<br>©Copyright CROSSLINES Global Report 1994<p><a href="medianatura_top.html"><img src="crosslines_pix/media_natura_logo2.gif"> Crosslines UK Representative: Media Natura</a><hr><a href="index.html"><img src="crosslines_pix/crosslines_logo2.gif"> Crosslines Home Page</a><hr></body></html>
