<html>
<head>
<title>Unicef  - Children First: The story of UNICEF, past and present</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" link="#333366" vlink="#3399ff" text="#000000">
<hr>
 <h2 align=center>     Children First: The story of UNICEF, past and present</h2>

                                 
 <h3 align=center>                        by Maggie Black</h3>
 
 <br>
 
<font size=4>This book takes as its starting point the rise of children on national and international
agendas in
recent years. In countries around the world, Presidents and Prime Ministers - including Clinton,
Mandela, and even Major - are nowadays keen, or at least willing, to identify with the children's
cause, in the context of health, education, family support, or to combat child exploitation, abuse
or crime. <i>The cause of children has abandoned its nanny image and taken on political edge.
</i></font><p>

<hr width=71%><p>

<b>Children First</b> was commissioned by UNICEF for its 50th anniversary year, and it naturally
focuses on UNICEF's role, especially that of its late Executive Director, James P. Grant, in
bringing children to a position of unprecedented prominence. But it is careful to stress that
underlying social trends hold the key, including changing patterns of reproduction and family life
and lengthening childhood dependency in developing and industrialised countries alike. UNICEF's
recent dynamic championship of children internationally has worked so well because it fell upon
fertile ground. <p>


Nominally, this is a history of an organisation. In fact it is an exploration of evolving ideas and
practice in international social development, with UNICEF acting as lens, barometer and
institutional expression of world-wide concern for children. Under Grant's leadership (1980-95),
UNICEF asserted the principle of "children first" within all macro-policy spheres, economic and
"developmental" as well as political and humanitarian. The strategy succeeded way beyond
expectations; humanity's willingness to mobilise behind the children's cause took even Grant by
surprise. <p>


Grant's initial UNICEF thrust, launched in the early 1980s, caused controversy within the
international community. He declared a "child survival revolution" and advocated widespread use
of low-cost public health techniques to save millions of children's lives needlessly lost to
preventable disease. Critics saw in this strategy a reversion to long abandoned "technical fix"
solutions to complex problems of poverty, but Grant waged an effective campaign to bring them
around. His "child survival" crusade was, in the final analysis, a triumphant success, delivering in
1990 "universal childhood immunization" and a World Summit for Children. This in turn helped
set in motion the reorientation of the whole international development agenda around "human
development" goals, since reflected in other UN initiatives and Summit declarations.<p>


The book is thematic, covering the evolution of policy and practice in maternal and child health
care, nutrition, water supplies and sanitation, education and emergency relief in the post-colonial
world. The "child survival revolution" enhanced activity on behalf of children in some of these
contexts; others suffered. The book is by no means uncritical either of UNICEF, or of the
direction in which it was steered by Grant. It also discusses children's issues within over-arching
themes such as urbanisation and industrialiation, human rights, armed conflict, the post-Cold War
transition, Africa's travails, and gender. <p>


In 1989 came a highly significant international development on behalf of children: the passage by
the UN of the Convention on the Rights of the Child. During the 1990s it has become the most
widely ratified human rights convention in history, with 187 signatory states. The extraordinary
response the Convention has elicited, alongside the constant media attention children's issues
today excite, is seen as corroboration that the cause of children has managed to gain
unprecedented currency. <p>


Since the 1960s, the perspective dominating UNICEF's work, a perspective dramatically
heightened under Grant, was to focus on the basic needs of children in the developing world as
part of the campaign against world poverty. In the post-Cold War era, the international campaign
on behalf of aid to the developing world is fast running into the historical sands. Therefore, in its
final chapter Children First suggests that the time has come for a major shift. UNICEF now
needs to reposition itself to pursue the fulfilment of children's rights within the framework of the
Convention in both developing and industrialised countries. Only in this arena can the international
prominence of the children's cause - on which UNICEF's own fortunes ultimately depend - be
sustained.<p>


This is the third historical review by Maggie Black of ideas and practice in the context of
international social development via an account of a key organisation and its evolving mission;
the two earlier volumes were a history of UNICEF (<i>The Children and the Nations</i>, MacMillan,
1987) and a history of Oxfam (<i>A cause for our times</i>, OUP and Oxfam, 1992). She is virtually
the
only writer producing this kind of historical analysis, and the book is an important contribution
to the aid and development literature.

15 July 1996


