</TABLE></center></h1><p>


<a name="amnesty"><br>


["Amnesty<br clear=left><br><br>

<b><li>The Amnesty International Report 1995</b><br>
Each year Amnesty International publishes its Annual Report, which summarises the human rights situation around the world.  The theme of this year's report is human rights abuses against women.<p>

Women suffer every known human rights abuse in the world. They are being raped, mutilated and killed by both government and opposition forces and held as prisoners of conscience.<p>

This latest Amnesty International Report is a contribution to their struggle for justice, equality and freedom. It exposes a range of human rights violations suffered by women, men and children in 151 countries and it shows who was responsible. It is a challenge to all governments to bring them to an end.<b><br>
£14.99<br>
July 1995<br>
0862102456<br>
The Amnesty International Report 1996 will be published in June 1996 at £16.99</b><br><br><br>



<b><li>Amnesty International Handbook</b><br>
Everything you ever wanted to know about the workings of Amnesty International, including structure, policies on individual issues, how the movement came into being etc. A reference manual, useful for both individuals and Amnesty Groups.<b><br>
£6.99<br>
1992<br>
pp148<br>
0862102057</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Optima Amnesty International Handbook</b><br>
Written and compiled by the UK Section  of Amnesty, this is an excellent introduction to the work and history of Amnesty International and the work of the UK Section.<b><br>
£4.99<br>
1990<br>
pp134<br>
Published by Optima<br>
Trade orders to Tiptree Book Services<br>
035618840X</b><br><br><br>



<b><li>Amnesty International Letter Writing Guide</b><br>A 30 page guide for Amnesty members and supporters. It contains sample phrases and letters, advice on sending telegrams and extracts from the text of the Universal Declaration on Human Rights.</b><br>
£2.25</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Slamming the Door<br>
The Demolition of the Right to Asylum in the United Kingdom</b><br>
Around the world, there are at least 15 million men, women and children who have been forced  out of their homeland by political terror, state oppression and armed conflict.  Under international law, all governments have an obligation to provide protection to such people.<p>

Despite repeated protestations of its commitment to the principles of international refugee law, in recent years the British Government has introduced a raft of measures intended to prevent or deter such people from travelling to the United Kingdom to seek asylum.  The imposition of visa regimes on refugee-producing countries, the incarceration of asylum-seekers in prisons and detention centres while their cases are dealt with, and the use of special "fast track" mechanisms for certain cases have all undermined the right to seek asylum in the United Kingdom.<p>

However, seemingly not content with the effect of these restrictions, the Government has now introduced two further measures which take this process to new - and unacceptable - limits.  The Asylum & Immigration Bill - likely to become law in mid-1996 - provides for a critical erosion of
existing legal safeguards.  And new Social Security Regulations - which came into force on 5 February 1996 and deny many needy asylum-seekers the means to obtain food and shelter while awaiting determination of their asylum claim or appeal - effectively render meaningless such legal safeguards as will remain once the Bill has become law.<p>

This report sets out Amnesty International's concern that the combination of these measures amounts to an effective demolition of the United Kingdom's asylum process, and therefore to an abdication by the Government of its obligations under international law.  It shows how these measures form part of a secretive process aimed at establishing a common, restrictive European Union asylum policy.  And it demonstrates that, in seeking to justify these measures, Government ministers have used "bogus" arguments and relied upon "bogus" statistics.<b><br>
£2.99<br> 
12th April 1996<br>
56pp<br>
ISBN 1873328206 </b><br><br><br>

<b><li>Human Rights are Women's Right</b><br>
For millions of women the 1990's have meant terror, deprivation and the imperitive of fighting for justice.  Today what unites women internationally is their vulnerability to abuse of their fundamental human rights and their dedicated efforts to claim those rights.<p>

Most of the casualties of war are women and children; most of the world's refugees are children; most of the world's poor are women and children.  Human rights abuses against women remain rampant because they are largely hidden.<p>

This report launches Amnesty International's 1995 campaign for the protection of women's rights.  The report highlights the situation of women in some seventy five countries and shows how much work must be done if we are to have the United Nations' objective of 'equality by the year 2000".<br>
<b>£6.99<br>
March 1995<br>
pp135<br>
0862102421</b><br><br><br>

<b><li>Childhood Stolen<br>
Grave Human Rights Violations Against Children</b><br>
Every day, somewhere in the world, children face arrest, detention, torture and political murder.  Some are held as political prisoners by governments, cut off from family and outside support, tortured and even killed.  Some suffer physical or mental torture to force family members to confess or give themselves up.  Some are executed.  Some "disappear", never to be seen again.  Killed by shadowy murder squads linked to the government, the police and the military.  This report highlights the perils faced by children all over the world despite the protection provided by the United Nations Conventions on the Rights of the Child, first adopted in 1989.
<b>£6.99<br>
May 1995<br>
pp65<br>
187332815X</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Dead Man Walking: An Experience of Death Row<br></b>
 <i>By Helen Prejean</i><br> 
When Helen Prejean, a sister of St Joseph of Medaille, was invited to write to an inmate on death row in the United States, she ended up befriending him and witnessing his execution two years later. Almost immediately she became spiritual adviser to another inmate who remained unrepentant until his execution. This book is the extraordinary account of her relationship with the two murderers and her initiation into the world of America's death row.<br>
<b>£5.99<br>
1994<br>
pp278<br>
Published by Fount <br>
0006278140<br>
Trade orders to Harper Collins Distribution </b><br><br><br>


<b><li>The Execution Protocol</b><br>
<i>By Stephen Trombley <br></i>
This is the first book to go behind the scenes and look at what it is like to live and die on America's death row. Author and film maker Steven Trombley spent over a year immersed in the shadowy world of the capital punishment industry, embarking on a journey that allowed him to see and hear things many people cannot bring themselves to think about. The result is a shocking and immensely readable insight into the history and present practice of state sanctioned killing. <br>
<b>£5.99<br>
Published by Arrow Books, 1993<br>
pp389, with 8 pages of photographs <br>
Trade orders to Tiptree Distribution</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>When the State Kills</b><br>
This report is a damning indictment of the death penalty, the premeditated killing of a human being by the state. The report looks at the issues behind Amnesty's campaigns on the death penalty and details the use of the death penalty in 180 countries.<br>
<b>£14.99<br>
 1989<br>
 pp268<br>
0862101646 </b><br><br><br>

<b><li>Getting Away with Murder: Political Killings and "Disappearances" in the 1990s</b><br>
Mass murderers are on the loose. They are called governments. Every day their agents are killing defenceless people or making them "disappear". This report exposes the official lies, cover-ups and covert methods of repression used to conceal human rights crimes and avoid international condemnation.<br>
<b>
£5.99<br>
1993<br>
pp129<br>
0862102251 </b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Political Killings and "Disappearances": a manual for action </b><br>
More than a million people in the last 25 years have been victims of "disappearances" and extrajudicial executions - unlawful and deliberate killings carried out by order of a government or with its acquiescence. Many others have been deliberately and arbitrarily killed by armed opposition groups. This report provides ideas and tools for the eradication of "disappearances" and political killings which will remain useful for years to come.<br>
<b>£9.99<br>
1994<br>
pp 300<br>
906463095X</b><br><br><br>



<h3>Country Profiles</h3>

<ul><li><b>The Americas<br>
Human Rights Violations Against Indigenous Peoples</b><br>
The indigenous peoples of the Americas are the inheritors of a 500 year legacy of violence and brutality. Today's indigenous activists have frequently paid for their efforts with their lives and their liberty. <br>
<b>
£5.99<br>
1992<br> 
pp114<br>
0862102200</b><br><br><br>

<b><li>China<br>
No One is Safe - Political Repression and Abuse of Power in the 1990s</b><br>
Amnesty International has just launched its biggest ever campaign on China and this report sums up Amnesty's concerns in that country. Despite economic reforms, political repression and abuse of power mean that everyone is at risk of serious human rights violations. Torture is endemic.<p>

Thousands of political dissidents and members of religious and ethnic groups remain in jail simply for expressing their views. Hundreds of people who have never been charged with a crime are arbitrarily detained, many of them in forced labour camps. More people are executed in China each year than in all other countries of the world put together.<b><br>
£6.99<br>
March 1996<br>
118pp<br>
0862102553</b><br><br><br>




<li><b>Colombia<br>
Political Violence, Myth and Reality</b><br>
In Colombia the military literally get away with murder. Army counter-insurgency strategy, honed in forty years conflict with guerrillas, is the backdrop to massacre upon massacre. Widespread human rights violations go unpunished. Since 1986 over 20,000 people have died in political violence. Many died in confrontations between guerillas and government forces. Most were peasant farmers in conflict zones. The evidence, drawn from thousands of cases, shows that the security forces and their paramilitary allies are responsible for most of the killings.<br>
<b>
£5.99<br>
1994<br>
pp109<br>
0862102286</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Greece<br>
Torture and Ill Treatment</b><br>
Despite the ending of systematic torture in Greece those arrested are still in danger of being tortured or ill treated in police stations.<b><br>
£5.99<br>
1992<br>
0862102154</b><br><br><br>



<b><br>India<br>
Torture, Rape and Deaths in Custody</b><br>
Torture is routine in every one of India's 25 states. Every day victims are beaten senseless, given electric shocks or have their limbs crushed by heavy rollers. Sexual torture, including rape, is also common. <br><b>£5.99<br>
1992<br> 
pp195<br>
086210209X</b><br><br><br>



<b><li>Indonesia and East Timor<br>
Power and Impunity, Human Rights Under the New Order</b><br>
Indonesia's rulers came to power in 1965 in the wake of one of the worst massacres in recent history. In less than a year up to one million people were killed and at least as many jailed. Despite its chilling human rights record, the government of Indonesia has enjoyed support and succour from the world's most powerful nations. Only the human rights violations in East Timor, illegally occupied since 1975, have touched the international conscience. This report demonstrates that human rights violations are widespread not only in East Timor, but in the entire Indonesian archipelago.<br>
<b>£5.99<br>
September 1994<br>
pp126<br>
0862102367</b><br><br><br>



<li><b>Mexico:<br>
Torture With Impunity</b><br>
Torture is institutionalised in Mexico. This report documents the pattern of torture in Mexico and recommends specific measures for its prevention and for the assistance of its victims.<br><b>
£5.99<br>
1991<br>
pp54<br>
0862102006</b><br><br><br>



<b><li>Philippines<br>
The Killing Goes On</b><br>
Documents the pattern of extrajudicial executions in the Philippines under the government of President Corazon Aquino since 1988. Shows why the killings have continued despite measures introduced by the new government to protect human rights.<b><br>
£5.99<br>
1992<br> 
pp119<br>
0862102081 </b><br><br><br>




<b><li>Sudan<br>
The Tears of Orphans</b><br>
<i>"Beware of the tears of orphans and the prayers of those who are victimized." </i><br>
With these words a Sudanese army officer, on trial for sabotage, faced his accusers. The military government's drive to control Sudan has produced human rights violations on a staggering scale across the country. No one is safe. The victims come from all classes, ethnic groups, and religions. The abuses they suffer include torture, arbitrary detention, mutilation, flogging, "disappearance" and death.<b><br>
£6.99<br>
January 1995<br>
130pp<br>
0862102383</b><br><br><br>



<b><li>Syria<br>
Indefinite Political Imprisonment</b><br>
When President Hafez al-Assad unexpectedly released some 2000 political prisoners recently hopes were raised for a new era in Syria. This report shows that these hopes may be premature or even misplaced.<b><br>
£5.99<br>
1992<br>
pp55<br>
0862102170</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>United Kingdom<br>
Political Killings in Northern Ireland</b><br>
In over twenty years of civil conflict over 3400 people have been killed. These include killings by members of the security forces, killings by paramilitary groups carried out with the acquiescence, collusion or complicity of the security forces and deliberate and arbitrary killings by armed political groups. This report also investigates bombings, "punishment" killings and beatings carried out by the IRA and UDA.<b><br>
£5.99<br>
1994<br>
pp74<br>
1873328095</b><br><br><br>
</ul>

<h3>Refugees</h3>

<ul><b><li>Playing Human Pinball</b><br>
Home Office Practice in "Safe Third Country" Asylum Cases</b><br>
In July 1993 the Government enacted new legislation - the Asylum & Immigration Appeals Act - providing for stricter application of the criteria for granting asylum and the rapid expulsion of rejected asylum-seekers.  Despite no apparent change in the nature of applications, the proportion
of successful applicants has since fallen substantially.<p>

In particular, the 1993 Act established a special "fast-track" procedure enabling the Home Office to seek to "pass the buck" by returning asylum-seekers to so-called safe third countries - that is, countries through which they passed in transit to the United Kingdom and where, it is held, they
should have sought asylum - without examining their asylum claims and without any guarantee that the "third country" in question will do so.<p>

This report - based on a nine-month study of 60 individual cases - demonstrates that this "fast-track" procedure has failed to perform to the Government's expectations: intended to allow for the expulsion of asylum-seekers to "third countries" within "a week to 10 days", the procedure has proven to be neither rapid nor productive in terms of expulsions.  It shows that the procedure imposes immense hardship on those unfortunate enough to fall within its scope.  It indicates that
this game of "human pinball" compromises the Government's upholding of its obligations under the 1951 UN Convention on Refugees.  And it concludes that, unless the Government is willing to introduce proper safeguards, such practice - and the "fast-track" procedure itself - should be
abandoned and the millions of pounds it costs every year put to better use.<b><br>
£7.99<br>
June 1995 <br>
pp85<br>
1873328176</b><br><br><br>

<b><li>Prisoners Without a Voice<br>
Asylum-Seekers Detained in the United Kingdom</b><br>
<i>Second revised and expanded edition.</i><br>
In October 1994 Amnesty International UK published the first edition of this report. It demonstrated that a lack of accountability and absence of judicial control over the decision to detain asylum-seekers results in arbitrary decision making and, in at least 44% of cases, unnecessary detention.<p>

In the wake of its publication junior Home Office Minister, Nicholas Baker, was forced to reveal for the first time that the average cost of holding an asylum seeker in an immigration detention centre is "over £800 per week" and in a criminal prison £422 per week. Using these figures
Amnesty International has calculated that the cost of detaining asylum-seekers is about £20million per annum.<p>

This important report has been fully revised, expanded and updated to include the government's response to Amnesty International's recommendations.<b><br>
£7.99<br>
May 1995<br>
pp82<br>
1873328117</b><br><br><br></ul>


