<b>Thursday 23 May</b><br>
<i>From webmaster@saudhouse.com</i><p>
<p>
<h3>Corruption in the House of Saud</h3>


INTERNET-Cyberspace  Committee Against Corruption in Saudi 
Arabia (C.A.C.S.A.) announced today the posting of its message and 
mission statement on a new site to be found under www.saudhouse.com.<p>


        www.saudhouse.com has three aims : <ul><li>1) to expose the corruption 
and the human rights abuses and lack of women's rights in Saudi Arabia. 
<li>2) to convince the United Nations to pass laws against corruption 
similar to those laws that protect humans from crimes and laws that 
allow the IMF and the World Bank fiscal control of a mismanaged society. 
<li>3) to build grassroots support in universities around the globe to help 
us in sending a strong message to our elected officials to stop 
corruption in Saudi Arabia.</ul>


        When a government is corrupt, the people that supported that 
government suffer the most. In a corrupt society, you have lower 
standards of living because you have monopolies and oligopolies and 
mafia-style inner circle of the priviliged few at the expense of the 
unpriviliged majority. In a vibrant democratic society like Israel, when 
a company makes $100 million in profits, the money is distributed 
amongst stockholders from all walks of life, in Saudi Arabia, when a 
company makes $100 million, that money gets deposited in a Swiss bank 
account owned by one Prince never to benefit the society at large. That 
is what is happening in Saudi Arabia and that is why CACSA exists today.<p>


        Saudi Arabia today is at the brink of bankrupty thanks to the 
mismanagement and corruption of King Fahd and Prince Sultan. If this 
continues, it will not be long before the US Congress is asked to bail 
out Saudi Arabia in order to save "our interests". This bail out will be 
very expensive indeed and to be paid for by US taxpayers. CACSA would 
like to see this avoided by passing laws to take voluntary fiscal 
control from the Saudis before it is too late. The blueprint of these 
laws is being put into effect today by the UN in Iraq. King Fahd, who 
had a stroke in November 1995, is willing to give up fiscal control with 
enough pressure from the US and the world community. 
<p>

        Saudi Arabia holds 25% of world oil reserves. Its style of 
government is a monarchy with the King having total control over 
the daily routine of the country. Population is around 15 million 
with about 5 million in expatriate workers. Its annual budget is around 
$50 billion.
<p>

<b><a href="HTTP://WWW.SAUDHOUSE.COM
">HTTP://WWW.SAUDHOUSE.COM</a></b><p>


<b>The writer wishes to remain anonymous</b><p>
<a href="../index.html">
</body>
