Economics and Development Resource Centre</b><br><br>

<b><li>Thirsty Cities: Water, Sanitation and the Urban Poor</b><br>

On World Water Day in 1994, Wateraid published a report entitled Mega-Slums: the coming sanitary crisis, which sounded a warning about modern urban growth.<p>

This year, Habitat II - the UN's second global conference on Human Settlements will be held in Istanbul.  Many of the issues set out in Mega-Slums will be raised during the Conference debates on what is now termed the 'brown agenda': the environment of urban settlements.  Rapid urban growth requires new considerations of the ways in which space and amenities should be managed so that city and townscape provide a liveable and healthy environment.<p>

Wateraid have recently issued a briefing note Thirsty Cities: Water, Sanitation and the Urban Poor for World Water Day 1996 (22nd March), providing an update of the facts concerning the sanitary crisis facing residents and authorities in many parts of the urban South.  It sets out the key changes in infrastructural policy needed to bring the crisis under control, and examines the recent record of policy and practice for signs of improvement.<br>
<b>Published by Wateraid<br>
Prince Consort House<br>
27-29 Albert Embankment<br>
London <br>
SE1 7UB<br> UK<br>
Tel: +44 171 793 4500<br>

Fax: +44 171 793 4545<br>
Internet: http://www.oneworld.org/wateraid/index.html</b><br><br><br>



