<HTML>





<HEAD>





<TITLE>Danish Development Assistance, The Plan for 1995-99</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<pre>



</pre><center><p>

<FONT SIZE=+2> Danish Development Assistance, The Plan for 1995-99


</FONT> <P><BR>


<FONT SIZE=+1> The present document is a summary of a plan for Danish Development Assistance. The plan is based on the development strategy outlined in "<a href="adw.htm">A Developing World: Strategy for Danish Development Policy towards the Year 2000</a>".</center>

</FONT><p><hr>


<P>


<B><FONT SIZE=5>Contents:</FONT></B>


<P>


1. The Aid Policy Framework


<P>


2. The Volume of Danish Assistance


<P>


3. Bilateral Development Assistance


<ul>


<li>a: Programme countries


<li>b: Transitional assistance and country programmes to be phased out


<li>c: Mixed credits

</ul><P>


4. Regional Assistance


<P>


5. Multilateral Assistance


<ul>

<li>a: The UN organizations


<li>b: The World Bank Group


<li>c: The global environmental programmes


<li>d: Funds-in-trust cooperation


<li>e: Humanitarian assistance


<li>f: EU</ul>


<P>


6. Other Types of Assistance and Activities


<P>


<hr><B>1. The Aid Policy Framework</B>


<P>


In accordance with the law on international development cooperation


the Minister for Development Cooperation once a year submits to


the Danish Parliament a plan for the expenditure framework of


the development cooperation for the next five-year period. The


plan reflects the order of priority - which is continuously adjusted


- in the preparation of Danish development assistance.


<P>


<B>The new development strategy: &quot;A Developing World&quot;</B>


<P>


On 22 March 1994 the Government submitted to the Danish Parliament


a new development strategy <I>&quot;A </B></I>Developing World:


Strategy for Danish Development <I>Policy towards the Year 2000.'


</I>The parliamentary debate that followed </B>demonstrated


broad political consensus on the strategy.


<P>


The present 5-year plan is thus the first after the adoption of


the strategy. The plan reflects the new initiatives that have


so far been initiated as a follow-up to the strategy.


<P>


<B>Poverty alleviation</B>


<P>


The fight against poverty is the fundamental principle underlying


Danish development assistance. This was emphasized in the new


development strategy. Efforts to realize the objective of poverty


alleviation will be continued, partly in connection with the preparation


of individual strategies for the development cooperation with


each of the programme countries and partly by updating existing


guidelines for the preparation, implementation and evaluation


of projects and programmes.


<P>


<B>Promotion of democracy and human rights</B>


<P>


The </B>promotion of respect </B>for human rights and democratization


has become an ever </B>increasing central and integrated </B>part


of </B>Danish aid policy cooperation with </B>the developing


</B>countries. The new </B>development strategy emphasizes


</B>this fact. </B>Increased respect for human rights is, of


course, an objective in itself. At the same time, respect for


human rights and broader popular participation in the development


process are instrumental in enhancing the development of sustainable


societies. The general development towards more democratic systems


of governance and respect for human rights in each country, therefore,


constitute an important prerequisite for the development cooperation.


Democratization, however, is both a difficult and a long-term


process, and progress in each country must be assessed over a


longer period of time.


<P>


<B>Support for indigenous peoples</B>


<P>


As an important part of the assistance given to promote respect


for human rights, particular emphasis will be placed on activities


in support of vulnerable groups, i.a. the indigenous peoples.


Assistance will be given partly to support the pursuit of political


objectives, partly towards concrete activities. In 1994 a specific


strategy was presented for Danish support for indigenous peoples.


<P>


<B>Environment and development</B>


<P>


It is stressed in the new development strategy that the connection


between environmervt and development, i.e. ensuring sustainable


development, must be incorporated into Danish poverty-oriented


assistance. This means, among other things, that environmental


impact assessments will be prepared in connection with all physical


activities implemented with Danish assistance. Furthermore, increased


priority will be given to efforts helping to augment the developing


countries' own capacity in this area. In an international context,


Denmark will continue to support the strengthening of environmental


cooperation both regionally and globally.


<P>


<B>Women and development</B>


<P>


The new strategy emphasizes the importance that will be attached


to incorporating women Into the development process. The objective


Is for gender issues to play a central and fully integrated role


in the development process. In the coming years, work on women


and development will be focused on the practical implementation


of Danida's new policy in this area: <I>Women in Development -


Danida's WID Policy towards the Year 2000, </I>which was presented


in 1993.


<P>


<B>Population policy</B>


<P>


In <I>&quot;A Developing World' </I>it is ascertained that Denmark


has provided considerable support through the years in the area


of population activities. Directly, via contributions to international


and multilateral organizations and indirectly, via the strong


focus on poverty-oriented assistance to, for example, health,


education and social infrastructure in bilateral development cooperation.


as </B>an element of the higher priority given to Denmark's


efforts within the area of population activities, it was decided


in 1994 to formulate a strategy for the Danish activities in this


area. The </B>point of </B>departure for the strategy was


activities aiming to strengthen the reproductive and sexual rights


of </B>the individual woman and couple to determine the number


of children they wish to have, </B>and to plan the </B>size


and composition of </B>their family themselves.


<P>


<B>Trade, debt and aid</B>


<P>


The new development strategy establishes the mutual interdependence


between aid, trade and debt. One of the objectives of Danish trade


policy is to contribute towards the dismantling of barriers discriminating


against commodities from the developing countries and barriers


that counteract a diversification of their production structures.


Equally it is an objective to work towards the gradual integration


of the developing countries into the multilateral trading system.


<P>


Most of the highly indebted middle-income countries, particularly


in Latin America, are working themselves out of their debt problems


and experiencing a new period of growth. There is growing international


recognition, however, that the poorest debtor countries, particularly


in Africa, need far-reaching assistance. Many of these countries


will never be able to repay their debts fully, let alone attain


economic growth at the same time. Denmark continuously applies


pressure to the effect that low-income countries in the most difficult


position ought to be eligible for debt reduction up to 80 percent


on the publicly guaranteed debt.


<P>


<B>Economic reforms and development</B>


<P>


In the course of the last 10 years a range of developing countries


have implemented far-reaching economic reforms. The reforms have


constituted a condition for support from the IMF and the World


Bank. In most countries the reforms have succeeded in arresting


the economic decline. Only in a few cases, however, have they


been able to create significant economic and social progress.


Denmark supports the implementation of the reforms and emphasizes


that the recipient countries must have the opportunity to take


responsibility. Denmark also focuses on the consequences of the


reforms for the poorest population groups. In accordance with


the resolution of the Danish Parliament on 22 March 1994, an independent


assessment of the IMF's and the World Bank's structural adjustment


programmes has been initiated. The report is anticipated by March


1995.


<P>


<B>Cooperation with non-governmental organizations (NGOs)</B>


<P>


In December 1993 a working group consisting of Danida and a series


of Danish NGOs presented a now strategy for Danlda's cooperation


with the NGOS. This was subsequently incorporated Into the new


development strategy. The NGO strategy establishes that the private


development organizations (NGOS) play an important role in the


overall Danish effort to promote development. In future, the NGO


assistance will also be concentrated on that which the organizations


are good at, and where they have comparative advantages. The NGO


assistance neither can - nor should - evolve into a 'shadow' of


the official Danish development assistance.


<P>


The materialization of the recommendations in the new NGO strategy


will result in a substantial reorganization of Danida's cooperation


with the private organizations. Administrative procedures will


be rationalized to favour especially the small organizations,


and the dialogue on development strategies and choice of programme


countries will be strengthened. The reorganization, which has


already been initiated, will be completed in the course of 1995.


<P>


<B>Cooperation with the Danish private business sector</B>


<P>


Danish companies are an important part of the resource base on


which the development cooperation is based. As a result of the


collaboration in the Special Liaison Committee on Industrial Development


in the Developing Countries, the Government in October 1993 presented


a <I>'Strategy for the Involvement of the Danisl7 Private Sector


in Bilateral Development Assistance.&quot; </I>With this strategy,


which has since been incorporated into <I>&quot;A Developing World,


</I>steps have been taken to involve the private sector more closely


both in the planning and implementation of the bilateral assistance.


It also entails increased commitment on the part of individual


companies in close collaboration with Danida and the recipient


countries.


<P>


The Danish business sector can contribute in various ways to solving


the development problems in the programme countries: through deliveries


of equipment, goods and advisory services. The aim has also been,


however, to focus on the Danish business sector's overall possibilities


for winning market shares in the developing countries, and not


just to look at its share of the Danish aid volume.


<P>


<B>2. The Volume of Danish Assistance</B>


<P>


The Government plans to maintain the development assistance at


one percent of GNP during the next five years. On that basis the


assistance in 1995 is expected to amount to DKK 9,734 million,


increasing to DKK 11,276 million by 1999.


<P>


The principle of a more or less even distribution between bilateral


and multilateral assistance was confirmed in the new strategy.


It is also reflected in the distribution of the assistance between


bilateral and multilateral activities during the present planning


period.


<P>


<B>3. Bilateral Development Assistance</B>


<P>


<B>A: Programme countries</B>


<P>


The new development strategy establishes that in future the official


bilateral development assistance is to be concentrated on the


20 programme countries which were reached in July 1994 with the


selection of Bolivia and Niger. Furthermore, it was decided in


July 1994 that Ethiopia should be appointed a new programme country


in connection with the previous decision to phase out cooperation


with Thailand. The GNP per capita in Thailand now exceeds the


established limit above which Denmark cannot grant official development


assistance.


<P>


<B>Bangladesh</B>


<P>


Danish assistance to Bangladesh will be designed to assist the


moderately poor population groups in developing themselves out


of poverty. It will also aim to reduce the constant risk of relapses


into poverty, and to assist those in extreme poverty through mobilization


activities and targeted employment creation efforts. In connection


with the new strategy for the development cooperation with Bangladesh,


which is anticipated by early 1995, geographical concentration


of the assistance is under consideration. Sectoral concentration


is also foreseen. The sectors under consideration are water and


sanitation, river transport and agriculture. The indicative planning


figures for the bilateral development cooperation with Bangladesh


are DKK 180 million in 1995, increasing to DKK 250 million by


1 999.


<P>


<B>Benin</B>


<P>


The development cooperation with Benin emphasizes the extension


and consolidation of the system of democracy, as well as the promotion


of social and economic development within the framework of the


structural adjustment programme. <B>A </B>strategy for the development


cooperation with Benin is under preparation. It is expected by


the end of 1995. Likely sectors on which the future programme


will be concentrated are water, transport, electricity and agriculture.


The indicative planning figures for the bilateral development


cooperation with Benin are DKK 60 million in 1995, increasing


to DKK 75 million <B>by </B>1999.


<P>


<B>Bhutan</B>


<P>


In future, efforts will be made to concentrate the development


cooperation with Bhutan on sector programme assistance within


three areas: health, incl. water and sanitation (approx. 600/.


of the assistance); environmental planning and administration;


and the political and administrative reform process. The strategy


for the development cooperation with Bhutan is expected to be


revised in early 1996. The indicative planning figures for the


bilateral development cooperation with Bhutan are DKK 50 million


per year throughout the planning pe6od.


<P>


<B>Bolivia</B>


<P>


Bolivia was selected as a now programme country in July 1994.


It is expected that a strategy for the development cooperation


with Bolivia will be ready before the end of 1995. The possibilities


for development cooperation are explored within the following


three areas: efficiency improvements and democratization of the


public sector; support for the integration of the indigenous Indian


population into the development process; and development of the


rural areas and agriculture. The indicative planning figures for


the bilateral development cooperation with Bolivia are DKK 25


million in 1995, increasing to DKK 1 1 0 million by 1999.


<P>


<B>Burkina Faso</B>


<P>


A strategy for the development cooperation with Burkina Faso will


be presented in the course of 1995. It is expected that the assistance


will be concentrated within the following areas: energy, water


supply, health, agriculture and support in strengthening the democratization


process. The indicative planning figures for the bilateral development


cooperation with Burkina Faso are DKK I 10 million in 1995, increasing


to DKK 175 million by 1999.


<P>


<B>Egypt</B>


<P>


The Danish assistance will be aimed at the poor population groups


in Upper Egypt as well as the modern sector of the economy. A


revised strategy for the development cooperation with Egypt is


expected in the course of 1995. The poverty-oriented activities


within the sectors of drinking water, sanitation, health, small-scale


industry and improvements to the environment will be continued


in Upper Egypt. There will also be activities within the energy


sector and in the area of the environment. The indicative planning


figures for the bilateral development cooperation with Egypt are


DKK 190 million in 1995, increasing to DKK 225 million by 1999.


<P>


<B>Eritrea</B>


<P>


A strategy for the development cooperation with Eritrea is expected


in 1995. Denmark, for its part, will seek to concentrate the assistance


on a few priority sectors in which the emphasis will be placed


on sector programme assistance. The possibilities for Danish assistance


within education and agriculture are under consideration. The


indicative planning figures for the bilateral development cooperation


with Eritrea are DKK 20 million in 1995, increasing to DKK 75


million by 1999.


<P>


<B>Ghana</B>


<P>


The strategy for the development cooperation with Ghana will be


revised during 1995. The possibilities for more concentrated development


cooperation are examined in the following sectors, among others:


water supply, health, transportation, environmental protection


and agriculture. At present the focus of the programme is a multi-pronged


approach to solving the poverty problems in the rural areas. The


indicative planning figures for the bilateral development cooperation


with Ghana are DKK 155 million in 1995, increasing to DKK 200


million <B>by </B>1999.


<P>


<B>India</B>


<P>


Based on the expectation that lndia's economy will continue to


experience considerable growth, Denmark has begun a reorganization


of the bilateral assistance. The reorganization entails scaling


down bilateral project assistance and phasing out programme cooperation


<I>per se </I>after 1997. The latter will occur over a number


of years to ensure the sustainability of the activities. In contrast,


increased support is expected via the facility for mixed credits,


the Private Sector Programme and the Industrialization Fund for


Developing Countries. The indicative planning figures for the


bilateral development cooperation with India are DKK 185 million


in 1995, decreasing to DKK 140 million by 1999,


<P>


<B>Kenya</B>


<P>


In connection with the reductions of recent years in the assistance


to Kenya, the Danish assistance has been focused on the following:


the health sector (gradual reorganization into sector programme


assistance); poverty-oriented and sustainable regional development


projects; improvements in food security through support to small


farmers and general support for the development of the rural areas;


and initiatives to fight corruption and improve public administration.


A strategy for the development cooperation with Kenya is expected


towards the end of 1995. The indicative planning figures for the


bilateral development cooperation with Kenya are DKK 130 million


in 1995, increasing to DKK 175 million by 1999.


<P>


<B>Mozambique</B>


<P>


A revision of the strategy for the development cooperation with


Mozambique was carried out in 1994. According to the new strategy,


the Danish assistance will be directed into three areas: activities


within small-scale and family agriculture as well as semi-industrial


fishery with a view to increasing the limited production capacity


of Mozambique; primary education and primary health care (the


latter in the Tete province) in order to increase access to basic


social services; and reconstruction of the economic infrastructure.


Finally, Danish assistance for the economic and social structural


adjustment programme is expected in the form of balance of payments


support. The indicative planning figures for the bilateral development


cooperation with Mozambique are DKK 165 million in 1995, increasing


to DKK 225 million by 1999.


<P>


<B>Nepal</B>


<P>


The aid cooperation with Nepal is in a phase of adjustment and


consolidation. This will entail a transition to actual sector


programme assistance as well as a concentration on fewer sectors.


A revision of the strategy for the development cooperation with


Nepal is expected by mid-1996. The most important areas of activity


are expected to be the following: animal husbandry (incl. dairies),


the education sector, environment and forestry, support for democratizabon


and specific activities related to women. The indicative planning


figures for the bilateral development cooperation with Nepal are


DKK 100 million in 1995, increasing to DKK 125 million by 1999.


<P>


<B>Nicaragua</B>


<P>


The aid cooperation with Nicaragua is focused particularly on


the following: improvements In the transport infrastructure, protection


of the environment and promotion of sustainable management of


natural resources, increased production possibilities for small-scale


agriculture, strengthening of the administration of local authorities,


and more rational administration of the medicine supply. A strategy


for the development cooperation with Nicaragua is expected in


the autumn of 1995. The indicative planning figures for the bilateral


development cooperation with Nicaragua are DKK 125 million in


1995 and 1999. The indicative planning figure for the three years


In between is DKK 120 million per year.


<P>


<B>Niger</B>


<P>


Niger was selected as a new programme country in July 1994. A


strategy for the development cooperation with Niger will be prepared


in the course of 1996. The development cooperation with this country


will therefore take shape in a gradual manner. A central theme


is expected to be natural resource management, with emphasis on


a sustainable strengthening of agricultural production. Access


to drinking water for people and animals is closely related to


this. In addition, general programme assistance and support for


the decentralization process seem to be suitable areas for Danish


support. The indicative planning figures for the bilateral development


cooperation with Niger are DKK 25 million in 1995, increasing


to DKK 75 million by 1999.


<P>


<B>Tanzania</B>


<P>


In the course of 1995 a revised strategy will be made for the


development cooperation with Tanzania. The strategy is intended


to result in a concentration of the assistance on fewer sectors.


Possible areas of priority include health and education as well


as selected productive sectors. The future emphasis will also


be shifted from project assistance to the development of sector


programme assistance. Furthermore, a number of the ongoing activities


will be continued, including an environmental programme, support


for road construction and telecommunications, and support for


the democratization process. The indicative planning figures for


the bilateral development cooperation with Tanzania are DKK 315


million in 1995 and DKK 300 million per year from 1996 to 1999.


<P>


<B>Uganda</B>


<P>


A now strategy for the development cooperation with Uganda is


expected early in 1995. Denmark will propose a continuation of


the cooperation within the areas of health, water, agriculture,


infrastructure, and support for the continued strengthening of


good governance and development of democracy. In future, the assistance


will be modified to take the shape primarily of sector programme


assistance. The indicative planning figures for the bilateral


development cooperation with Uganda are DKK 245 million in 1995


and DKK 250 million per year for the remainder of the planning


period.


<P>


<B>Vietnam</B>


<P>


in the spring of 1994 a new strategy for the development cooperation


with Vietnam was presented. The assistance will be concentrated


on the development of fishery; storage, transport and processing


of foodstuffs; and exploitation of the fresh water resources.


At the same time, the activities of the programme will be concentrated


on selected provinces, particularly in the central highlands,


but also in the northern and southern parts of the country. Furthermore,


support will be given to rehabilitation of two ferry crossings


on the Mekong River, to the financing of a master plan for the


cement sector and to the democratization process. The indicative


planning figures for the bilateral development cooperation with


Vietnam are DKK 95 million in 1995, increasing to DKK 250 million


by 1999.


<P>


<B>Zambia</B>


<P>


The main focus of the development cooperation with Zambia is to


contribute to the implementation of economic reforms with particular


emphasis on poverty alleviation. A strategy for the development


cooperation with Zambia will be finished by mid-1995. The assistance


is initially expected to be concentrated on sector programmes


within education and health. In addition, assistance may possibly


be given in the area of infrastructure, especially roads, bridges


and telecommunications. Until the programme is fully built up,


it will also include short-term efforts in the form of commodity


assistance and balance of payments support. The indicative planning


figures for the bilateral development cooperation with Zambia


are DKK 105 million in 1995, increasing to DKK 150 million by


I 999.


<P>


<B>Zimbabwe</B>


<P>


A now strategy for the development cooperation with Zimbabwe will


be finished early in 1995. The Danish assistance will be concentrated


on four main areas: agriculture, health (sector programme assistance),


development of the private sector and support for selected activities


within infrastructure (telecommunications and construction of


minor roads in the rural areas through labour-intensive methods).


The indicative planning figures for the bilateral development


cooperation with Zimbabwe are DKK 115 million in 1995, increasing


<B>to DKK </B>150 million <B>by </B>1999.


<P>


<B>B: Transitional assistance and country programmes to be phased


out:</B>


<P>


 At present, there are eight programmes of transitional assistance


of different size and duration: <I>Albania </I>DKK 45 million


over 3 years, initiated in late 1994; <I>Angola </I>DKK 200 million


over <B>4 </B>years, shelved due to the civil war; <I>Cambodia


</I>DKK 345 million during the period 1992-97; <I>Gaza and the


West Bank </I>DKK 250 million over 2-4 years; <I>Kirgizstan </I>DKK


60 million during the period 1994-96; <I>Mongolia </I>DKK 175


million during the period 1991-97; and <I>Namibia </I>DKK 200


million during 1990-95.


<P>


In addition to the above, there is a large programme of transitional


assistance to <I>South Africa. On </I>1 January 1994 a 5-year


transitional assistance was launched to a total value of DKK 750


million. The transitional assistance is to support the endeavours


of the new majority to consolidate democracy and promote social


and economic development for the masses. The assistance will be


concentrated within four main areas, with the poorest part of


the population as the target group: democratization and violence


reduction, develoment of the rural areas, education, and private


enterprise and the creation of employment opportunities.


<P>


The assistance to other recipient countries will be phased out


in the course of the planning period.


<P>


<B>C: Mixed credits</B>


<P>


The now facility for mixed credits was established in 1993, and


the Mixed Credft Commiffee, which is vested with the authority


to allocate assistance, was created in 1994. This facility enables


support to be granted for interest payments on export credits


for financing of projects in developing countries. At present,


developing countries with a maximum GNP per capita of USD 2,160


are eligible. By the end of 1994 the project pipeline for this


facility was approximately DKK 1 billion. After a start-up period


(1995-96) the allocations for mixed credits are expected to amount


to approximately DKK 300 million per year.


<P>


<B>4. Regional Assistance</B>


<P>


The new development strategy sets the stage for a major reorganization


of the future Danish regional assistance. The idea is - in accordance


with the main thrust of the strategy - that regional assistance


is to be defined primarily as a special type of multilateral assistance,


concentrated on support to regional institutions and organizations.


Consequently, the bulk of the individual regional programmes will


be financed via the multilateral aid allocation. Regional programmes


are foreseen in Indochina, Central America, Southern Africa and


the Sudan-Sahel region.


<P>


As a rule, future Danida assistance to regional programmes will


be given only if:


<P>


- the assistance is granted directly to regional organizations


and institutions as general support and/or support for specific


activities (as with the fundsin-trust cooperation), 


<P>


- the organization or institution implements the project and is


responsible for


<P>


this.


<P>


This, however, does not exclude the possibility of a certain degree


of official bilateral development cooperation in the form of regional


activities. During the planning period, funds have been set aside


for this in Indochina, Central America and Southern Africa.


<P>


<B>5. Multilateral Assistance</B>


<P>


Approximately half of Denmark's development assistance is given


in the form of multilateral assistance, i.e. through international


organizations, primarily through the organizations within the


UN system, the World Bank and the regional development banks,


and through the European Union (EU). <I>'A Developing World' </I>suggests


a more active policy in the area of multilateral assistance under


the heading: 'active multilateralism.' The idea is, for example,


that in future the multilateral assistance is to be distributed


to a greater extent in accordance with Danish aid policy priorities


and on the basis of the type of activity and efficiency of the


individual organization. The endeavour to materialize the 'active


multilateralism' will be initiated in earnest in 1995 - and this


will be reflected in the next 5-year plan for the period 1996-2000.


<P>


With the submission of the new strategy in the Danish Parliament


in March 1994, however, an initiative has already been taken to


establish the &quot;International Humanftarian Response Capacity',


which was formally launched in November 1994.


<P>


<B>A: The UN organizations</B>


<P>


The Danish assistance through the United Nations system is quite


substantial, both in absolute and relative terms. The discussions


about a financial reform of the UN's aid activities have been


continued in 1994 and are expected to result in concrete proposals


by mid-1995. Denmark will continue to endeavour to promote the


Nordic ideas about more solid and predictable financing of the


organizations, which at the same time, will ensure more equal


burden sharing among the donors. Further developments in the reform


progress will weigh heavily in the deliberations on the size of


the future contributions to the UN organizations. General UN policy


concerns will naturally also weigh heavily. As far as the distribution


of contributions among the individual organizations is concerned,


this will depend on the assessment of the organizations' efficiency


and the extent to which their activities and policies are in agreement


with Danish aid policy principles.


<P>


<B>UNDP</B>


<P>


The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) is the central


body of the UN for the financing and preparation of technical


assistance. In 1994 the UNDP presented a new overall development


concept - &quot;sustainable human development&quot;. This concept


seeks to combine the objective of environmentally sound development


with a human-centred effort within capacity building in order


to alleviate poverty, create jobs and strengthen the status of


the weak groups in society. Denmark supports this initiative.


Meanwhile, Denmark has emphasized that the somewhat general character


of the concept must not result in the UNDP continuing to spread


its activities too wide. In 1994 Denmark was the thirdlargest


contributor to the UNDP (after the United States and Japan). The


UNDP is the single largest recipient of Danish development assistance.


The possibilities of establishing strategic funds will be examined.


<P>


<B>UNICEF</B>


<P>


The United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) aims to assist the


developing countries in their efforts to improve living conditions


for women and children. UNICEF is normally regarded as one of


the most well functioning UN aid organizations. In recent years,


however, it has also become increasingly clear that UNICEF's approach


has certain weaknesses in a broader development perspective. The


most important factor in this respect is that the sustainability


of the organization's activities is generally not sufficient.


The size of Denmark's general contribution to UNICEF will depend


especially on the organization's will to pursue the recommendations


of the board of directors, inter alia in regard to the sustainability


of Ks activities. No major increases in the general contribution


to UNICEF are foreseen. The possibility of establishing strategic


funds within UNICEF will be examined, however.


<P>


<B>UNFPA</B>


<P>


The United Nations Fund for Population Activities (UNFPA) has


the leading role within the UN system in respect of promoting


understanding of the social, economic and environmental aspects


of national and international population problems. It is the general


opinion that UNFPA is well functioning and well managed. The ability


and will of the organization to launch activities within primary


health programmes and broad socioeconomic programmes will be decisive


when establishing the size of future Danish contributions.


<P>


<B>WHO</B>


<P>


Denmark supports six of the global programmes of the World Health


Organization (WHO): the programme concerning research on tropical


diseases (TDR), the programme concerning control of diarrhoea


diseases (CDD), the programme concerning human reproduction (HRP),


the extended programme of inoculation (EPI), the global AIDS programme


(GPA) and the programme for basic medical supplies (DAP). For


several years, Denmark has criticized the leadership of WHO for


its insufficient ability to prioritize tasks. A reform process


is now under way. During the coming 5-year period the funding


eligibility of the individual WHO programmes will be assessed


continuously on the basis of professional, strategic and administrative


parameters.


<P>


<B>WFP</B>


<P>


The World Food Programme (WFP) aims to promote global food security


through the implementation of projects to improve social and economic


conditions in the developing countries. The projects are implemented


in the areas of food deliveries to vulnerable groups and food


aid in connection with catastrophe situations. Surveys indicate


that the demand for food aid will increase, but the supply is


expected to be constant. Consequently, the food aid has to be


made as efficient as possible. A recent evaluation of WFP concludes


that relief work in general is carried out with great efficiency,


while the results of the organization's development projects are


more difficult to establish. In 1994 this situation generated


a discussion which aims at a thorough revision of the overall


strategy of WFP.


<P>


<B>IFAD</B>


<P>


The International Fund for Agricultural Development (I FAD) aims


to provide loans on favourable terms in order to promote agricultural


development in the developing countries. Grant assistance is also


provided on a lesser scale. Generally speaking, IFAD is considered


an efficient organization, which usually presents projects of


high quality with a significant developmental effect for the poorest


population groups in the rural areas. At the same time, it is


relevant to mention that IFAD's poverty orientation is in line


with the Danish aid policy principles. <B>New </B>replenishment


negotiations are expected to be concluded in 1995.


<P>


<B>The Junior Professional Officer Programme</B>


<P>


Through the Danish Junior Professional Officer Programme, Danida


finances the employment of young, well educated Danes in international


organizations, especially the UN system, but also the EU and international


research institutions. In order to accommodate the need to strengthen


the Danish resource base, a minor increase in the number of junior


professional officers is expected within the coming 5-year period.


<P>


<B>B: The World Bank Group</B>


<P>


The World Bank Group consists of the World Bank (IBRD), the International


Development Association (IDA), which is the World Bank's fund


for concessional loans, and the International Finance Corporation


(IFC), which invests in - and arranges loans to - private companies


in the developing countries. Furthermore, in 1989 the Multilateral


Investment Guarantee Agency (MIGA) was established. The World


Bank Group constitutes the most important channel for resource


transfers to a very large number of developing countries. Therefore,


it also plays a leading role in coordinating the activities of


the donor community in these countries. This is also due to the


role of the World Bank in connection with the implementation of


economic reforms. Generally speaking, the World Bank Group must


be considered an efficient institution. In recent years, its activities


have become much more poverty oriented, just as concern for the


environment and the role of women in the development process have


been accentuated. Denmark will continue to press the World Bank


Group to promote Danish aid policy objectives.


<P>


<B>The Regional Development Banks and Funds</B>


<P>


The regional development banks and funds provide loans to the


developing countries in the respective regions. The countries


which make up the respective regions have the majority of votes


in the regional banks, while the donor countries have considerably


more influence in the Funds. In the regional banks, Denmark strives


to promote the general Danish aid policy objectives, not least


the poverty orientation, as well as the inclusion of environmental


and gender aspects.


<P>


<B>C: The global environmental programmes</B>


<P>


An awareness has existed for decades that several environmental


problems affect such a large part of the world that ft is reasonable


to characterize them as global. As a follow-up to UNCED, a sub-strategy


for the Danish effort in relation to the global environmental


problems has been prepared and implemented. This effort is predominantly


financed from the multilateral allocation, but a smaller amount


also comes from the Special International Environment and Catastrophe


Facility.


<P>


<B>D: Funds-in-trust cooperation</B>


<P>


Funds-in-trust cooperation is project assistance implemented by


an international organization but financed by earmarked Danish


aid funds. h may be assistance to concrete activities, selected


on a case-by-case basis, or to sectors or programmes defined in


a long-term framework agreement with the organization in question.


In accordance with the new development strategy, the level of


the combined funds-in-trust cooperation is expected to be reduced


during the planning period. Changes may occur in the distribution


of funds to the individual organizations in order to concentrate


the assistance on organizations and sectors where experience has


proved positive, and where central Danish aid policy objectives


may be advanced.


<P>


<B>E: Humanitarian assistance</B>


<P>


The humanitarian assistance comprises the Danish contributions


to emergency relief - including catastrophe assistance per se


<I>- </I>and contributions to international refugee work. The


Danish humanitarian assistance is channelled mainly through international


relief organizations and private Danish relief organizations.


Internationally, recent years have been characterized by more,


larger and more complex catastrophe situations, while at the same


time humanitarian questions have occupied an ever more prominent


place in the consciousness of international public opinion. This


has had the effect internationally of more and more resources


having been allocated to emergency relief. The developments in


the Danish humanitarian assistance in recent years have reflected


the increasing demands internationally in the area of emergency


relief.


<P>


<B>The International Humanitarian Response Capacity</B>


<P>


With the submission to the Danish Parliament in March 1994 of


the new strategy for Danish development policy, it was decided


to establish an international humanitarian response capacity with


a view to strengthening civilian Danish efforts in crisis situations.


The International Humanitarian Response Capacity is to <B>be </B>in


charge <B>of </B>the deployment of Danish personnel, as a part


of the civilian elements of humanitarian, conflict-preventing


or peace-keeping operations anywhere in the world. The objective


is to contribute to endeavours <B>by </B>the recipient country


or the international community to prevent conflicts and thus contribute


towards maintaining peace and stability.


<P>


<B>F: EU</B>


<P>


The development cooperation within the European Union is growing


continuously, both qualitatively and quantitatively. The EU's


programme of development assistance comprises all kinds of development


assistance, including financial and technical assistance, support


for structural adjustment, food aid, catastrophe assistance and


support for development research. The assistance is managed by


the Commission (almost exclusively grant assistance) and by the


European Investment Bank (EIB loan assistance).


<P>


The focus of the EU's development assistance remains the cooperation


with the countries in Africa, the Caribbean and the Pacific (the


ACP countries) in accordance with the Lom6 Conventions. In addition


to this, the EU has substantial cooperation with the developing


countries in Asia, Latin America and the Mediterranean region.


Denmark emphasizes the need to strengthen the poverty orientation.


And Denmark makes an effort to ensure that the assistance to middle-income


countries is directed mainly towards the most vulnerable population


groups. The promotion of human rights and democratzation, the


environment and the role of women in the development process also


play an increasing role in the EU assistance.


<P>


The coming into force of the Maastricht Treaty introduced treaty


obligations in the development cooperation. The Maastricht Treaty


states that greater coherence is to be attained in the policies


of the European Union vis-a-vis third countries. This is an element


in the common policy on foreign affairs, security, economics and


development cooperation.


<P>


<B>6. Other Types of Assistance and Activities</B>


<P>


<B>Personnel Assistance</B>


<P>


The Implementation of bilateral aid programmes is supported by


personnel assistance comprising the deployment of advisers and


volunteers, as well as provision of stipends for the education


of personnel from the programme countries. The objective of the


new strategy for Danish development policy of securing the sustainability


of assistance through increased use of the developing countries'


own human resources implies a gradual re-organization of this


type of assistance. In future, an effort will be made to reduce


the number of long-term advisers deployed, in favour of greater


utilization of local resources supported by the deployment of


short-term advisers. The number of the latter is expected to be


increased. The effort to increase the proportion of women in the


personnel assistance will be continued.


<P>


Agreements have been reached concerning volunteer programmes with


the Danish Volunteer Service, Ibis, the Danish Missionary Council


and the Danish Youth Council, particularly in a number of African


countries. The programmes comprise more of the 'grass-root' type


of tasks, exchange between youth organizations and public information


work in Denmark. These activities are increasingly carried out


in collaboration with local organizations in the developing countries.


In connection with the traditional deployment of volunteers -


which is expected to decline - the emphasis is on strengthening


local partners in the collaboration.


<P>


The stipend programme has experienced continuous growth, particularly


within the area of local stipends, which are granted for studies


in the scholar's own country or region. This tendency is expected


to be increased in connection with the reorganization of the personnel


assistance after the adoption of the now strategy.


<P>


<B>Projects In Denmark</B>


<P>


The Danish Bilharziosis Laboratory, the Danish Forest Seed Centre


and the Danish Government Institute of Seed Pathology for the


Developing Countries are educational and research institutions.


The scope of these projects is directed towards the developing


countries. The support function of these projects vis-a-vis the


developing countries' own professionals and institutions is expected


to take on particular importance in the years ahead. This is the


case because the new strategy for Danish development policy aims


to increase the use of the developing countries' own human resources.


<P>


<B>Evaluation and Research</B>


<P>


The main purpose of Danida's evaluation activities is to control


and document the quality of the assistance, as well as to contribute


towards the improvement of Danish development assistance through


the collection, processing and presentation of experiences. Fifteen


evaluations will be carried out during the period 1994-97 within


the following areas: water, health, environment, education, infrastructure,


institution building, agriculture and research. Furthermore, six


sector evaluations will take place (fishery, cement, agro-industry,


transport, education and health), and four evaluations of different


types of development assistance (transitional assistance, private


sector support, mixed credits and NGO framework agreements). Finally,


five thematic evaluations will take place, among others: environmental


aspects, technology, aid administration, support for democratization


and the poverty reducing effects of the development assistance.


The Nepal programme will also be evaluated in 1995.


<P>


It is also expected in the coming period that support for development


research will be directed towards bilateral research assistance,


support for Danish development research and support for international


research activities, especially agricultural research. Furthermore,


an effort will be made to incorporate research components into


the ordinary bilateral development projects.


<P>


<B>Information and Cultural Activities</B>


<P>


The objective of the information activities is to ensure that


the development problems maintain an ongoing and natural position


in the information and educational activities undertaken by organizations,


institutions, schools, the massmedia and individuals. Support


is granted for information activities on the developing countries'


economic, social and cultural conditions, as well as the relationship


between the developing countries and the industrialized countries,


and Denmark's participation in the international development cooperation.


A major proportion of Danida's information activities in 1995


will relate to the two large UN conferences during the year: The


Social Summit in Copenhagen from 6 to 12 March and the UN's Fourth


World Conference on Women, which takes place in Beijing in September.


<P>


The cultural cooperation with the developing countries is handled


by the Committee for Cultural Cooperation with the Developing


Countries. This committee, which in recent years has experienced


a strong and growing interest in cultural cooperation, and thus


increased competition for the allocation, has intensified the


collaboration with the other Nordic countries. It will also seek


to extend the collaboration/coordination with the cultural projects


of the Danish embassies. In the coming years support for, among


others, literature projects in Africa is expected to be increased.


<P>


<B>Danida</B>


<br>


<B>Ministry of Foreign Affairs</B>


<br>


<B>2, Asiatisk Plads</B>


<br>


<B>1448 Copenhagen K</B>


<br>


<B>Denmark</B>


<br>


<B>Phone: +45 33 92 00 00</B>


<br>


<B>Fax: +45 31 54 05 33</B>


<br>


<B>ISBN: 87-7265-243-8</B> 


