<HEAD>





<TITLE>Danish Development Assistance, The Plan for 1995-99</TITLE>


</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<pre>



</pre><center><p>

<FONT SIZE=+2> Danish Development Assistance, The Plan for 1996-2000


</FONT> <P><BR>


<FONT SIZE=+1> The present document is a summary of a plan for Danish Development Assistance. <BR>


The plan is based on the development strategy outlined in "<a href="adw.htm">A Developing World: Strategy for Danish Development Policy towards the Year 2000</a>". This latter document is also available on this homepage.</center>

</FONT> <P><hr><p>

<B><FONT SIZE=5>Contents:</FONT></B>


<P>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Summary</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>										


<B><FONT SIZE=3>1.	Preconditions of Danish Development Policy	</FONT></B>		


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>2.	Scope of Development Cooperation	</FONT></B>				


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>3.	Bilateral Development Cooperation</FONT></B>


<BR>					


a:	Programme Countries


<BR>


b:	Transitional Development Assistance and Project Discontinuation										


<BR>


c:	Human Rights and Democratization					


<BR>


d:	Mixed Credits Scheme							


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>4.	Regional Development Cooperation</FONT></B>					


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>5.	Multilateral Development Cooperation</FONT></B>					


<BR>


a:	Multilateral Policy


<BR>								


b:	The UN System									


<BR>


c:	Development Banks								


<BR>


d:	Global Environmental Programmes					


<BR>


e:	Multi Bilateral Development Assistance				


<BR>


f:	Humanitarian Assistance						


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>6.	Other Development Assistance Types and Activities	</FONT></B>	


<BR>


<BR>











<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Summary</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=+1>1. Preconditions of Danish Development Policy</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


In compliance with legislation on international development cooperation, the Minister for Development Cooperation submits an annual report to the Danish parliament, Folketing, on expenditure frameworks for development cooperation for the forthcoming five-year period. This report reflects the priorities set, on an ongoing basis, during the organization of Danish development assistance.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>The new development strategy: A Developing World</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





On 22 March 1994 the Government presented its new development strategy in the Danish parliament, A Developing World, Strategy for Danish Development Policy towards the Year 2000. The subsequent parliamentary debate showed broad political acceptance of the new strategy.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>The reduction of poverty</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





The reduction of poverty constitutes a fundamental principle of Danish development cooperation. This principle is emphasized in the new development strategy. Efforts designed to concretize poverty reduction will continue at all levels - when framing bilateral strategies for development cooperation with programme countries, when updating existing guidelines for the preparation, implementation and evaluation of projects and programmes and when organizing active multilateralism.  These efforts will create the basis for reporting back to the Foreign Affairs Committee on the actual application of the poverty orientation principle in the current parliamentary year.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Promoting democratization and human rights</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


The promotion of democratization and respect for human rights have become increasingly central and integral elements of Danish development cooperation with the developing countries.  This is emphasized in the new development strategy. Improved respect for human rights is obviously a goal in itself. At the same time the observance of human rights and broader popular participation in the development process contribute to promoting the development of a sustainable society. Thus overall development towards more democratic forms of government and respect for human rights in individual countries constitute important preconditions for development cooperation. Democratization, however, is a difficult and long-term process.  Democratic development should therefore be evaluated over a longer time span in individual countries.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Support for indigenous peoples</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


As an important element of assistance designed to promote respect for human rights, particular emphasis will be placed on activities that support vulnerable groups, including indigenous peoples, through support for political objectives and support for concrete activities. Follow-up on the strategy to support indigenous peoples is well advanced, at both bilateral and multilateral level.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Environment and development</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


The new development cooperation strategy stresses the relationship between environment and development. In other words, securing sustainable development will be integral to Danish poverty-oriented development assistance. Environmental impact analyses of all major, physical activities, initiated with Danish development assistance, is one way of achieving this objective. In addition, efforts which contribute to augmenting the developing countries' capacity in this respect will be given priority. In an international context Denmark will continue to contribute to strengthening environmental cooperation at regional and global level.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Women and development</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


The new strategy emphasizes the major importance attached to involving women in the development process. The objective is to give women-specific aspects a central and fully integral position in the development process. Activities in support of women's role in the development process will concentrate in the years ahead on the practical application of Danida's policy in this area: Women in Development - Danida's WID Policy towards the Year 2000, which was presented in 1993, as well as follow-up to the Fourth World Conference on Women.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Population policy</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A strategy for Danish population policy was formulated in 1994, as an element of Denmark's upgraded initiatives in the area of population control. The basis of this strategy is support for activities aimed at strengthening the individual woman's and the individual couple's reproductive and sexual rights, to enable them to plan their own families in terms of number of children and birth intervals.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Commerce</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


The new development cooperation strategy establishes the reciprocal relationship between development assistance, commerce and debt. One objective of Danish trade policy - in terms of general trade policy, which is collective competence, and in relation to trade cooperation with AVS countries under the Lomé Convention - is to contribute to breaking down the barriers that discriminate against goods from the developing countries and that counteract diversification of their production structure, while at the same time working towards the gradual integration of the developing countries into the multilateral trade system.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Debt</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


While most highly indebted middle-income countries, especially in Latin America, are in the process of working their way out of their debt problems and are entering a new growth period, there is growing international recognition that the poorest debtor countries, particularly in Africa, are in need of extensive help.  Many of these countries will never be in a position to repay their debts in full, let alone implement economic growth simultaneously.  Denmark is pressing for additional debt remission for the most encumbered low-income countries.  The problems associated with multilateral debt have been discussed by the World Bank and IMF executive committees.  The World Bank presented an informal proposal for a multilateral debt remission fund in September.  Denmark has responded positively to this proposal, which is now under consideration.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Economic reform and development</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Over the past 15 years a number of developing countries have implemented extensive economic reforms. Economic reform is a precondition for support from the IMF and the World Bank. In most countries the reforms implemented were capable of stemming economic decline. However, only in a few instances did reforms lead to marked economic and social progress.  Denmark supports the implementation of reforms but emphasizes the need to recognize that these reforms, as an element of the development process, have made it difficult to achieve results in the short-term, particularly in the African context. To elaborate on this point it is Denmark's standpoint that the objective of economic reform must be the reduction of poverty and that economic growth strategies must be based on this principle.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Cooperation with non-governmental organizations (NGOs) in the developing countries</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


In December 1993 a working group consisting of representatives of Danida and a number of Danish NGOs presented a new strategy for Danida-NGO cooperation. This was later incorporated into the new development policy strategy. The strategy recognises that voluntary organizations in the developing countries play an important role in overall Danish development assistance efforts. NGO assistance will continue to concentrate on the areas of expertise of individual organizations and on issues where they have a clear comparative advantage. NGO assistance cannot and must not degenerate into a "shadow" of national development assistance efforts.


<BR>


<BR>


The implementation of the new NGO strategy recommendations has resulted in large-scale restructuring of cooperation with voluntary organizations. This includes the introduction of biennial application rounds for NGOs seeking funds for individual projects. Standardized procedures have also been introduced, contributing to shorter case consideration periods and more uniform application processing procedures.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Cooperation with Danish business and industry</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Danish industry is an important element of the development cooperation resource base. To culminate the work of the Committee on Industrial Development in Developing Countries, the Government presented a Strategy for Danish Business and Industry's Involvement in Bilateral Development Cooperation in October 1993. This strategy, which has since been incorporated into A Developing World, enabled steps to be taken to enhance the involvement of Danish industry in the organization and implementation of bilateral development assistance. The strategy also contributed to the increased involvement of individual firms in close cooperation with Danida and the recipient countries.


<BR>


<BR>


The opportunities open to Danish business and industry for obtaining contracts relating to the implementation of multilateral activities are becoming more central themes in multilateral development assistance organization.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Follow-up to the Social Summit</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


The World Summit for Social Development held in Copenhagen in March 1995 closed with the adoption of a policy declaration and programme of action. The Copenhagen Declaration consists of ten obligations aimed at more equitable social development, including a national obligation to formulate a poverty reduction strategy. Denmark will actively pursue the Declaration's obligations at multilateral and bilateral level.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=+1>2. Scope of Development Cooperation</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


In compliance with Government policy development assistance over the next five-year period will account for 1 per cent of GDP. On this basis development assistance in 1996 is expected to amount to DKK 10,189 million, rising to DKK 11,771 million by 2000.


<BR>


<BR>


The principle of approximate equal division between bilateral and multilateral development assistance is confirmed in the new strategy and reflected in the actual division of development assistance between multilateral and bilateral activities in the strategy period.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=+1>3.	Bilateral Development Cooperation</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


<B>A:	PROGRAMME COUNTRIES</B>


<BR>


The development cooperation strategy establishes that in future national bilateral development cooperation will concentrate on 20 programme countries. Malawi was selected as the 20th programme country in November 1995.


<BR>


<BR>











<B><FONT SIZE=3>Bangladesh</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Danish development cooperation with Bangladesh is designed to assist moderately poor social groups out of poverty, lessen the constant risk of relapse into poverty and assist the extremely poor through organized activities and targeted efforts to promote employment. The new bilateral strategy with Bangladesh, adopted in June 1995, states that from now on development cooperation with Bangladesh will be sector concentrated. The sectors selected are water and sanitation, river transport and agriculture. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Bangladesh is DKK 185 million in 1996, rising to DKK 275 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Benin</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Development cooperation with Benin stresses the development and consolidation of democratization and the promotion of social and economic development within the framework of the structural adjustment programme. A revised bilateral strategy with Benin is at the preparatory phase and is scheduled for completion in 1996. In future development cooperation is expected to concentrate on agriculture, water and energy as well as on support for the democratization process. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Benin is DKK 65 million in 1996, rising to DKK 85 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Bhutan</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A new bilateral development cooperation strategy with Bhutan is being prepared and is scheduled for completion during 1996.  Health and environment are among the sectors under consideration for the forthcoming strategy period. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Bhutan is DKK 50 million per year in the strategy period, rising to DKK 55 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Bolivia</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Bolivia was selected as a programme country in July 1994. A strategy for bilateral development cooperation is expected to be ready in 1996. Possibilities for cooperation are being investigated in the following three areas: agriculture and rural development, reform of the public sector and support for the integration of the indigenous population in the development process. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Bolivia is DKK 60 million in 1996, rising to DKK 110 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Burkina Faso</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A bilateral strategy for development cooperation with Burkina Faso is due for completion at the beginning of 1996. Development cooperation is expected to concentrate on the following sectors: water supply, agriculture and energy. In addition to initiatives in these sectors support will be given to the democratization process. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Burkina Faso is DKK 115 million in 1996, rising to DKK 180 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Egypt</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Danish bilateral development cooperation with Egypt will be directed at impoverished sections of the population in upper Egypt while at the same time concentrating on the modern sector. A revised bilateral development cooperation strategy was presented in 1995. The new strategy states that development cooperation - in continuation of ongoing programmes - will concentrate on three sectors: environment, renewable energy and energy saving, and water and sanitation in upper Egypt. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Egypt is DKK 200 million in 1995, rising to DKK 225 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Eritrea</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A bilateral strategy for development cooperation with Eritrea is scheduled for completion in 1996. Efforts are expected to concentrate on assistance to agricultural development and primary education. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Eritrea is DKK 30 million in 1996, rising to DKK 90 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Ghana</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


The bilateral strategy for development cooperation with Ghana will be revised during 1996. Possibilities for more concentrated development cooperation efforts are being investigated within the following areas: water supply, health care, environmental protection and agriculture. The main thrust of the programme at present is a multi-pronged approach to solving poverty problems in rural areas. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Ghana is DKK 170 million in 1996, rising to DKK 225 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>India</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


It was decided to continue bilateral development cooperation with India in spring 1995. A revised bilateral development cooperation strategy will be drawn up during 1996. The main objective of Danish development assistance to India will continue to be the reduction of poverty. Geographic and sectoral concentration are also important factors. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with India is DKK 185 million in 1996, rising to DKK 200 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Kenya</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Considering the cutbacks in development assistance to Kenya in recent years, Danish efforts will now focus on: health care, poverty-oriented regional development projects, improving food security through support to small farmers and support to rural development generally, and on initiatives designed to combat corruption and improve public administration.  A bilateral development cooperation strategy is expected to be completed in 1996. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Kenya - presupposing positive developments in terms of economic reform and progress in the political liberalization process - is DKK 130 million in 1996, rising to DKK 175 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Malawi</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Malawi was selected as a programme country in November 1995.  A bilateral development cooperation strategy is expected to be drawn up in 1996. Possibilities for initiating development cooperation efforts within water supply, health care, education, sustainable agriculture, infrastructure and telecommunications are being investigated. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Malawi is DKK 40 million in 1996, rising to DKK 150 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Mozambique</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A revised bilateral development cooperation strategy with Mozambique was presented in 1995. Under the terms of the new strategy Danish efforts will concentrate on five sectors: small holdings and family agriculture, semi-industrial fishing, primary education, primary health care services (concentrating on Tete province) and infrastructure, concentrating in particular on the electricity sector. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Mozambique is DKK 140 million in 1995, rising to DKK 250 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Nepal</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Development cooperation with Nepal has entered a restructuring and consolidation phase which will involve a transition to sector programme support proper and concentration on fewer sectors. A revised bilateral development cooperation strategy will be drawn up during 1996. Among the sectors under consideration are continued assistance to the education sector, the agricultural sector (natural resources administration) and the telecommunications sector. Support will also be granted to the democratization process. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Nepal is DKK 100 million in 1996, rising to DKK 140 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Nicaragua</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Development cooperation with Nicaragua in recent years has concentrated particularly on improving physical infrastructure, protecting the environment - including the promotion of sustainable exploitation of natural resources - broadening production possibilities for small-scale farming, strengthening local authority administration and more equitable administration of medicine. A bilateral strategy for development cooperation with Nicaragua is scheduled for completion in 1996. As a basis for forthcoming sector selection thorough analyses of the opportunities existing in a number of sectors have been initiated. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Nicaragua is DKK 120 million in 1996, rising to DKK 125 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Niger</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


Niger was selected as a programme country in July 1994. A bilateral cooperation strategy will be drawn up during 1996 which will lead to the gradual establishment of a development assistance programme. The administration of natural resources, with particular emphasis on the sustainable strengthening of agricultural production, is expected to be central to the strategy. Access to drinking water will be closely related to this process. In addition, general programme support and support to the decentralization process are obvious areas for Danish development assistance. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Niger is DKK 30 million in 1996, rising to DKK 80 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Tanzania</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A revised strategy for bilateral development cooperation with Tanzania will be presented early in 1996. It is expected that the strategy will concentrate efforts on fewer sectors, namely: health care, agriculture, roads and the development of the private sector. Assistance will also be granted to the democratization process. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Tanzania is DKK 300 million in 1996, rising to DKK 315 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Uganda</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A new bilateral development cooperation strategy with Uganda was drawn up in 1995. The strategy concentrates on four sectors: health care, water, agriculture and infrastructure.  Support will also be granted to programme anchorage, good governance and the promotion of democratization. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Uganda is DKK 250 million in 1996, rising to DKK 260 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Vietnam</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A bilateral development cooperation strategy with Vietnam was adopted in spring 1994. Development cooperation concentrates on developing the fishing industry, the storage, transport and processing of agricutural output and the exploitation of fresh water resources. Programme activities will also concentrate on selected provinces, especially in the central highlands but also in northern and southern regions. Modernization of ferry transport on the Mekong River will also be supported. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Vietnam is DKK 130 in 1996, rising to DKK 275 in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Zambia</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A bilateral development cooperation strategy with Zambia was drawn up in 1995. Efforts will concentrate on sector programmes within education and health care. Danida will also be involved on infrastructural projects - roads, bridges and telecommunications in particular. Support for the democratization process will also be an element of the strategy. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Zambia is DKK 100 million in 1996, rising to DKK 160 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Zimbabwe</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


A new bilateral development cooperation strategy with Zimbabwe was adopted in 1995. Danish development assistance will concentrate on four main areas: agriculture, health care (sector programme support), development of the private sector and support to selected projects within infrastructure. The indicative planning figure for bilateral development cooperation with Zimbabwe is DKK 120 million in 1996, rising to DKK 160 million in 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>B: TRANSITIONAL DEVELOPMENT ASSISTANCE AND PROJECT DISCONTINUATION</B>


<BR>


<BR>


Transitional development assistance initiatives are underway in Albania (1993-97), Cambodia (1992-98), Gaza/West Bank (1993-97), Kirghizia (1993-97), Mongolia (1992-97) and South Africa (1994-99).


<BR>


<BR>





Under the terms of the new development strategy transitional development assistance can be granted for the purposes of introducing comprehensive social restructuring typically in relation to the introduction of a political system based on popular participation, transition from a centrally controlled to a marketoriented economy, termination of war or reconstruction following a natural or human disaster. In future transitional development assistance will be granted primarily in the form of aid programmes implemented by multilateral or voluntrary organizations (NGOs). In addition to the above support may also be provided for the promotion of democratization, the supply of Danish goods and services, restructuring and modernization etc, administered in a manner that precludes the physical presence of Denmark.


<BR>


<BR>


In the forthcoming strategy period new transitional development assistance efforts are expected in Burundi, Rwanda, Liberia and Angola. It is envisaged that transitional development assistance to Gaza and the West Bank will be extended.


<BR>


<BR>


Development assistance to some other recipient countries will be phased out during the strategy period.


<BR>


<BR>


<B>C: HUMAN RIGHTS AND DEMOCRATIZATION</B>


<BR>


<BR>


The new development strategy affords the possibility of granting support to promote respect for human rights and democratization in countries other than programme countries. From 1996 onwards a global appropriation framework will be established whereby smaller scale human rights and democratization initiatives can be financed. Funds have been earmarked for human rights and democratization initiatives in Ethiopia and in Gaza and the West Bank.


<BR>


<BR>


<B>D: MIXED CREDITS SCHEME</B>


<BR>


<BR>


Regulations governing the mixed credits scheme were adopted in 1993 and a Parliamentary Select Committee on Mixed Credits, responsible for the allocation of funds, was established in 1994. Interest subsidy on export credits to finance projects in the developing countries is granted under this framework.  Support is granted under OECD consensus agreements on tied development assistance credits. Following an interim trial period (1995-96) it is expected that appropriations to mixed credits will amount to DKK 300 million per year.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=+1>4. Regional Development Cooperation</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


The new development cooperation policy provides for substantial restructuring of future Danish regional development assistance. The rationale is that regional development assistance - in compliance with the main objectives of the strategy - should in future be defined as special multilateral development assistance, concentrating on support to regional institutions and organizations.  As a consequence of this policy the greater part of individual regional programmes will in future be financed within the framework of multilateral development cooperation.


<BR>


<BR>


The regulations governing Danida's future involvement in regional programmes presuppose that:


<BR>


<BR>


* development assistance is granted directly to regional organizations/institutions in the form of general grants and/or support to concrete initiatives (as in the case of multi-bilateral development assistance)


<BR>


<BR>


* the organization/institution is project oriented and accountable


<BR>


<BR>





Danish regional development assistance encompasses the following regional programmes: southern Africa, Sudan-Sahel, southeast Asia, Central America and the Middle East.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=+1>5.	Multilateral Development Cooperation</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>


<B>A:	MULTILATERAL POLICY</B>


<BR>


<BR>


As a follow up to the new strategy on Danish development cooperation policy towards the year 2000, an Action Programme for Active Multilateralism will be formulated in early 1996.  Active multilateralism will be based on maintaining Denmark's considerable multilateral involvement including the approximate equal division of development assistance between bilateral and multilateral development assistance. Denmark will attempt to influence and strengthen the international system, in compliance with Danish development cooperation policy objectives, through active multilateralism. Finally, to a greater extent than hitherto, Denmark will engage in a more active fund allocation policy.


<BR>


<BR>


<B><FONT SIZE=3>Activity division and coordination in the international development assistance system</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





Activity division between organizations has traditionally been marred by lack of clarity and duplication. At present the World Bank is in the process of taking over a number of development projects, mainly from UN agencies. The background to this development is lack of efficiency on the part of these agencies, limited resources and the diffusion of available resources over a number of minor activities. As an element of active multilateralism, Denmark will promote the concentration of UN agency projects on their mandates and fields of strength.


<BR>


<BR>





The need to strengthen coordination is stressed in active multilateralism. The perspective of strengthened coordination at country specific level, with the recipient country as the driving force, seems quite promising.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Priority areas for Denmark's multilateral development cooperation</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





In the Action Programme for Active Multilateralism a number of political priorities for Denmark's multilateral development assistance will be established:


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Poverty reduction:</I> the adoption of the reduction of poverty as the central objective of development organizations' efforts, including in programme/project activities and in the geographic division of funds, will be encouraged.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Follow up to the Social Summit:</I> Denmark will build up support for an independent monitoring forum.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Debt relief:</I> Denmark will work to promote the completion and implementation of the World Bank's informal proposal on the relief/remission of multi-lateral debt in the most impoverished countries.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Strengthening women's influence and situation:</I> gender-specific aspects will be incorporated into multilateral organizations' development-related activities generally. In terms of following up the Fourth World Conference on Women particular emphasis will be placed on promoting sexual reproductive health and rights and on improving women's economic situation.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Environment and development:</I> follow-up activities to the United Nations Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED) will continue and efforts to incorporate environmental issues into multilateral organizations' activities will be strengthened.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Population policy:</I> follow-up to the International Conference on Population and Development (ICPD) in Cairo will concentrate on multilateral efforts and initiatives in relation to United Nations Fund for Population Activities (UNFPA) and United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Human rights, democratization and good governance:</I> Denmark will promote multilateral organizations' efforts in areas where individual organizations are particularly competent, particularly in relation to vulnerable population groups, while at the same time promoting the active participation of the population in development processes.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Capacity building:</I>  Denmark will contribute to further developing the World Bank's, United Nations Development Programme's (UNDPS) and UNICEF's comparative advantage in this area.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Bridging catastrophe assistance and development assistance:</I> there is a need for emergency aid organizations to take into account the more long term development aspects of their efforts.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Preventing catastrophes:</I> Denmark will be active in giving higher priority to preventing natural and man made disasters.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Greater administrative effectiveness in organizations:</I> Denmark is prepared to take the consequences of unacceptable administrative practices by reducing its contribution or, if necessary, by terminating membership of the organization in question.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Danish staff:</I> as an element of active multilateralism Denmark will increase its efforts to secure the employment of more Danes in multilateral organizations.


<BR>


<BR>


<I>


*	Supplying Danish goods and services:</I> multilateral organizations will be encouraged to include potential Danish suppliers in their purchasing procedures.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Monitoring the efforts of multilateral organizations</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





A more systematic monitoring system has been put into effect to evaluate the impact of multilateral organizations' activities in recipient countries. In future more emphasis will be placed on positive cooperation in terms of donor coordination at country specific level and in relation to framing these organizations' multilateral programmes and strategies.


<BR>


<BR>





Furthermore, from now on a number of quantitative and qualitative indicators of multilateral organizations' effectiveness will be taken into account when considering efforts in Danish priority areas, etc.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Application of active multilateralism</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





Considerable emphasis will be placed on building alliances with similarly disposed donors and recipient countries.


<BR>


<BR>





In addition attempts will be made to strengthen political and technical dialogue through more direct contact with management and staff - possibly in the form of annual negotiations corresponding to annual bilateral negotiations.


<BR>


<BR>





Funding policies - i.e. major changes in funding, earmarking funds, trust funds - will be employed to a greater extent than hitherto.


<BR>


<BR>





Finally, efforts will be made to create better interaction between multilateral and bilateral development assistance.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Determining contributions to multilateral organizations in 1996</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





The Action Programme for Active Multilateralism will be presented at the beginning of 1996. In cases where contributions are not already determined by international agreements, concrete decisions on contributions to multilateral organizations in 1996 will not be taken until this programme is adopted.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>B: THE UN SYSTEM</B>


<BR>


<B>UNDP</B>


<BR>


<BR>





The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) is the UN central organ for financing and coordinating technical development assistance. The UNDP's overall principles are perfectly in keeping with the objectives of Denmark's development assistance policy. Over the decades UNDP has become involved in a multiplicity of areas. This has resulted in the inexpedient dissipation of UNDP's scarce resources. Together with India, Sweden and the UK, Denmark is analysing the future role of the organization. Denmark is attempting to contribute to improving the organizations capacity with regard to monitoring and evaluating its regional activities. Denmark has also taken the initiative to encourage UNDP, UNICEF and UNFPA to harmonize their budgets and accounting procedures. Denmark will be forced to reconsider its funding commitments if the timetable for presenting concrete proposals in this regard is not adhered to. In 1994 Denmark financed almost 10 per cent of UNDP's overall budget.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>UNICEF</B>


<BR>


<BR>





The objective of the United Nations Children's Emergency Fund (UNICEF) is to improve the living conditions of women and children in the developing countries. UNICEF is prominent as a central actor in poverty reduction. UNICEF is also strong in other areas   especially in terms of women's and children's rights   which are in perfect harmony with Danish development assistance principles. The organization is criticized, however, for spreading its activities too thinly over 140 recipient countries and for not ensuring the sustainability of these activities through support to capacity building in these countries. Denmark will support UNICEF's projects during 1996, including its capacity building projects. By earmarking a proportion of its contribution to UNICEF, Denmark will attempt to ensure that the organization gives higher priority to activities involved with reproductive health and rights, and the rights of children. In the area of administration, pressure will be placed on the secretariat to present the promised proposals on joint budgetary and accounting procedures for UNDP UNICEF and UNFPA during 1996. Failure to fulfil this commitment will have consequences for Denmark's contribution to the organization.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>UNFPA</B>


<BR>


<BR>





The objective of the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) is to promote population policy issues. UNFPA is generally regarded as a well-run organization. Denmark's cooperation with UNFPA has been enhanced immensely in recent years as a result of the higher priority given to population issues in Danish development cooperation policy. However, criticism of UNFPA's mounting administration expenses has been voiced. Denmark has proposed the re-organization of budgetary and accounting procedures, as noted above under UNDP and UNICEF.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>WHO</B>


<BR>


<BR>





The objective of the World Health Organization (WHO) is to achieve the best possible standard of health for all. In recent years the organization has been criticized for not fulfiling its role as a policy formulator in the area of health. WHO has also been criticized for lacking priorities and for administration and management problems. As a reaction to these criticisms WHO has initiated a reform process. The process is proceeding quite slowly however. In the light of these developments Denmark has decided to reduce the number of its joint WHO programmes from six to three in 1996. This will involve a contribution reduction of at least 50 per cent.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>WFP</B>


<BR>


<BR>





The objective of the World Food Programme (WFP) is to promote global food security through the implementation of projects designed to improve social and economic conditions in the developing countries, with the help of food supplies to exposed population groups and by granting food-aid to disaster areas. Over the decades WFP has become increasingly dominated by emergency aid activities, which have proved quite effective. However, this has resulted in a reduction of WFP's capacity and affected resource priorities for development projects.  There is a lack of long term activity planning and opportunities to adjust projects to local food needs are consequently dimished. A study of the relationship between emergency aid and development efforts within WFP is planned with a view to determining a balance in Denmark's cooperation with this organization.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>IFAD</B>


<BR>


<BR>





The objective of the International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) is to grant loans on favourable terms to promote agricultural development in the developing countries.  A limited number of grants are also allocated. IFAD's activities are in keeping with Danish development cooperation policy objectives. IFAD is considered a well-administered organization.  In light of this positive evaluation Denmark's voluntary contribution to the IFAD will be raised.


<BR>


<BR>








<B><FONT SIZE=3>Junior Expert Programme</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





Under the terms of the Junior Expert Programme Danida finances the employment of young, well-educated Danes with international agencies especially within the UN, the EU and international research institutes. To accommodate the need to strengthen the Danish resource base, efforts will be made to increase the number of junior experts.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>C: DEVELOPMENT BANKS</B>


<BR>


<BR>





The multilateral development banks encompass the World Bank and regional development banks for Africa, Asia and Latin America. These four bodies are based on a bank that grants loans on market terms and a fund that grants loans on a concessionary basis. Technical assistance is also granted.  The development banks are also empowered to grant loans and make investments in the private sector.


<BR>


<BR>





The regional development banks and the World Bank in particular play a central role in the developing countries. The World Bank Group is the most important channel for resource transfer to a large number of developing countries and plays a leading role in coordinating donor efforts in these countries. These functions are closely related to the World Bank's role in implementing economic reform. The World Bank also plays a dominant role in the formulation of new development strategies and policies.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>The World Bank Group</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





Considering the World Bank's weighty financial and development policies it is crucial that Denmark secures an influence on the Bank's policies and future course of action. This can be accomplished through "formal" channels, through participation in the work of the executive and during funding negotiations, as well as through bilateral contacts. The Bank is generally receptive to donors' points of view.


<BR>


<BR>





The overall policy of the World Bank is in full accord with Danish development cooperation policy. However, the Bank is often criticized for not being poverty-oriented in the practical application of its development assistance programmes.  Criticism is levelled in particular at the implementation of the structural adjustment programmes, lack of environmental accountability and failure to incorporate women-specific aspects of development assistance policy.


<BR>


<BR>





Denmark will continue its efforts in encouraging the World Bank to live up to its policies and objectives. The possibilities of promoting the Bank's efforts within the area of good governance will also be examined.


<BR>


<BR>





Denmark will endeavour to guarantee the substantial re-funding of IDA-II and to ensure that those countries not wishing to participate in supplementary funding are excluded from commercial contracts and any influence on them.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>Regional development banks and funds</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





Regional development banks and funds grant loans to developing countries in their respective regions. Countries in these regions have majority voting rights in regional banks but donor countries retain considerable influence over funds.  Denmark promotes the general development assistance objectives of the regional banks, including poverty orientation and the incorporation of environmental and women-specific aspects.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>The African Development Bank/Fund</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





Insufficient control of loan policy and general management problems have resulted in a crisis within the African Bank, which could ultimately threathen its existence. Negotiations on capital funding have commenced but the donor community, including Denmark, has clearly indicated that no further funds will be allocated before a clear indication is given that serious efforts will be made to reverse this negative development.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>The Asian Development Bank/Fund</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





The Asian Development Bank is normally considered the best run of the three regional banks. However, re-orientation in recent years towards greater emphasis on poverty reduction is progressing with difficulty.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>The Inter American Development Bank/Fund</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





The Inter American Development Bank has been strengthened in recent years and now surpasses the World Bank in the volume of loans granted to the region. A new orientation towards increased emphasis on poverty reduction is also in progress here.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>The Nordic Development Fund</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





The objective of the Nordic Development Fund is to co-finance projects of Nordic supplier interest with multilateral financial institutions on easy terms. The fund is well run and Denmark will support considerable re-funding when negotiations commence.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>D: GLOBAL ENVIRONMENTAL PROGRAMMES</B>


<BR>


<BR>





It has been acknowledged for decades that many environmental problems affect such large sections of the earth that they are now global in character. A sector strategy for Danish efforts in relation to global environmental problems has been drawn up and put into operation as a follow up to UNCED. These efforts are financed entirely by multilateral funds.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>E: MULTI-BILATERAL DEVELOPMENT ASSISTANCE</B>


<BR>


<BR>





Multi-bilateral development assistance is project development assistance executed by an international, inter-state organization but financed by earmarked Danish development assistance funds. Multi-bilateralism can involve development assistance to concrete activities selected individually or sectors or programmes defined in a multi annual framework agreement with the organization concerned. The extent of overall multi-bilateral development assistance is expected to decline during the strategy period, in compliance with the new development cooperation strategy objectives on this issue. Proportional changes in allocations to individual organizations may occur in an effort to concentrate support on those organizations and sectors where experience has proved positive and where the central objectives of Danish development cooperation can be promoted.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>F: HUMANITARIAN ASSISTANCE</B>


<BR>


<BR>





Recent years have seen an increase in the need for humanitarian assistance together with an expansion in the activities of humanitarian organizations' aimed at normalizing conditions once emergency situations have ended. Danish humanitarian assistance is channelled through international organizations and through Danish voluntary organizations (NGOs). Taking advantage of the experience gained from bilateral emergency aid activities is of great importance to the impact of Danish efforts in influencing multilateral organizations.


<BR>


<BR>





International assistance is granted primarily through the UN humanitarian agencies: United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), United Nations Relief and Work Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East (UNRWA), World Food Programme (WFP), UNICEF, WHO and UNDP. The UN has set up a Department of Humanitarian Affairs (DHA) in recognition of the need to increase the effectiveness and improve the coordination of humanitarian assistance. The DHA has, however, experienced difficulties in fulfiling its mandate. Denmark is encouraging the DHA to be more focused in its efforts.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>International Humanitarian Capacity (IHB)</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





To coincide with the presentation of the new development cooperation policy in the Danish parliament in March 1994, it was decided to establish an International Humanitarian Capacity, with the aim of strengthening Denmark's civilian efforts in crisis situations. The Capacity has now been formed and deployment experiences to date have been positive and will create the basis for further development of IHB.


<BR>


<BR>





<B><FONT SIZE=3>International human rights organizations</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





Denmark is supporting UN efforts in the area of human rights through support for the UN Human Rights Centre. Support is also granted to a number of voluntary international human rights organizations.


<BR>


<BR>





<B>G: EU</B>


<BR>


<BR>





The EU's development assistance programmes are a component part of the EU's overall external relations with the developing countries. Efforts to create coordination between the various policies are still at the inital stages. In the long-term, however, it does have potential strength, considering the EU's weight in global politics. Denmark considers it quite a challenge to influence this aspect of EU policy. With a view to making development cooperation more effective, steps have been taken to create a degree of coordination between EU policy and the various policies of member states. This also involves operational coordination at both country and sector level and enhanced cooperation with other donors. The above themes are expected to dominate the debate until 2000.


<BR>


<BR>





In wider activities to implement a joint foreign and security policy, whereby the overall objectives of the Community's dealing with third countries and regions will be established, EU development assistance could play an important role as a element of soft-security policy, especially in the context of preventive efforts.


<BR>


<BR>








<B><FONT SIZE=+1>6. Other Development Assistance Types and Activities</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>








<B><FONT SIZE=3>Personnel assistance</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





The implentation of bilateral development assistance programmes is supported by personnel assistance. This involves posting advisers and volunteers and granting scholarships to personnel from programme countries. Denmark's new development cooperation strategy objective of ensuring the sustainability of development assistance, through the increased deployment of human resources in the developing countries, will involve a gradual restructuring of this type of development assistance. From now on the objective is to reduce the number of long-term posted advisers, who are expected to increase in number. Efforts to increase the number of women in advisory assistance will continue.


<BR>


<BR>





Together with such DANISH NGOs as the Danish Association for International Cooperation (MS), Ibis, The Danish Missionary Council (Dansk Missionsråd) and the Danish Youth Council (Dansk Ungdoms Fællesråd) agreements have been reached on voluntary programmes, especially in a number of African countries. These programmes involve grassroots-based projects, youth exchange and information and publicity activities in Denmark.


<BR>


<BR>





The scholarship programme has developed steadily especially in the area of local scholarships, granted for studies in a student's own country or region. This tendency is expected to continue in relation to the restructuring of personnel assistance, in accordance with the new development cooperation strategy.


<BR>


<BR>








<B><FONT SIZE=3>Projects in Denmark</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





The Danish Bilharzia Laboratory (DBL) (Dansk Bilharzioselaboratorium), The Danish Forest Seed Centre (DFSC) (Skovfrøcentret) and the Danish Institute of Seed Pathology for the Developing Countries (FIU) (Frøpatologisk Institut for Udviklingslandene), are educational and research institutes. Projects at these centres are directed at the developing countries. The support function of the projects, in terms of the developing countries' own professionals and institutes, will be particularly meaningful in the years ahead in implementing the new development cooperation strategy objective of employing an increasing proportion of the developing countries' own human resources.


<BR>


<BR>








<B><FONT SIZE=3>Evaluation and research</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





The main objective of Danida's evaluation function is to control and document development assistance quality and contribute to improving Danish development assistance efforts by gathering data and assessing and publicising the results. In the forthcoming strategy period twelve project evaluations, seven thematic evaluations and two programme evaluations will be carried out.


<BR>


<BR>





It is expected that support for research in the developing countries in the forthcoming strategy period will be directed at incorporating research components into projects which have another main objective, at bilateral research assistance and at support for Danish research in the developing countries.


<BR>


<BR>








<B><FONT SIZE=3>Information and cultural activities</FONT></B>


<BR>


<BR>





Publicity activities in 1996 will concentrate in the main on the cultural festival Images of Africa, which will be mounted in conjunction with Copenhagen '96.


<BR>


<BR>





Cultural cooperation with the developing countries is administered by a committee whose function is to coordinate development assistance activities and cultural cooperation with the developing countries. A massive rise in interest in cultural cooperation has been experienced in recent years. This has increased pressure on appropriations. The Committee has therefore intensified cooperation with the other Nordic countries and will attempt to expand cooperation/coordination with cultural projects undertaken by Danish embassies. In the years ahead support for such projects as the promotion of literature projects in Africa is expected to increase.


<BR>


<BR>








<P>


<B>Danida</B>


<P>


<B>Ministry of Foreign Affairs</B>


<P>


<B>2, Asiatisk Plads</B>


<P>


<B>1448 Copenhagen K</B>


<P>


<B>Denmark</B>


<P>


<B>Phone: +45 33 92 00 00</B>


<P>


<B>Fax: +45 31 54 05 33</B>


