<h2>Sale of New Zealand' commercial radio stations network opposed 
by Maoris</h2>

The sale of Radio New Zealand's network of 41 commercial radio stations to an international media consortium, New Zealand Radio Network, has come as something 
of a surprise.  The $89 million sale was quickly condemned by the opposition Alliance and Labour parties.  Maori groups, which have already halted the sale of the network 
in March, are also opposing the sale.  New Zealand Radio Network has promised new investment and development in the network. <p>


The deal gives control of the state-owned Radio Company Ltd to three partners: Wilson and Horton, Australian Provincial 
Newspapers Holdings, and Clear Channel Communications, of the United States.  All three have links to the Irish media magnate, Tony O'Reilly.<p>


Out in the cold are the other bidders, a British radio company, GWR, which already runs 12 New Zealand commercial radio stations and was widely considered a front-runner and TV3's Canadian owner, CanWest.  A fourth group initially interested, 
the Ohio-based Jacor, is believed not to have entered a bid.<p>

 
GWR, which had stitched together a last-minute arrangement with the Maori Development Corporation in an attempt to strengthen its appplication, had said it would pay a maximum of  85.8m dollars for the stations.  The corporation was said to 
have taken an interest of more than five per cent in the GWR bid, which was also supported by several institutions. <p>


Still complicating the sale are the Maori objectors led by the Maori Council and the Maori Congress.  They also include the Maori Women's Welfare League and the Wellington Maori Language Board.  Although their attempt to get a High Court 
injunction to stop the sale was unsuccessful,  Justice McGechan, in ruling on the injunction request, said he agreed with the group that the Crown had failed to meet its Treaty of Waitangi obligations to promote and protect the Maori language through broadcasting.  The objectors say they will appeal.<p>
 

The practical difficulties of broadcasting in Maori while retaining a sufficient audience 
to maintain commercial viability are enormous. The new owners may have to dedicate 
certain frequencies exclusively to Maori broadcasting if they are to address the need to 
encourage it and also to maintain an audience on their other stations.<p>


The successful consortium will control two Auckland stations, one of them part of the Newstalk ZB chain.  It will also control an advertising production studio and RNZ Sport.  Auckland has several independent radio stations and that 
mix alone should be enough to ensure competition.<p>


<i>Source</i>: `The Press', Christchurch via BBC Monitoring<p>



