<h1>Newsfile</h1>



<font size=4>"About 120 million acts of sexual intercourse take place each day

resulting in violence, coercion, subjugation, fun, 400,000 live

births, 150,000 induced abortions and 500,000 sexually

transmitted infections...

<p>

"Reproductive ill-health constitutes for women, around 40 per

cent of the total burden of disease between the ages of 15 and

44...

<p>

"Women must be given the right to control their own bodies, their

fertility and their lives."</font>

<p>



<h5>Halfdan Mahler, former Secretary General of IPPF at the first

Mahler Forum in Copenhagen, an annual event instituted by the

Danish Family Planning Association.  </h5>


<hr>
<h3 align=center><a href="#amazon">Amazon Roads</a> / <a href="#voice">A Voice for Widows</a> / <a href="#rivers">Sharing the Rivers</a> / <a href="#fishing">Fishing Limits</a></h3>

<a name="amazon"></a><br><hr>
<h3>Amazon roads</h3>

<p>Concern is growing over plans by the Brazilian Government to
build four major highways through the Amazon rainforest.

<p>One of these will extend the BR 364 highway through to the
Pacific.  Another would open up an allyear road to Venezuela and
the Caribbean coast.  Other schemes would involve paving more of
the transamazon highway and extending it to the south.

<p>All these plans are part of the socalled Amazon Charter, signed
by Brazilian President, Fernando Enrique Cardoso, and nine state
governors last April.  

<p>Farmers, ranchers, lumber merchants and regional governors
welcomed the Charter which would lead to huge savings in the
current export route via the Atlantic ports and the Panama Canal
to Pacific markets.  It would also bring hydro energy from
Venezuela to Manaus, provide an export route for southern soya
bean plantations and open up the Amazonas state to logging.

<p>But environmental campaigners are concerned that such
developments could repeat the ecological and social damage of
previous road schemes if they are not carried out with great
care.

<p>According to local Greenpeace campaigner, Anna Fanzeres, the
governor of the state of Amazonas, Amazino Mendes "has a lot at
stake.  He's been offering incentives to loggers from other
states to come to Amazonas, attracting mineral companies and
aiming at a massive export industry from Manaus."

<p>Greenpeace Brazil also points out that the proposed development
policy for the region is not compatible with the Biodiversity
Convention once it is signed by the Brazilian Government and sits
oddly with the Government's pilot programme to preserve tropical
forests, which receives funding support from the G7 countries.

<p>"Brazil has enough experience with negative impacts of large
scale development schemes in the region (hydro dams, roads,
mining, predatory logging) to know that pursuing this line of
development we are going to lose the immense biodiversity
reservoir that is Amazonia," said Anna Fanzeres.

<p>President Cardoso, in justifying the coasttocoast highway, said
that his aim was to balance economic and technological
development with respect for the environment.  This would involve
relocating Indians to 50 reservations, which it appears that
Germany has offered to finance.  Where the funds needed to build
these highways will come from remains unclear.


<a name="voice"></a><br><hr>

<h3>A voice for 
widows</h3>

<p>One positive outcome of the NGO Forum at the Fourth World Women's
Conference in Huarou, outside Beijing, in September, was the
birth of a new international initiative to promote the cause of
widows.

<p>This followed an international workshop which discussed the grave
implications of the low status  in law, religion, traditions and
society  of the millions of women who are widows. It dealt with
the causes and consequences of their extreme marginalization,
poverty and vulnerability for development and society as a whole.

<p>The meeting, which was supported by Planet 21, publishers of this
magazine, and the Swedish International Development Agency
(SIDA), heard widows speak eloquently of physical violence,
property grabbing and degrading mourning rites often involving
sexual activities. 

<p>It heard successful examples of widows organizations in South
Asia and Africa, and attention was drawn to ways in which the
Women's Convention (CEDAW) could be invoked to protect their
persons and property and encourage acknowledgement of their
economic contribution to the community. 

<p>The workshop drew on other national and regional Forum panels
which discussed aspects of widowhood and, for the first time,
discussed the treatment of widows in the context of international
human rights norms and treaties. Too often widows do not enjoy
fundamental human rights to life, shelter, food, health or
livelihood. They are forced to live in the shadows, easily
exploited, their children's future equally endangered.

<p>It was resolved that widows now need an international voice,
linking the many local groups which have recently sprung up,
through the development an international NGO. The name for this
is Empowering Widows in Development (EWD), and funding is being
sought from a consortium of donor agencies.

<p><i>All those interested in EWD should contact Margaret Owen at
36 Faroe Road, London W14 OEP, UK. Margaret Owen is the author
of a forthcoming book The World of Widows to be published this
year by Zed Books. Research for this has been provided by Planet
21 in collaboration with SIDA.</i>


<a name="rivers"></a><br><hr>

<h3>Sharing the 
rivers</h3>

<p>Water sharing between countries is destined to become one of the
most contentious international issues in the new millennium, as
demand grows along with agricultural and industrial development
and growing populations. Two rivers, the Mekong and the
Euphrates, are likely to attract special attention in 1996.

<p>The signing of the agreement for Cooperation in Sustainable
Development of the Mekong River Basin, last year, opens the way
for major dam and water diversion schemes, especially in Thailand
where the demand for water is growing by more than 12 per cent
a year. A report funded by UNDP advocates that six major dams
should be constructed on the Mekong's main stem.

<p>Of the other signatory states to the Mekong Agreement, Laos is
looking to develop major hydroelectric projects, while Vietnam
is seeking water both for irrigation and industrial needs.
Cambodia's concern is largely to maintain its fishing industry. 

<p>Critics of the scheme warn that it could threaten rare marine
species, reduce the supply of water into the Tonle Sap reservoir
in Cambodia, decrease downstream fertility, increase flooding and 
salt water incursions, and even threaten the delta itself as the
flow of silt is reduced.

<p><b>Turkey's plans</b>

<p>Other huge dams are planned in Turkey where the government's
gigantic water schemes could eventually reduce the flow of the
River Euphrates by between a third and a half.

<p>Writing in Middle East International, Hugh Pope says that
Turkey's determination to complete what will be the biggest
engineering feat in history will have major consequences on
downstream states. And a crisis is inevitable if no sense of co
operation can be fostered between the states of the Tigris
Euphrates basin, principally Turkey, Syria and Iraq. 

<p>Since April last year, the first stream of brown water has been
flowing down a concretelined canal from Turkey's gigantic
Southeast Anatolian Project (GAP) into the fields of the Harran
plain.  So far it is a mere 2 per cent of the flow of the
Euphrates.  But that is just the beginning.

<p>Turkey has promised that it does not plan to take full advantage
of the fact that it supplies 70 per cent of the waters of the
TigrisEuphrates basin.  The head of the GAP, Olcay Unver, says
he expects Turkey eventually to use about 11 cubic km of water,
or about a third of the previous annual 31 cubic km flow of the
Euphrates.  

<p>What will hurt the Arab states downstream is that until now
Turkey has made only superficial use of the water.  

<p>According to Nurit Kilot, Professor of Geography at Haifa
University in Israel, Syria and Iraq at present use far more than
Turkey, about 5 and 14 cubic km respectively.   However, all
three countries are currently planning irrigation and
hydroelectric projects that would consume 41 cubic kilometres,
about a third more than the total flow of the Euphrates alone.

<p>Of a current estimated cost of $20 billion, $12 billion has been
spent so far.  Three of the 22 dams have been completed,
including the centrepiece of the project, the massive 1.6km
wide, 169metrehigh Ataturk Dam.  Six other dams are under
construction, and work on two more will start this year.

<p>The case for cooperation on optimal use of this limited resource
is further sharpened by the fact that by the time the water
reaches Iraq, at least half will have been degraded by exposure
to agricultural salts and chemicals.  There is also the question
of wastage through seepage and evaporation.  Currently, the
figure for wastage is 10 per cent but it could rise to 20 per
cent by the time all the dams are finished.  

<p>If an allround agreement cannot be reached, dammedup lakes
totalling the size of more than two years' flow of the Nile will
eventually lie shrinking in the scorching Middle Eastern sun.<br>
<i>Hugh Pope's article was distributed by Third World Features.</i>


<a name="fishing"></a><br><hr>

<h3>Fishing limits</h3>

<p>The continuing growth in the world's population and a
corresponding rise in demand for fish threaten to push this
valuable source of protein out of reach for the nearly one
billion people  most of them poor  who rely on fish as a
principal source of animal protein, according to a new report
by Population Action International (PAI).

<p>According to the new study, Catching the Limit: Population and
the Decline of Fisheries, population growth will especially
strain the availability of fish in developing nations, where
more than 700 million people already cannot obtain sufficient
calories and nutrients to lead healthy and active lives.

<p>"At the moment, population growth is fuelling about twothirds
of the current growth in demand for fish," says Robert
Engelman, coauthor of the study and director of PAI's
Population and Environment Program.  "As population pressures
on this resource grow, fish prices will continue to climb,
further reducing consumption among the poor.  In the next
century, many species of fish will become luxuries only the
welltodo can afford."

<p>The global fish catch peaked in 1989 at 89 million metric
tonnes and has hovered at around 85 million tonnes since then. 
The UN Food and Agricultural Organization (FAO) estimates that
nearly 70 per cent of the world's conventional fish species 
such as cod, hake and haddock  are already fished up to or
beyond sustainable limits.

<p>Sound conservation and management strategies are central to
ensuring the future health of the fisheries and the
sustainability of fish catches, according to the PAI study. 
Early stabilization of world population would ease all aspects
of managing the world's fisheries into the 21st century and
beyond.  In the area of fisheries management, experts
recommend that governments:

<p>     reduce the throwing away of unwanted fish by encouraging
     methods that discriminate between target and nontarget
     species;
     improve storage and distribution technologies to reduce
     postcatch losses;
     eliminate subsidies that support overcapacity in the
     fishing industry (the world's fishing fleet has doubled
     its size since 1970);
     protect coastal and other fishery habitats by controlling
     development and pollution.

<p>"The Food and Agricultural Organization estimates that 60
million  tonnes of fish is the maximum sustainable harvest of
wild fish that can be captured for human consumption," says
Engelman.  "The international community  and individual
nations  will have to work hard to ensure that we respect
what appear to be the natural limits to fish catches."

<p>Copies of the study are available for purchase from PAI, 1120
19th Street NW, Suite 500, Washington DC 20036.  Tel: 1 202
659 1833, Fax: 1 202 293 1795.

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>
Saving the Albatross

<p>Concern is growing for the continued survival of more than 13
species of albatross and a number of other seabirds which
frequent the Southern Oceans and the Pacific.  The principle
cause of this decline is know to be bycatch resulting from
longline fisheries.  

<p>Recorded declines in albatross populations at breeding
colonies have alarmed the scientific community and a real
possibility exists for the extinction of one or more species
within the next few decades.  Many albatross are killed as
they are caught by the baits of longline tuna fishing boats
and drown.  Currently, an estimated 44,000 albatrosses are
killed each year from this alone (including an estimated 10
per cent of the world's Wandering Albatross).

<p>WWF is calling on the Southern Ocean tuna fishing nations and
the fishing industry to take measures that will dramatically
reduce albatross deaths as a matter of international priority. 
"There is almost no time left to save this magnificent
wanderer of the world's oceans." said Dr Ray Nias, Director of
Conservation at WWF Australia.  This organization recently
completed a project to track the endangered Wandering
Albatross and discovered that it achieves voyages of over 1000
kilometres each day over open water.

<p>Work to develop bycatch mitigation devices, such as tori
poles (streamers that scare birds from the sinking baits) and
nightsetting is being carried out with some success.  The use
of such methods, and others such a closing off areas around
breeding colonies, will be essential if the extinction of the
albatross is to be avoided.

<p><i>For more information contact WWF Australia, Level 10, 812
Bridge Street, Sydney, NSW 2000, Australia.  Tel: 2 247 6300,
Fax: 2 247 8778.</i>
