<html>

<header>

<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>

</header>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Switzerland</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the

National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.

<br> 

<h5> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.

1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen

European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The

report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The

Hague, the Netherlands.

</h5>

<hr>

<h3>Contents:</h3>

<ul>

<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Swiss Development Cooperation</a>

<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>

<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>

<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>

<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"></a>

</ul><p>



<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Swiss Development Cooperation</h3>



Official Swiss development cooperation started in the early 1960s, based on a strong voluntary and

charitable tradition and on Switzerland's role as an international humanitarian intermediary. Public support

for development cooperation has always been active, as can be judged from the population's high financial

contributions and active political participation. Although attention was rather focused on emergencies and

disasters, there is a shift away from traditional development issues to international environmental problems,

economic interdependence and consequences of consumption and production patterns of Northern countries

for the South. Government and NGOs are very active in development education, and their information

activities underline their very independent position. For instance, the accession of Switzerland in 1992 to the

Bretton Woods institutions is not only acclaimed in official documents, but also critically followed with

regard to the institution's internal functioning and their role in poverty alleviation. 

<p> 

Net official development assistance in 1992 stood at US $ 1 139 million, or 0.46 per cent of GNP, including

Switzerland's first year's contributions to the IMF and World Bank. Since the 1980s, ODA grew

considerably (in 1987 0.27 per cent of GNP). However, the target of 0.4 per cent of GNP, formulated in

1992 at UNCED, will not be reached in 2000. Due to economic constraints, the ODA budget for the period

1993 - 1996 will reach a level between 0.34 - 0.35 per cent of GNP. Over the years multilateral

contributions amounted to around one-third of ODA; in 1992 to 41 per cent. Since Switzerland's accession

to the Bretton Woods institutions, a permanent shift towards more multilateral cooperation is presently being

discussed. 

<p>

<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>

<p>

Swiss development cooperation programmes are managed by two federal ministries. The Directorate for

Development Cooperation and Humanitarian Aid, known as the Swiss Development Cooperation (SDC,

created in 1961) which comes under the competence of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. SDC is responsible

for technical cooperation, parts of the financial cooperation, and humanitarian assistance, amounting to 77

per cent of total Swiss aid in 1992. The Federal Office for Foreign Economic Affairs (OFAEE) in the

Ministry of Public Economy is responsible for a major part of financial support, amounting to around 20 per

cent of total Swiss aid in 1992. A small but growing fraction of the total aid (4.1 per cent in 1992) is

managed by the Federal Ministry of Finance, the Federal Ministry of Education and other ministries, and

2.0 per cent of total aid (in 1992) by the Municipalities and Cantons. Swiss emergency aid is managed by a

special Division of SDC, that takes autonomous decisions on the basis of a multiannual credit separately

from the cooperation budget voted by Parliament.

<p>

Implementation is done on the basis of subsidiarity: the Federal Government is not allowed to do things

which can be done by other institutions in Swiss society. Project preparation, implementation and evaluation

are mainly carried out by NGOs, consultants and enterprises, through various arrangements. Traditionally

the Government has a job-sharing relationship with the NGOs. SDC also directly finances international

NGOs and NGOs in developing countries. Specific aspects of the aid programme are implemented by other

ministries, for instance scholarships and the Global Environment Facility by the Ministry of the Interior. In

concentration countries the SDC has Coordination Offices for implementation. 

<p>

Both offices, the SDC and the OFAEE have a policy planning division. Consultants, NGOs and research

institutes are involved in policy planning. Allocations of responsibilities between the ministries, as well as

between the Government and outside groups (institutes, NGOs, enterprises) are finely tuned. These careful

processes of coordination may result in time consuming procedures. Two bodies that manage parts of the

financial aid and also have a coordinating function are the Export Risk Guarantee Commission and the

Board of the National Bank. 

<p>

<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>

<p>

Switzerland has a Consultative Commission on Development Cooperation for the SDC. One Sub-Committee

follows the implementation of the Debt Reduction Facility (created in 1991) and another Sub-Committee

follows Swiss policies in the Bretton Woods institutions. The Commission was established in 1976, when the

Federal Law on International Cooperation was accepted by Parliament. It is the Commission's task to advise

the Government on development cooperation policy, to scrutinise the objectives and priorities of

development cooperation, and to draw up recommendations on its own initiative. The Commission

contributes to the preparation of policy documents before final versions are written and sent to Parliament.

<p>

The Advisory Commission has 15 Members including Members of Parliament from all political parties,

representatives from the business-community, trade-unions, the research community, from one umbrella

NGO, and from other groups in Swiss society that have an interest in development cooperation. Members

are appointed by the Government for a four year period, with a maximum of four periods. The

Commission's secretariat is located at the Policy and Research Section of the Policy and Planning Division

of the SDC. The Head of the Policy and Research Section is the - part-time - Executive Secretary of the

Commission.

<p>

The Commission generally meets 4 times a year, unless specific issues warrant extra meetings. The agenda

is prepared by the Secretary in consultation with the Director General of SDC and the Chairman of the

Commission. The Chairman can draw up its own agenda and raise specific topics for discussion. Its mandate

allows the Commission to go beyond the policy areas of the SDC: it has right of initiatives, although

restricted. It can present its views to other ministries or the Government. The Sub-commission on the

Bretton Woods institutions meets around ten times a year. It is not known whether the Commission has its

own budget and information gathering activities. Presently the Commission prepares documents for the

coming UN Conference on Population and Development, the Social Summit, and the World Conference on

Women and Development. Documents are being prepared on world trade and the GATT. Each December

the Commission discusses the country reports of SDC and the various instruments of development

cooperation.

<p>

The results of the Commission's discussions are laid down in protocols for the officials of the ministries

concerned and for members of the Government. They are for internal use only and are very seldom

published. Beside this Commission, only one other coordinating body is known, the Committee on Foreign

Economic Policy which advises the Government on questions of trade and exports.

<p>

Parliament actively debates issues of development cooperation, although it appears to concentrate more on

general foreign policy matters than on specific topics of development cooperation. The long process of

decision making by consensus may generate a sense of superfluity of discussions in Parliament. 

<p>

<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>

<p>

Switzerland's many NGOs have a long standing and effective relationship with the Government for

implementation of projects and programmes. In the 1950s traditional Swiss NGOs, such as Helvetas,

Swisscontact, Swissaid and a number of Church-related NGOs, directed their attention from Europe to the

Third World. In later years many solidarity groups and voluntary sending organisations were founded. There

are around 165 development NGOs. Governmental NGO programmes are managed by the SDC. 

<p>

The SDC co-finances projects of individual NGOs (8.2 per cent of bilateral assistance in 1992), finances

their general costs, and contracts NGOs for SDC projects. In 1991 27.5 per cent of the total public and

private development assistance was received and spent by NGOs. There is only one umbrella-type NGO

organisation taking part in a formal policy dialogue with the Federal Government, the Swiss Aid Agencies

Coalition (representing five NGOs). The Coalition is also represented in the Consultative Commission and

its Sub-committees, and in the Consultative Committee on Foreign Economic Policy.

<p>

NGOs follow Swiss official development policy critically. They are often initiators of referenda on

development issues. One NGO campaigned, unsuccessfully, against Swiss membership of the World Bank.

In 1989, on the occasion of the 700th Anniversary of the Swiss Confederation, NGOs campaigned

successfully for reducing LDC debt to Switzerland. In 1991 the Parliament approved the establishment of a

Debt Reduction Facility, over and above the regular ODA budget. For three other issues relevant to the

South the required number of signatures for a referendum have been collected: the demand for a complete

halt to Swiss arms exports, the reduction of military expenditure and, third, the protection of bio-diversity

against scientific and commercial exploitation. NGOs opposed with success further budget cuts for 1992.

<p>

The many topics of policy dialogue with the Government include: larger NGO participation in government

commissions and delegations, additional funds for the increase in multilateral contributions and for the

growing costs of peacekeeping, evaluation of multilateral and of financial aid activities, World Bank policy

and poverty alleviation, and implementation of ecologically sustainable development in Switzerland as well.

<p>

According to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey 24 institutes in Switzerland qualify as Development Research

and Training Institutes. In 1993, SDC and the Swiss National Research Foundation started a programme for

promotion of research on Development and Environment by joint institutions in the South and in

Switzerland. Together with the Swiss Academy of Sciences, SDC promotes research in developing

countries. Many researchers are involved in government programmes and activities.

<p>

<hr>

<H6></a>

<i>Updated on November 7, 1995</i><br>

