<h2>To order ITDG publications, <a href="../itdg/orders.html">click here.</a></h2><a name="international"><hr><br>

<table>
<tr>
<td rowspan=2>
[International Planned Parenthood Federation]</td>

<td valign=top>
</td>

<tr><td><h3> International<br>
Planned<br>
Parenthood<br>
Federation</h3></td></table><p>


<li><b>Vision 2000<br>
Moving forward after Cairo and Beijing</b><br>
The new publication, called Vision 2000: Moving Forward After Cairo and
Beijing, is one of the first by an NGO to examine the relationships between
its own goals and the mandates of the Beijing Conference and the
International Conference on Population andDevelopment (ICPD) in Cairo. <p>
The booklet will guide the work of IPPF member Family Planning Associations (FPAs) in the years ahead, and will act as an advocacy tool to encourage governments to act on the commitments of the Cairo and Beijing Conferences.
It will also be used at other international meetings, such as the UN Habitat II Conference scheduled for June 1996, to remind decision-makers of the promises already made in the areas of women's sexual and reproductive health and rights. 
<p>


In the preface to the booklet, IPPF Secretary General Ingar Brueggemann, describes the ICPD and the Beijing Women's Conference as important milestones in the understanding of the challenges and priorities for human development. The Cairo Conference moved the global debate from the demographic view of population issues toward the broader concept of sexual
and reproductive health including family planning. It emphasised the importance of women's interests, needs and rights as essential components of developmnt. The Beijing Conference went one step further, focusing on    how to achieve equality and empowerment for women in all areas of life.
<p>

The understandings and messages that emerged from the two Conferences are being integrated into IPPF's approach to tackling the six challenges identified in its Strategic Plan, Vision 2000. These challenges, which together form the basis for all of IPPF'swork are: the demand and unmet need in family planning, sexual and reproductive health, unsafe abortion, empowerment of women, youth, and quality of care.
<p>

The prime responsibility for implementing the commitments of the ICPD and Beijing Women's Conference now lies with governments, while non-governmental organizations have a vital role to play in advocating action and monitoring progress on implementation o the promises made. Vision 2000: Moving Forward After Cairo and Beijing will serve as an effective guide by listing specific commitments made by governments and suggesting actions that can be taken by IPPF, its affiliated Family Planning Associations and ther NGOs to help governments fulfil their
promises.
<p>


Copies of the booklet in English or French  (and from April in Spanish and Arabic) may be ordered  by interested organizations and individuals from the IPPF Distribution Unit at the following e-mail address: 
<a href="mailto:csavage@ippf.attmail.com">csavage@ippf.attmail.com
</a><p><br>

