<b><li>Choice and Use-Continuation of Methods of Contraception</b><br>
IPPF has now published a report of this study, which was carried out between 1984 and 1987 in co-operation with family planning associations in six countries: Guatemala, Trinidad and Tobago, Hong Kong, Jordan, Nepal and Kenya.<p>

This multi-centre study was designed to obtain information about factors that affect choice and use-continuation of contraceptive methods. Special emphasis was paid to clients' perceptions of the quality of care provided. The results of the study have assisted programme managers and service providers in the countries involved to gain a deeper insight into their programmes and to identify gaps in the provision of quality of care.<p>

The report has been prepared in order to share the information with family planning programmes worldwide. Available in: English only.<br>
<b>Free of charge<br>
1993 <br>
163 pages 
<p></b><br>



