<br><br><br>
<a name="save"><hr><br>

[Save the Children Fund]<br clear=left><br><br>

<b><li>In Our Own Words<br>
Disability and integration in Morocco</b></b><br>
In Morocco and throughout the world, disabled people are increasingly voicing their claim to rights rather than charity. Quality education, provision of health care, access to housing, transport and employment are essential if disabled people are to play a constructive role in society. In our own words considers:<p>
<ul>

 <b>*</b>the integration of disabled people into communities;
 <b>*</b>the particular needs of disabled women and female caregivers;
 <b>*</b>disabled children's needs and their participation in programmes and services;
 <b>*</b>community-based rehabilitation;
<b>*</b>an analysis of Save the Children's work in Morocco.</ul><p>


As well as being essential reading for local and international organisations and ministries involved in disability work, In our own words will be invaluable for researchers, development practitioners in the field. At a time when seeking the participation of project beneficiaries is recognised as crucial to successful development work, In our own words offers an example of how this has been achieved in Morocco.<br>
<b>£9.95<br>
 December 1995<br>
128 pages<br>
paperback <br>
ISBN 1 899120 21 1</b><br><br><br>


<b><li>Invisible Children<br>
Images and disability</b><br>
<i>"Disabled people should be shown as an ordinary part of life in all forms or representation"&nbsp;</i><br>
This was the conclusion reached at the Invisible Children conference, organised by Integration Alliance and Save the Children. It was attended by more than 150 key image makers. These included TV and film directors, producers, scriptwriter, editors, actors, authors and illustrators who came together with leading members of the Disabled People's Movement.<p>

The report looks at the arguments made for change in the way disabled people are portrayed. Presentations form key speakers include the historical portrayal of disability, and entertaining look at how disability has been presented in children's literature, a moving account of a parent's view  with practical ways forward, and a critique of moving images from TV, film and theatre.<p>

There is a summary of the plenary discussion in which various speakers give examples of the effect of exclusion and stereotyped images and changes that need to a happen.<p>

A practical list of ideas is included as the way forward, along with contact names and addresses and examples of positive representation suggested by members of Integration Alliance.<br>
<b>£5.20  <br>
A4 60 pages  <br>
ISBN 1 899120 19 X</b><p>


