<head>
<title>Protecting children on the Net</title>
</head><a name="top">
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="000000" link="#23238E" alink="#4D4DFF" vlink="#3299CC">
Schools Section<br clear=left>
<br>
<p>
<center><b><font size=+3>POLICING THE INTERNET</font><br>
<h2>Teachers: how to make sure your pupils don't surf into a brothel</h2></b></center>


<br>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<font size=+1>The World-Wide Web is becoming increasingly important for the young, for both educational and entertainment reasons. (Even Santa Claus has a home page.)<p>
But the Web is an anarchic place.  Nobody is making sure unsavoury pictures of sex and violence aren't available on all our computer screens.<hr width=71%>
<p></font>
For many adults, that's not a problem.  But it is for parents - and teachers in charge of other people's children - who want to be sure that kids aren't stumbling across material they wouldn't dream of letting them see on television or in magazines.
<p>
But now there are several software packages that block out unsavoury parts of the Internet. Parents and teachers can rest assured about their children's welfare while the kids surf the rest of the Internet unhindered.  <p>

<i><h3>What are they?</h3></i>

<li><h2><a href="http://www.microsys.com/cyber/">CYBER PATROL</a></h2>
<ul>Cyber Patrol allows parents to choose when and where their children surf.  Parents can block specific times of the day (like peak telephone rate times), specific newsgroups, ftp sites or Web sites.  <p>

And they can also enter a list of 'approved sites' to be surfed around in safety.  The makers even draw up their own updated list of banned sites, which parents can download over the Internet.</ul>

<li><h2><a href="http://www.leaf.co.uk/netnanny.htm">NET NANNY</a> (PC only)</h2>
<ul>Basically, Net Nanny does what you tell her to.  She will do anything from making a note of  a 'forbidden' word in a log-book to actually shutting down the Internet-access program altogether. <p>

Concerned teachers and parents can enter forbidden words - like 'sex' - into a special dictionary, and Net Nanny will take action whenever they are encountered on a page.  (But won't this cause problems for home pages in Middlesex and Essex?  In short, yes.  So Net Nanny's dictionary now includes 'alt.sex' instead.)<p>
</ul>

<li><h2><a href="http://www.solidoak.com/cybersit.htm">CYBERSITTER</a></h2>

<ul>CyberSitter is another filtering program - except that instead of looking for restricted words, it looks for restricted file types, including pictures (gif or jpg files) and encoded images from newsgroups.  It prevents their transfer down the Internet, and keeps your hard disk clean.<p>
A new version is due out soon, which will also block access to pre-defined Web sites.  Click on the title above to find out the latest.<p></ul>

<h2>Oh, and happy surfing....</h2>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<br clear=left><br>



