<Html><Head><Title>&quot;BEYOND RAIN MAN&quot; NATIONAL SURVEY RESULTS</title></head>

<Body  bgcolor="#CCFFCC" link="#336633" vlink="#669966">

<i>The material that follows has been provided by <b><a href="../index.html">The National Autistic
Society</a></b></i>

[nas logo]
<hr>
<b>NEWS RELEASE<br>
Date: 19th November 1996 Ref: NAS/21/96</b>



<h2>&quot;BEYOND RAIN MAN&quot; NATIONAL SURVEY RESULTS</h2>


Today, (2nd December) the first day of Autism Awareness Week,  sees the release of the results of a
national survey  investigating levels of understanding and awareness of autism. The survey, called 'Beyond
Rain Man',   looks at the experiences of carers of people with autism and Asperger syndrome,  the general
public's  awareness and understanding of autistic spectrum disorders and includes interviews with people
with autism, giving an insight into how they perceive the world.  Harris Research Centre carried out the
survey, which was commissioned by The National Autistic Society. 

<p>'Beyond Rain Man' shows that 99% of carers felt the general public have little understanding of what it
is like to care for a person with autism. 84% had experienced people staring at them and 57% had
experienced people making unwelcome comments when out with the person they care for.  These
comments included:

<p>&quot;There should be euthanasia for kids like yours - he'll never be any use to himself or anyone
else.&quot;

<p>&quot;My dog acts better than that.&quot;

<p>&quot;Don't worry - they often don't live long.&quot;

<p>Perhaps not surprisingly, 96% of carers reported their caring responsibilities have put a strain on them
with 87% reporting it has put a strain on their relationship with their spouse or partner and 85% reporting
it has put a strain on their family.  As one carer put it:

<p>&quot;I have lost friends, space to have a normal life, my daughter finds it hard to study, cannot
work. My marriage broke down. My husband left after 25 years of marriage.&quot;

<p>Carers also feel it is extremely difficult to get the support they need, with 83% reporting  they 
have to fight for every service and 82% feeling that the majority of services lack awareness 

<p>of autism or Asperger syndrome.  This was backed up by the findings from the survey of the general
public, with only 7% of those who had heard of autism feeling people with autism receive enough support.
As one parent commented:  

<p> &quot;...education, doctors, paediatricians, speech therapists all (said) there (was) nothing wrong,
that he does not have problems. Asperger syndrome was not diagnosed until he was 16 years old. No
outside support for my son until recently - never having any support for myself or my family.&quot;

<p>'Beyond Rain Man' shows that 96% of the general public have not heard of Asperger syndrome and 35%
have not heard of autism. Whilst it may seem encouraging that 65% have heard of autism, many of these
people were apparently unaware of some of the main characteristics of the condition - e.g. 72% are
unaware it involves obsessive behaviours; 69% are unaware it involves temper tantrums in children and
77% are unaware it involves resistance to change in routine. 

<p>It is seven years since the film 'Rain Man' brought the attention of a wide audience to the condition of
autism. However, it is forty years since autism and Asperger syndrome (a form of autism) were officially
diagnosed. The film certainly helped to raise awareness of the condition; however, it would have been
impossible for the film to present a full picture of the complexity of autistic spectrum disorders.  For
instance, whilst some people with autism do have special abilities, such as those displayed by Raymond,
Dustin Hoffman's character in the film, they comprise a relatively small number - about one in twenty. 
Autistic spectrum disorders are not rare - over 320,000 people in the UK have the condition, which is a
life-long disability. 

<p><small>Editors' Notes:
<ol><li>Advance complimentary copies of 'Beyond Rain Man' are available from the Press Office of The
National Autistic Society. 
<li>A video news release illustrating the survey results is available. Contact Liz Main, Bulletin International on 
0171 278 6070.
<li>A direct radio link will be available on the morning of 2nd December. Geraldine Peacock, Chief Executive
of  the NAS and a parent of a person with autism will be available for interview. Contact James Battison,
Bulletin International on 0171 278 6070.
<li>Awareness raising and fund-raising events are being held around the country. Please call the Press Office
of the NAS for details.  
<li>'Beyond Rain Man'  is available for purchase from the NAS at £5.50 exc p&p.
</ol></small>
<p>
<address>For further information please contact:Ann Stirling, Communications Manager or Angela
O'Brien, Press & PR Officer on 0181 451 1114 : Direct line: 0181 830 4187. </address>
<Hr>

<Address>The National Autistic Society, 276 Willesden Lane, London NW2 5RB <br>
Tel: 0181 451 1114<br>
Email: <b><A href="mailto:nas@clus1.ulcc.ac.uk"> 

nas@clus1.ulcc.ac.uk</a></b></adDRESS><p>

