<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>

</header>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in Italy</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the

National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.

<br> 

<h5> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.

1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen

European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The

report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The

Hague, the Netherlands.

</h5>

<hr>

<h3>Contents:</h3>

<ul>

<li><a href="#org">Organisation of Italian Development Cooperation</a>

<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>

<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>

<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>

<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"></a>

</ul><p>



<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of Italian Development Cooperation</h3>



Official Italian development cooperation started in the 1960s, and was based on considerations of foreign

policy, of which development cooperation forms an integral part. Public support was strong in the 1980s,

but is now declining, apparently under influence of the revelations about management deficiencies and the

existence of parallel political and economic circuits. Reform measures that have been prepared already,

might restore the credibility of the aid organisation. 

<p>

The Government has proposed measures to identify problems and to introduce reforms in the conception,

planning, implementation and organisation of Italy's aid programme. A Special Commission of Experts was

installed in 1992 to examine the programme. In its report to Parliament in February 1993 it has suggested

fundamental changes with regard to the distribution of presently overlapping competencies of government

institutions, simplifying the current complicated administrative procedures, strengthening capacities and

expertise for planning, implementation and evaluation, procurement rules, as well as loosening the narrow

linkages between aid and foreign policy, trade and other national Italian interests, and improving policy

coordination between ministries.

<p>

Italian net official development assistance in 1992 amounted to US $ 4 122 million, which was 0.34 per cent

of GNP. Since the mid-1980s the ODA/GNP ratio had risen notably, reaching 0.42 per cent in 1989. In the

years thereafter actual disbursements fell, which resulted in large amount of undisbursed aid funds.

However, one should bear in mind that figures from different sources may disagree. Aid allocations for the

years 1993 - 1995 are projected to decline further to 0.20 per cent of expected GNP. The proportion of

Italian multilateral aid was always about 40 per cent of ODA, consisting mainly of compulsory

contributions. These rose in 1992 to 14 per cent of ODA to the EU, and to 27 per cent of ODA to other

multilateral organisations.

<p>

The proposed reductions in the total budget have to be borne mainly by the bilateral programme. One of the

reasons for the reductions, imposed by Parliament, was the apparent lack of capacity of the administration to

manage the growing number of projects in the past years. It is doubtful whether these commitments,

together with a decreasing budget, will leave much room for new policies and new projects in the coming

years. 

<p>

<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>

<p>

Italian aid policy remains at present based on an Act from 1987 that established development cooperation as

part of Italian foreign policy, and that refers to the principles of solidarity among peoples, and of human

rights laid down by the UN and confirmed by the Lom&#233; Conventions. The 1987 law also shaped the

administrative structure. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs is responsible for development cooperation. The

central unit for the management of Italy's aid programme is the Directorate-General of Development

Cooperation (DGCS) in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs. The DGCS has 19 offices. Three Undersecretaries

of State assist the Minister of Foreign Affairs, one of which handles development cooperation. His position

does not appear to be a strong one. This Undersecretary is also in charge of policies in several other areas.

<p>

The directorate DGCS is also in charge of aid implementation. However, due to lack of capacities at the

DGCS and the embassies, implementation in recipient countries is left to a large extent to private

enterprises, consultants and NGOs.

<p>

Apart from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs three other ministries are involved in development cooperation:

the Treasury, the Ministry of the Budget and Economic Planning, and Ministry of Foreign Trade, the latter

through the Medium Term Loan Bank and the Bank of Italy. Allocations of responsibilities are not known. 

<p>

The law of 1987 created two interministerial committees for decision making as well as a Consultative

Committee. The Interministerial Committee for Development Cooperation (CICS) is chaired by the Minister

of Foreign Affairs, and comprises the Ministers of the Budget and Economic Planning, of Foreign Trade,

and of the Treasury. The CICS mainly sets priorities for the geographical and sectoral distributions of aid.

The second committee, the Steering Committee (or Directing Committee) decides on the allocations of the

annual amount of aid, within the framework established by CICS. The Steering Committee is chaired by the

Under-Secretary for Development Cooperation, and consists of the Directors-General of the same ministries

that are represented in the CICS, and of members of the Consultative Committee.

<p>

Since Italy traditionally has intensive trade relations with developing countries, the Interministerial

Committee for Foreign Economic Policy (CIPES) also plays an important role. After a reorganisation in

1990, a second reorganisation of the aid administration is currently under way, which includes new

mechanisms of interministerial coordination.  

<p>

Systematic planning of country programmes is absent. Bilateral cooperation is based until now on

negotiations with recipient countries. There is no system for regular ex post evaluation. External institutions

have carried out some evaluations, mainly focusing on disbursement aspects. Due to lack of staff, it is

difficult at the moment to integrate evaluation findings into aid management. Proposal are being made for

the establishment of an Evaluation Unit. 

<p>

<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>

<p>

The Consultative Committee on International Cooperation is a consultative body chaired by the Minister of

Foreign Affairs or the Under-Secretary in charge of development cooperation. The Committee has 45

members: five experts appointed by the NGOs, three by the major trade union confederations; ten members

are appointed by institutions and private enterprises operating in development cooperation; five members

belong to the public sector, and five to the private sector; three members are appointed by the Interregional

Commission - representing Italian Regions; one expert is appointed by the National Universities Council,

and one by the National Research Council; one expert represents the Overseas Agronomic Institute, nine

experts represent the State Administrations - civil servants of other ministries involved in development

cooperation - and lastly, both the Director General for Development Cooperation and the Director General

for Economic Affairs of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs are members of the Committee. Members are

appointed by the Minister of Foreign Affairs, following the nomination of the organisations and institutions.

<p>

It is the task of the Consultative Committee to formulate and express opinions about the planning and the

measures elaborated by the Steering Committee, and about the annual report of the CICS. Exerting one of

its tasks, the Consultative Committee informed Parliament in December 1993 that it could not approve the

Annual Report 1992 of the CICS because of a general scarcity of data, and insufficient explanations on the

policies pursued.

<p>

Until recently the Committee had hardly been consulted by the Government. It seems however, that with the

revision of the aid programme and its management, the Committee obtained more relevance. In 1993 it has

established several new working groups for various sections of cooperation. The Government has stated the

intention to take the results of the Committee's work into account. 

<p>

Until recently the role of Parliament in discussing development cooperation has been very limited. Annually

it voted the funds for the aid budget. Discussions on aid programme policies or planning did not take place.

Recently Parliamentarians appear to take more interest in the use of funds and the planning of programmes.

<p>

<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>

<p>

There are many, relatively small, NGOs in Italy. About 120 organisations are eligible for Government co-

funding of their development activities. Another 35 organisation requested that status. Many more

organisations do not seek such status. Private fund raising from the Italian public represents only 12 per cent

(1989-1991) of their total income; the remainder originates from the EU, churches, municipalities, and other

ministries then the MFA. Government funding for NGO activities has been severely curtailed in the years

1992-1993, and sometimes stopped altogether.

<p>

There are no umbrella organisations acting as representatives of their members in dialogue with the

Government. The main vehicle for the policy dialogue is the Consultative Committee, in which NGOs are

represented. There are a number of NGO networks, such as the Catholic Federation Christian Organisations

for International Voluntary Service (FOCSIV), the secular urban based Coordination International

Organisations for Development (COCIS), and the Coordination of International Solidarity People Initiatives

(CIPSI) with small, mainly Catholic NGOs. The Consultative Committee has a working group for NGOs,

chaired by a NGO representative. The working group advises, among other things, the Minister of Foreign

Affairs on eligibility of NGOs. This membership allows the NGO representative to participate in the work

of the interministerial Steering Committee. NGOs participate currently in the discussion on new policies and

structure of development cooperation. Although some structures for policy dialogue do exist, and many

government projects and policy concepts originate from NGO thinking and their partnership relations in the

Third World, the formal and recognised influence of NGOs does not appear to be considerable.

<p>

According to the 1991 OECD/EADI survey, 38 institutes in Italy qualify as Development Research and

Training Institutes, some of which are known to be involved in consultancy work for the Government, or to

undertake policy studies. The Centre for Studies in International Politics (CeSPI), an independent research

institute, in 1991 presented a paper with criteria for a new government policy, during an international

conference in Rome, organised by the Government. The Institute for International Economic Cooperation

and Development (ICEPS) provides information on economic cooperation and development, and fosters

Italian initiatives abroad, especially in developing countries. It is composed of prominent members from

politics, culture and private enterprise. 

<p>

As explained the Italian business community appears well represented in various aid institutions until now,

and its interests are integrated in development policy. However, the business community also feels the need

for reforms in the organisation and procedures of aid. A study by the Directorate for Technical Cooperation

of the IRI, the main industrial state holding company, stressed in 1992 inter alia the need for overhauling

the DGCS.

<p>

<hr>

<H6></a>

