<body>
<title>Poor in Health - Section 2</title> 
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><TABLE BORDER=2>
<TR>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<i>The material that follows has been provided by  <a href="scf_info.html"> Save the Children Fund</i></a>
<p></center>
<hr>

<br>
<h2>WHAT'S GOING WRONG?</h2>

<h3>2.1 PROBLEMS WITH AID</h3>

The poorest countries are gripped by poverty and unable to compete in the global market place. And yet they exist within a system which forces them - through structural adjustment programmes and debt repayment - to compete 'equality' (<a href="box3.html">see also "two definitions")</a>, in spite of their tiny government revenues.<p>
<p>
There is an argument that they should spend more on health, and less on defence, for example. But the reality is that with most of their money swallowed up by priorities set by the West (such as debt repayments) and other indispensable parts of the national programme, governments in the least developed countries have little room for manoeuvre within their budgets.<p>
<p>

Even if they were to increase their health budgets, they would still not be able to provide adequate health care: if Nepal doubled its health budget, it would still fall $10 per head below the World Bank suggested minimum.<p>


As the market-led model of development is unlike to change, the priority now must be to look at the vital extra source of funding - overseas aid.<p>

<h3>Inadequate and inappropriate investment</h3>

The poorest countries have been dealt a double blow, described above: not only are many of them at a juncture where their own resources cannot meet the needs of their children; but also levels of international aid to low income countries are falling.<p>


In 1996, investment of international aid by donor countries is inadequate. But the problem is not just the lack of resources. It is also a question of how development aid has been, and is, spent. Successful long-term investment in health should:

<ul type=circle>
<li>be appropriate to the context into which it is delivered;
<li>be affordable  for countries to sustain;
<li>build up local infrastructure and health and welfare systems;
<li>work through systems that are locally financed.
</ul>

Much of the investment during the 1980s did not meet these criteria. High cost programmes by western governments fragmented public health sector systems in developing countries into a series of 'quick fix' solutions, one-off treatments and high profile, big budget campaigns with unsustainable targets. Known as vertical programmes (<a href="box3.html">see also "two definitions")</a> these often addressed one problem in isolation rather than as part of a wider problem of poverty and welfare.<p>


The problem of donor-driven vertical programmes, difficult to sustain, is borne out by a national family planning campaign in Nepal. Encouraged by international donors, the National Planning Commission in Nepal set a fertility target for the millennium.<p>

An average of six children per woman will supposedly be reduced to 2.5 children by the year 2000 in a country of over 20 million people where 237,000 couples use contraception. To achieve this, six times as many people will need to use contraceptives as do now and the level of use must increase fivefold. Nepal spends $5.85 per user on contraception. The cost per year of meeting and sustaining the target would be $16.4 million or roughly $0.90 per head - the equivalent of all of Nepal's government spending on health.<p>

Even a more modest target of 4.6 births per woman by the year 2000 would need three times as many people to use contraceptives and the level of use to double costing $9.1 million, roughly $0.50 per head or half of the government's health expenditure. Countries as poor as Nepal cannot sustain such ambitious donor-led programmes - even for essential basic health services - at current levels of expenditure.<p>


Many such vertical programmes had a design fault: they crumbled once the donor departed. They budgeted for capital costs such as building a health centre without recognising that the burden of running that centre would eventually prove too much for the government. If these running costs were not met, the centre would not be sustainable.<p>


As the history of tuberculosis control shows (<a href="case_b.html"see case study b - "controlling TB")</a>health technologies cannot exist in a health policy vacuum; they must be part of an appropriate system for health care delivery and affordable within the context of the specific country.<p>

<a name="underinvestment"><h3>Under investment in running costs</h3></a>

Frequently, analysis of the cost of treatment only concentrates on the net cost of drugs to treat a single disease. The running costs of getting the drugs to the child - the delivery system - are all too often absent from the balance sheet.<p>


The value of vaccines, antibiotics and other medical technologies in the control of common diseases is beyond question. At face value, any treatment which saves a life for a handful of dollars must be money well spent. But for many countries, the cost of these technologies alone - without budgeting for the running costs - can be prohibitive. For example:<p>

<ul type=circle>
<li>In Ethiopia, a country overwhelmed by TB and showing no signs of being able to control the epidemic, the drugs needed to effect a cure and stop a person being contagious would consume the whole national budget.
</ul><p>

In Britain, the running costs of health care consume over two-thirds of the overall health budget - between £500 and £600 per person per year. In poorer countries, in the absence of an infrastructure, running costs can be an even higher proportion. For example:

<ul type=circle>
<li>In a country as poor as Ghana, the government spends $3.20 of its £3.60 per person on running costs - nearly 90 per cent of overall government health spending.
</ul>

<p>
But in many of the poorest countries, the complete neglect of running costs means the health system cannot work. They are the first costs to be cut in a period of economic decline or during structural adjustment programmes. And basic essential health services within the World Bank package become unaffordable (<a href="case_c.html">see Case Study C)</a>.<p>

Save the Children fully supports the work to immunise children and is actively involved in extending immunisation to children around the world. Where resources are in place to foot the bill, it is without question money well spent. But the running costs for governments in the poorer countries to reach the year 2000 target and sustain immunisation of all children are more than they can afford.<p>

<table border=6>
