<head>
<title>Africa takes a male-friendly approach to family planning</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<h3>International<br>Planned<br>Parenthood<br>Federation</h3>
<i>The material that follows has been provided by <a href="../ippf_info.html">IPPF</a></i>
<br clear=left>

<hr>



<h1>Africa takes a male-friendly approach to family planning</h1>

<b>by Deryck Onyango Omuodo</b><p>








Men are more like to be in favour of family planning - and to use a method themselves - if programmes and services are provided through "men only" clinics, and educational programmes are conducted men-to-men.  This has been demonstrated in several studies and by the popularity of such approaches when they have been introduced.  <p>




Human beings will resist changes which threaten their security. Very often in the field of family planning, programme objectives contain words or slogans which threaten men.  The men end up rejecting programmes which, if presented in different ways, would gain their full support and participation.  
<p>



Programmes which empower women to deny men their human rights and freedoms are not male-friendly.  Instead, those working in family planning should encourage men to accept, respect and promote the sexual and reproductive rights and freedoms of women.  Families thrive on sharing, and programmes of change could usefully focus on persuading men to become more involved in reproductive health issues and in sharing the burden of family planning with their wives or partners.  
<p>



The following excerpts from taped conversations among educated African men on changing male responsibility illustrate the level of male dominance and the significance of fears of threats to their security.<p>





<blockquote><i>"If you are a man you are the boss in the home. You decide what the family should look like. You decide how many children you should have. You decide where your children should go to school, or if they should go to school or not. You are the boss."</i> <br>(Journalist from Kenya).</blockquote><p>



<blockquote><i>"...The man ...is the major decision-maker ... he determines almost everything that happens in the family... Even when his wife is working, and earning income, she is still subject to the decisions of the husband. ... Even if she makes more money than the man, she is expected to submit to her husband." </i><br>(Demographer from Nigeria).</blockquote><p>




<blockquote><i>"If you look at the real situation, most of the career women have problems with their families because the man becomes kind of inferior.., you find the marriages having problems. The man becomes more comfortable when he has economic power." </i><br>(Finance official from Malawi).</blockquote><p>




Male-friendly approaches should address the fears of men. For example, there is a deep-rooted fear that contraception endows women with too much freedom and so reduces a husband's span of control over a wife's sexuality. Some men believe that contraception causes unfaithfulness and that continuous child-bearing places unfaithfulness under control.<p>




While it is essential to promote programmes which empower women to exercise control over  their fertility, such programmes can improve their chances of success if implemented alongside educational programmes which help men to understand the rationale and need for them to be sensitive and responsive to the needs of women, and why sexual and reproductive health decisions should be the joint responsibility of men and women. <p>




The concept of rights can imply militancy, so care must be taken if statements of programme objectives and goals are phrased in terms of rights.  A process of change has to be courted through education and persuasion.  The more men are reminded of women's reproductive health rights without proper explanation, the more they will resist positive change.<p>




Male-friendly and negotiated approaches can speed up the move towards gender equality in matters of planned parenthood.  Promoting spousal communication will encourage mutual understanding between husbands and wives on sexual and reproductive health decisions and practices.  Family life education programmes which promote respectful and harmonious partnership between males and females, young and old can be a good starting point.  As well as educating men about the benefits of sharing more equally in family life, such programmes should help family members understand their sexuality and inform them how to protect themselves from unwanted pregnancies, sexually transmitted diseases and other sexual and reproductive health problems. 
<p>



In several African countries, projects are being run which take a male-friendly approach.   In Togo, the family planning association is using the media to sensitize specific male groups, aiming in particular to instil positive attitudes towards family planning in traditional and religious leaders. The family planning association in Ghana is providing information to targeted groups of men in various locations and has reported improved male involvement in terms of increased awareness and knowledge turned into practice. The forerunners to this approach were successful initiatives with male plantation managers to get their workers to promote and practise family planning, and a Daddies Club aimed at persuading men to share in parental responsibility. <p>




In Swaziland the family planning association runs a programme to dispel fears and rumours among men and assure them of the safety of contraception.  Men-to-men teams join women in targeting male audiences in specific locations with family planning education and messages.<p>




The Sierra Leone family planning association has achieved successful results conveying messages about preventing sexually transmitted diseases and the benefits to family well-being of family planning at male-specific group meetings, film shows, lectures and visits.  Other associations have used drama, song, puppetry and other forms of entertainment, as well as the print media, audio-visual presentations, awareness seminars, training workshops, advocacy and social marketing, to reach men. Income-generation, advocacy and workers' education are other initiatives undertaken. <p>




 The most direct approach is being carried out  by the Family Planning Association of Kenya, which is providing "male only" services at its special clinics in three district locations in the country.  This bold, male-friendly venture expects the same positive results reported by other "male only" service outlets.<p>




Women, too, are calling for male-friendly approaches.  At the Africa Regional Conference on Women, Islam and Family Planning, organized by the International Planned Parenthood Federation in 1995,  men were urged to become more involved in the implementation of reproductive health and family planning programmes.  Women attending the conference realized that men-by-men and men-for-men programmes could achieve good results.<p>




Male-friendly approaches can go a long way to moderate societal and cultural barriers that prevent men take joint decisions with women on family planning and sexual and reproductive health, and sharing the responsibility with them.  And they can achieve far better results than programmes which threaten men's security and which diminish their feeling of masculinity. <p>










 
<hr><p>

