<html>
<head>
<title>YES - Youth Home Page</title>
<body text="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#8E2323" vlink="#4E2F2F">
</head>

<center><h1>The STEP Project</h1></center>
<br><br clear=left>


STEP, The Painswick Inn, Gloucester Street,<br>
Stroud, Gloucestershire GL5 1QG<br>
Tel: 01453 759941,  Fax: 01453 759211<p>


STEP is affiliated to the Painswick Inn Project,<br>
an initiative of Shire Training Workshops<br><br><br>


<h2>STEP - Project Proposal</h2>

<h3>1. Outline</h3>

Swaziland Theatre Experience Project will provide a one year programme to motivate, train and develop the individual potential of a group of unemployed young people. The UK base for this project is Stroud, Gloucestershire.<p>
Following a six month preparation period, the group will go to Swaziland in Southern Africa where they will work together with a group of local young people to refurbish and bring to life a defunct theatre in Mbabane. It is intended that this pioneer project will lead the way for further self-help schemes for disadvantaged young adults.

<h3>2. The People</h3>

Larry Leighton, the founder and co-ordinator of this project, has nurtured for some years the wish to bring together his experience of living and working in Africa and of working with disadvantaged young people.<p>

The possibility of transforming the Swaziland Theatre Club facilities, which have been virtually unused for 4-5 years, into a Community Theatre and Arts Centre, provides an ideal opportunity to establish and international, cross-cultural project. <p>

The Theatre Club was founded in 1963, opened in 1964, and for a quarter of  a century was active as a centre for drama. Its decline and neglect over the past few years has been due to a diminishing membership and an apparent lack of enthusiasm and commitment by those remaining to be open to, aware of and responsive to the needs and potential in the local community. However, in response to our initiative, there is now a new, enthusiastic Theatre Management Team (TMT) in place who are committed to redevelopment and who have invited People's Educational Theatre (PET), a local community-based youth theatre group, to participate in the project.

<h3>3. The Link with Swaziland</h3>

In Swazi culture, the elements of story-telling, dance, music and singing, figure strongly. Add to this the rapidly changing social, cultural and political scene in Southern Africa and the desire, particularly among the young, to find new, valid and acceptable forms of exploring and expressing social and environmental issues, and accessible centre for the performing arts would be highly valued. As this is Swaziland's only theatre and near the centre of the capital, Mbabane, this potential becomes emphasised.<p>


Swaziland is currently struggling with the difficulties of integrating traditional and modern ways of life. As a result of this and other social, economic and political issues, their young people are experiencing great vulnerability and powerlessness in the face of social problems such as high unemployment, crime, AIDS, poverty, homelessness, drugs and conflicting social and cultural values. <p>

These experiences are reinforced by growing environmental challenges including deforestation, drought and pollution. <p>

Against this bleak background, the opportunities for personal development, self-esteem and true confidence building for such unemployed young people within the context of a community cultural project, are great. They would be suitably enriched and enhanced by working together with a group of similar aged individuals from another country and culture who have encountered similar problems at home but have begun the process of challenging them. As a result they would then be well-placed and motivated to participate in local economic regeneration and the struggle for self-reliance.<p>



The young people from England will mostly come from Stroud, which is somewhat similar to Mbabane in that it is a small town that straggles out along beautiful rural valleys. The lack of opportunities for long-term meaningful employment and suitable available housing, the apparent meaninglessness of life and constant social challenges that they experience in England will find a different hue when they meet what their Swazi partners experience.


<h3> Benefits and Beneficiaries.</h3>

STEP aims:<p>

<ul>
<li>to provide a substantial programme of training, motivation, orientation and confidence-building for approx. 15 young people from the UK between the ages of 18 and 28.<p>


<li>to share and develop the experiences of this programme with a similar group of young people in Swaziland.<p>


<li>to create an experience of community awareness for the participants through providing for the community.<p>


<li>to provoke and promote cross-cultural, international and racial awareness which will lead to a sense of purpose, understanding, openness and acceptance.</ul><p>


The overall objective for each project participant will be to establish a creative yet sustainable attitude, approach, and strategy to meet and survive today's ever-shifting world. To foster and encourage this, individual programmes and projects will feature throughout the year and be woven into group and project objectives. The available skills to be pursued will range through:<p>


<ul><li>administration: book-keeping, computing etc.<p>


<li>craft: carpentry, painting and decorating, costume, mask-making, lighting, sound, photography etc.<p>


<li>
Performing arts: acting, story-telling, music, movement, voice etc.<p>


<li>Social communication, leadership, understanding, co-operation, negotiation etc.</ul><p>


These are the benefits to the participants in the project, but clearly the beneficiaries will also be the communities within which they will work. <p>
In the UK, foundations will be laid for the STEP Youth Theatre during the preparation period and on our return. This will provide a resource for current and future opportunities for other local young people. <p>

The Stroud Community as a whole will clearly benefit also from this. In Swaziland, the aim is to create a sustainable community theatre and Arts Centre. This would provide a rich cultural resource for not only the community of Mbabane but also the whole of Swaziland in that travelling performances and exhibitions could be developed and venture out throughout the country. Furthermore, realistic new employment and training opportunities would arise there. The presence of  a group of enthusiastic young people from Britain seeking inspiration from the Swazi people, their culture and environment could also inspire new confidence and self esteem in the community.<p>

<center>
<br><br clear=left>
