<html>

<header>

<title>Policy review and development cooperation</title>

</header>

<hr>

<H2><center><p></a>

Policy review and development cooperation:<br>Quality accorded priority</h2>

<h4><i>NAR Secretariat</i>

<p>

Source: <i>In Brief: Information from the NAR</i><br>No. 11, June 1995</h4>

<h5>The full text of the report in English, as well as a list of other publications, are available free of

charge from the Council's secretariat: E-mail: nar-dgis@dgis.minbuza.nl</h5>

</center>

<hr>

<h3>Background</h3>



At the beginning of June 1995 the National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the

Netherlands took the initiative of submitting to the Minister for Development Cooperation, J.P. Pronk,  an

advisory document (recommendation no. 105) entitled Review of foreign policy: a changing approach to

development cooperation in a changing world. It had been prompted to do so by a meeting which had taken

place the previous October with members of the Permanent Committee on Foreign Affairs of the Lower

House of Parliament.

<p>

<h3>Determining the place of development cooperation ('Major review')</h3>



The globalisation of the world economy has not left developing countries untouched. Quite the reverse in

fact; some of these nations are at the forefront of this process. Developing countries' economies are growing

more rapidly than those of rich countries, and this trend looks set to continue. They will increasingly fuel

the progress of the global economy. The familiar socioeconomic issues have been supplemented by other

questions which are making ever more urgent calls upon our attention: these include the refugee issue,

peacekeeping, the protection of human rights, democratisation and good governance. The question posed by

the National Advisory Council focuses on whether the instruments of Dutch foreign policy are still adequate

to deal with these issues, and on their effect on development cooperation.

<p>

Some of what were formerly styled Third World countries have reached or are about to reach a stage at

which they will no longer require special treatment in international relations, such as preferential measures

in the field of trade. It is easier for them to finance their development through the international private

capital market. These countries can be held responsible for poverty alleviation within their own borders.

Official flows of capital can be concentrated on a smaller group of developing countries. This should in no

way deflect efforts from the goal of global liberalisation of the movement of goods, services and capital.

While some economies are growing rapidly, others are being left behind. The gap is growing fast. Each

year sees an increase in the number of the poor; in the seventies this was estimated at 700 million, but their

ranks have now swelled to some 1,300 million. Of this latter group, 750 million men, women and children

go hungry every day. More attention must be given than hitherto to those left behind in the race for

development, to ensure that they do not entirely lose their chance of catching up. 

<p>

The end of the Cold War has shaken the international political map up considerably. Domestic and

international conflicts have broken out, altered or stopped. Undreamt of forces have been unleashed. The

stable picture hitherto presented by the international legal order has been replaced by a dynamic which

works sometimes towards peace, but more frequently towards increasing conflict and anarchy. An urgent

need has arisen to set the parameters for economic development, such as peacekeeping operations, good

governance, domestic legal order, social development, social integration and sustainability.

<p>

The National Advisory Council believes that the aim of Dutch foreign policy should be to promote the

international legal order and to achieve a more equitable distribution of the ecoscope. Development

cooperation is one of the instruments of that policy. In addition to the above-mentioned considerations, it is

important to realise that well-regulated international relations are very much in the Netherlands' interests.

Such a situation would be to the country's advantage, but it also places upon us obligations which cannot be

shrugged off as someone else's responsibility.

<p>

Development aid has become a staple instrument of international cooperation. Some countries, such as South

Korea and Taiwan, have benefited from it in the early stages of their development. Others have failed to

develop, for various reasons. Sometimes such failure has been attributable to the country itself; sometimes,

though, it has been the result of manipulative aid. In the past, the humanitarian principle underlying aid has

sometimes been made subservient to economic or political considerations. In this respect the current

tendency to remove the barriers formerly segregating policy fields may prove very beneficial - always

assuming that such policy 'mergers' lead to behavioural changes, that is.

<p>

The field of emergency aid/peacekeeping operations is a good example of an area which would benefit from

merged policy. The many organisations active in the field are in themselves efficient bodies. Efficiency

could however be improved by creating a single liaison office for international and national organisations in

situations where speed is of the essence. At present there is no such office in the Netherlands; the

implementation of such operations is channelled through various ministries and ministers. The National

Advisory Council proposes that the possibility of a liaison office, which would be responsible for policy

preparation and decision-making, be studied.

<p>

Another effect of globalisation has been an increase in the dissemination of information. In turn this has

greatly influenced people's aspirations with regard to participation in decision-making, good governance and

protection of human rights, and it has also made them more articulate and more ready to demand their

rights. Social development should be an independent element of development cooperation. Non-

governmental organisations can do much to promote such development. Efforts should continue to focus on

the development of criteria and the setting of priorities in the entire field of political and social development.

<p>

<h3>Tasks of development cooperation ('Minor review')</h3>



The central aim of development cooperation should be structural poverty alleviation within the parameters of

sustainability and political development (good governance, human rights, democratisation and social

development). An element of enlightened self-interest is permissible here, provided that it is not hidden, that

it is controllable, that it serves a purpose, and, most importantly, that it is subordinate to the real objective.

This aim should be furthered, just as in the eighties, by allocating 0.9 percent of GNP for traditional aid,

and 0.1 percent of GNP for international cooperation in the field of the environment. This should not affect

the aid currently being given to Central and Eastern Europe; this should be covered by a different budget.

<p>

In the long term, trade relations will assume greater importance to developing countries than aid relations.

However, the National Advisory Council believes that up to now many of the pleas for 'trade, not aid' have

amounted to empty rhetoric, since they have not been linked to proposals to achieve a greater liberalisation

of trade for developing countries. The Council is of the opinion that the Netherlands should take a stand

within the European Union for a simpler preferential system which will ultimately offer only the least

developed countries completely free access for all trade products (i.e. including textiles, clothing, steel and

agricultural products), gradually excluding the somewhat less poor countries from preferential measures.

The Netherlands must moreover make extra efforts to abolish European export subsidies which lead to the

dumping of agricultural products in developing countries. The agreements made during the Uruguay Round

must be honoured. This does not detract from the fact that the Netherlands should investigate scope for

going further than the dictates or agreements proceeding from 'Brussels'. Since protectionism can always

rear up unexpectedly, it is important to adhere, in the years ahead, to the agreed steps towards liberalisation

and to resist any delay on this point.

<p>

As indicated above, the Netherlands should adhere to the commitment it made in the framework of UNCED

to make 0.1 percent of GNP available for international environmental projects. However, the National

Advisory Council does not share the Ministry of Housing, Spatial Planning and Environment's view that

these resources should mainly be deployed in Central and Eastern Europe and in East Asia. International

demand should take precedence over Dutch supply, here. The Council does, however, see scope for a

financial contribution to be made towards the cost of provision of Dutch expertise, say in the fields of soil

cleanup, water purification and environmental management. World Bank project funding would seem to

provide reasonable guarantees of environmental protection. The Council believes that the Netherlands should

ensure that other financial institutions, too, such as the Asian Development Bank, subject their proposals for

project financing to critical environmental assessment and that they recruit the staff necessary for such

assessment. The Dutch bilateral development aid programme should incorporate target figures for the total

amounts to be spent on environmental activities. It is important, though, to ensure that this sort of aid is not

increasingly made subject to requirements and conditions emanating from the Dutch political agenda.

<p>

Development projects come in many shapes and sizes. There is no simple formula for a successful project.

They often entail intricate intervention in complex social and political systems. A paucity of data makes it

difficult to predict the effects of such interventions (even in the Netherlands, where data are relatively

abundant, it is difficult to predict what the effects of an extra airport runway will be!). Nevertheless,

evaluation of thirty years of experience in development does provide some pointers. The provision of

development aid has worked better in Asia and Latin America than in Africa. And yet in the latter

continent, too, some successes have been achieved. Countries not torn by civil war have seen a sharp drop

in infant mortality rates, a great increase in life expectancy, great improvements in literacy rates and a far

greater number passing through higher education. These achievements are largely due to aid in the form of

vaccination campaigns, food programmes and education. The failures that have occurred have been in the

field of large-scale infrastructural projects, of industries which were technologically inappropriate and too

large in scale. The likelihood of failure increased greatly when the provision of aid became clouded by

economic interests and political motives.

<p>

The National Advisory Council feels that it is important for aid work to be done by professionals. It

recommends that an organisation's quality enhancement methods be viewed as a barometer when recruiting

bodies for aid work. To this end it will be necessary to ascertain whether they make use of independent

evaluation and reflect the results in their policy. Self-evaluation and self-criticism are qualities which are not

invariably possessed by aid agencies. The Council accordingly believes that the extent of the Netherlands'

voluntary contributions to international bodies should depend on the perceived quality of the organisation in

question and its evaluation methods. In the case of obligatory contributions the Netherlands and other

countries will have to insist that quality be adopted as the yardstick for increasing or reducing future

contributions. In theory, a wide range of NGOs qualify for aid, particularly as the Council would like to see

greater importance attached to a balanced programme of social development. It is against this background

that the Council urges a gradual increase in the share of co-financing organisations in the total development

budget. In general, these have proved an efficient aid channel, fulfilling the sustainable poverty alleviation

condition, and have in recent years worked towards quality improvement.

<p>

The Dutch economy is very much an open economy; a good proportion of our prosperity is derived from

international trade. And yet that openness is relative. Compared to other countries, our international contacts

tend to be restricted to ties with rich nations. If the sustainability of the Netherlands' links with developing

countries is to be promoted, the Council feels that new ways must be sought to intensify such relations. We

might approach other donors for advice on aid-initiated relations in the field of trade and investment.

<p>

What is the status of the quality of aid provided and the aid channels used by the Netherlands on a bilateral

basis? Over the years this has become ever more complex in nature, with a sharp increase in the number of

main aims, subordinate aims, and social and political requirements. Improvement of the quality of such aid

would, the Council believes, make both Dutch policy and the organisation of aid more transparent and

straightforward. In the interests of manageability and quality it would seem sensible to concentrate aid on a

smaller number of countries. With regard to Dutch bilateral aid, the Council is thinking in terms of ten

countries in which broad programmes of development aid could be set up, and twenty countries in which

only theme or sector programmes would be financed. The Council once again reiterates its earlier

recommendation to concentrate 80% of traditional aid in the poorest countries (with a per capita GNP of

less than USD 650). Development cooperation is very much a knowledge industry, and loss of quality and

fragmentation are inherent dangers. For this reason it is also recommended that special programmes

(environment, women, research, urban poverty, etc.) are integrated in the proposed country programmes.

The Council would stress here that it is not proposing that specific expertise in the said areas be lost, only

that it should be incorporated more effectively in the country programmes.

<p>

The quality of bilateral aid can also be enhanced through various personnel-related measures (aiming at

professionalisation) and by decentralising powers and staff. Staff recruited for the preparation, approval and

monitoring of aid should have considerable experience in the field of development cooperation. The rotation

of staff should also be restricted, in terms both of the length and location of their postings (e.g. possibly

only within regional clusters). It should also be possible to recruit personnel with both experience of

managing complex organisations and development expertise. If not, it will be necessary to consider setting

up a government agency for aid implementation. In the latter case, one will have to ensure that

implementation does not become too far removed from the Minister for Development Cooperation's political

accountability and control. Before setting up such an agency, it would be advisable to commission, in the

short term, a comparative study of other donor country practices in respect of management and the

implementation of decision-making in the field of development cooperation. Responsibility for identification,

supervision and disbursement of smaller sums should lie with the developing countries, and the Council

accordingly recommends that field offices be set up. The 'ownership' of projects and programmes could also

be better structured. The Council believes this could be achieved within the existing personnel establishment

and budget.

<p>

The new approach outlined above would, in the view of the Council, justify expansion of the Minister for

Development Cooperation's portfolio (perhaps specified under the heading of 'International Cooperation'). In

addition to his present responsibilities in the field of aid and cooperation, the minister would become

responsible for the issues relating to development cooperation, namely international trade*, the global

environment and political concerns (good governance, human rights, democratisation and social

development). In order to cope with this extended mandate, the Minister could make greater use of

professional aid agencies in the implementation of the aid programme.

<p>

* A member of the National Advisory Council has registered a formal objection to the words 'international

trade' in this recommendation.

<p>

<HR>

