<header>

<title>Development Cooperation Advisory Structures in Europe</title>

</header>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<center><h3>Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy in the United Kingdom

</h3></center>

This information is drawn from the report of a survey (1993-1994) carried out by ECDPM on behalf of the

National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation (NAR) of the Netherlands.

<br> 

<h5> Source: Kooij, A. and R. Mevis.

1994. <i>Cooperation of Advisory Structures for Development Cooperation Policy: A Survey in Seventeen

European Countries</i>. The Hague: National Advisory Council for Development Cooperation. The

report is available from: NAR Secretariat, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, P.O. Box 20061, 2500 EB The

Hague, the Netherlands.

</h5>

<hr>

<h3>Contents:</h3>

<ul>

<li><a href="#org">Organisation of British Development Cooperation</a>

<li><a href="#ins">Institutional Framework</a>

<li><a href="#adv">Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</a>

<li><a href="#ngo">Non-State Sources of Advice</a>

<li>Acronyms can be checked by clicking on <a href="../../ecdpm/acro.htm"></a>

</ul><p>



<hr><a name="org"><h3>Organisation of British Development Cooperation</h3>



Official British development cooperation, which started in the early 1960s, was based on the United

Kingdom's (UK) colonial legacy and a strong charitable ethic under the population. Already in the 1940s

and 1950s development approaches (in technical assistance and financial aid) for British overseas territories

evolved (amongst others the 1950 Commonwealth Plan of Colombo). In 1961 a first development

administration was created. Public support has always been strong, based on church and voluntary activities.

Well-known international NGOs, such as the Save the Children Fund and Oxfam respectively started in

1919 after World War I and as a response to the Greek famine in 1942. Opinion polls show that the British

public feels that development cooperation should not be left to voluntary organisations only, and that

government efforts could be enhanced.

<p>

In 1992 UK's net official development assistance amounted to US $ 3 217 million, which was 0.31 per cent

GNP, a fall of 3.5 per cent since 1991. The ODA/GNP ratio reached its peak in 1979 with 0.51 per cent,

and then steadily fell to 0.27 per cent in 1990, due to the UK's negative annual growth rate. Within a

growing budget for external assistance programmes for the period 1994 - 1996, the financial volume for aid

programmes to developing countries will remain unchanged (in current terms). 47 per cent of British ODA

in 1992 was disbursed through multilateral channels, of which 21 per cent through the EU. Multilateral

contributions, in the 1980s amounting to around 40 per cent of all British aid, could approach two-thirds of

the aid budget in the late 1990s, including one-third for the EU budget. After 1996 the budget for the

developing countries will not be separately identified in the overall external assistance budget, as it is

currently. The total external assistance budget includes now: aid to developing countries, aid to Central and

Eastern European Countries (CEECs), the former Soviet Union, and Global Environmental Assistance. 

<p>

<hr><a name="ins"><h3>Institutional Framework</h3></a>

<p>

British aid has its legislative basis in the Overseas Development and Cooperation Act of 1980, which

succeeded the 1966 Overseas Aid Act. All expenditures for development assistance must be authorised by

Parliament in additional legislation. With the establishment of the Department for Technical Cooperation in

1961 all Third World expertise, spread over several Ministries, was concentrated in one organisation. Since

then, many changes and reorganisations of the development administration have been implemented (1964,

1970, 1974, 1979), strongly influenced by the UK's changes of Government.

<p>

Since 1979, aid is administered by the Overseas Development Administration (ODA). A Minister for

Development Cooperation, who holds the position of Foreign and Commonwealth Minister of State, heads

the Overseas Development Administration and is under responsibility of the Foreign Secretary. The ODA is

located within the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO). It manages the three components of the British

external assistance programme: global environmental assistance, overseas aid to developing countries (the

main component), and assistance to Central and Eastern Europe and the Former Soviet Union (managed

jointly with the Diplomatic Wing). The latter two are to merge after 1996. ODA is responsible for

multilateral aid, including contributions to the World Bank group and the EU.  

<p>

ODA is responsible for policy formulation and implementation. Actual implementation is delegated to

various types of institutions. Six Development Divisions play an important role in planning and managing

bilateral aid; these are located in Kenya, Barbados, Malawi, Zambia, Thailand and Pretoria. In addition

there are two Aid Management Offices (in Dhaka and the Pacific Islands). Staff based in Embassies and

High Commissions in Commonwealth countries assist in administering aid programmes. The Natural

Resource Institute (NRI), the scientific arm of British aid, conducts research, consultancies and evaluations.

The NRI is part of the aid administration and is directly responsible to the Minister for Development

Cooperation. The Commonwealth Development Corporation (CDC), a government funded public

corporation, is the main instrument for assisting the private sector in developing countries. Crown Agents

for Overseas Governments and Administration provide procurement and management services to

governments of developing countries, to the UK and other donors. In formulation, implementation and

evaluation of development policy, the Government cooperates with NGOs, research institutes and private

enterprise. 

<p>

Allocations of responsibility, at ministerial as well as on administrative level, between the Aid

Administration on the one hand and the Foreign Policy Departments of the FCO and the Treasury on the

other, traditionally have been subjects of regular discussions. Various mechanisms for internal and external

coordination and consultation have been created, in order to achieve compromises between the above

mentioned organisations. British practice allows ministers to interfere in each other's affairs. The main

interministerial instrument for consultation and coordination of aid policy is the Joint Aid Policy Committee

(JAPC). This Committee includes representatives of ODA, the Diplomatic Wing of the FCO, the Treasury,

the Bank of England, the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI), and the Export Credit Guarantee

Department (ECGD).

<p>

The Aid Policy Department within the Finance Division of the ODA is the central section for policy

planning within the FCO. As in the Aid Policy Department, officials from ODA and the Diplomatic Wing

take counsel in the Aid Policy Board and the Aid Policy Management Group. Policy planning for

development cooperation of the EU is done by the European Community and Food Aid Department in the

International Division of the ODA. In addition the Prime Minister may install Sub-committees.

<p>

Over the years several White Papers (1963, 1975) have been formulated by the Government. In 1975 the

white paper on development cooperation, More Help for the Poorest, was published, on which current

British aid objectives are based. After UNCED, the Strategy for Sustainable Development was published,

with which all development strategies forthwith have to be consistent. Policy objectives are further

elaborated in Sector Policy Papers, in Country Objective Papers and Country Review Papers, commitment

targets, strategy papers for technology development and transfer, and corporate plans. Programmes are

considerably scrutinised and regularly evaluated, amongst others by the independently operating Evaluation

Department of the ODA. Some of these documents are published.

<p>

<hr><a name="adv"><h3>Formal Advisory Structures and Mechanisms</h3></a>

<p>

In the UK there was never felt a need for a formally organised advisory body for development cooperation.

Firstly, over the years a large network of officials and experts developed. Within this network the function

of an advisory body seems to be 

accounted for. Secondly, the Overseas Development Administration has a large number of professional

advisors and sector specialists. Additionally, the Minister and the administration have regular formal

contacts with a wide range of NGOs and academic institutions in the UK. In the United Kingdom a wealth

of knowledge and experience on development cooperation is made available through its many institutes. In

fact, it were renowned economists at British Universities - and in ODA - that since the 1960s elaborated

development theory and strategies.

<p>

The annual external assistance budget is submitted to Parliament and actively discussed as an integral part of

the total government budget. Several Standing Committees, such as the Standing Committee on Foreign

Affairs, the Estimates Committee, and Select Committees scrutinise government proposals. The House of

Lords as well as the House of Commons regularly publish extensive reports and studies on development

cooperation issues.

<p>

In order to be better informed, back-benchers in Parliament have organised themselves separately from the

existing Committee on Foreign Affairs, in an All Party Parliamentarian Group on Overseas Development

(APPGOOD) in 1984. The group has contacts with researchers and other experts and occasionally organises

meetings and seminars.

<p>

<a name="ngo"><HR><h3>Non-State Sources of Advice</h3></a>

<p>

Among the research and development institutes the Overseas Development Institute (ODI) and the Institute

for Development Studies (IDS) are considered as the leading institutes, in particular on 'European issues'.

Publications of this institutes are widely available. The Intermediate Technology Development Group

(ITDG) is one of the leading institutes in development and transfer of technology. According to the 1991

OECD/EADI survey a total of 71 institutes qualifies as Development Research and Training Institutes.

<p>

Following the publication of the National Strategy for Sustainable Development, the Government announced

to set up a three level consultation structure in the UK for the continuation of the UNCED-process: a

Citizens Council, an informal Round Table Group, and an Advisory Panel to the Government, consisting of

eminent members of society.

<p>

The NGO development community in the UK, of which many started as church-based organisations, is one

of the strongest and oldest in Europe. NGOs in Britain actively search the policy dialogue with the

government, and vice versa. Working through NGOs is one of the fastest growing aspects of the British aid

programme. Of the approximately 300 British NGOs 100 receive government support (1992). Four large

NGOs cooperate with the Government in the British Voluntary Service Programme for personnel assistance

overseas. In 1993 an umbrella organisation was created: British Overseas NGOs for Development (BOND),

in which some 80 NGOs are represented. BOND was purposely created to encourage policy discussions,

coordination, to create a two way flow of information between the ODA and the NGOs, and to intensify

government cooperation with NGOs. Other NGO umbrella organisations for lobbying on aid policy issues

are a.o. the Human Rights and Development Forum, the National Association of Womens Organisations and

the Aid and Environment Group.

<p>

Topics of concern of the NGOs in the discussion with the Government are a.o. maintaining the UK's

volume for ODA, commercialisation of aid, the growing volume required for emergency aid, and

availability of operational information on government programmes.

<p>

<hr>

<H6></a>

<i>Updated on April 25, 1996</i><br>

Developer's Note: These pages were developed for use on the Netscape browser. Please address comments

on content or style to <a href="mailto:pb@ecdpm.org">Peter Ballantyne</a>, Information Programme,

ECDPM</H6>

<HR>

</BODY>

